<FIRST>u w AM-WeaponsImports     03-16 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weapons Imports,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post: NRA Blocks Gun Halt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A complaint by the National Rifle Association
stopped the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms from banning the
importation of 25 more models of semiautomatic weapons Thursday, a
newspaper reported.
   The Washington Post, in its Friday editions, said the bureau was
ordered to hold off by Treasury Department officials after the NRA
raised objections.
   The newspaper said senior BATF officials decided at a meeting
Thursday morning to announce the restrictions on the additional
models later in the day, according to an official familiar with the
events. But then they were instructed by the parent Treasury
Department not to proceed, according to the official.
   James Jay Baker, a senior NRA official, said the group learned on
Wednesday night that other weapons might be added to the list of
five types of assault weapons which drug czar William J. Bennett
temporarily banned on Tuesday and contacted Treasury officials who
said there would not be any new restrictions, the newspaper said.
   The ban announced by Bennett included the Chinese-made AK47 and
the Israeli Uzi, and covered about 80 percent of total imports of
semiautomatic weapons.
   ATF then sought to close the door on the semiautomatic weapons
not covered by the initial ban, fearing that these firearms would
fill the void, the Post said. In addition, BATF officials worried
that manufacturers affected by the import ban would complain they
were unfairly singled out.
</TEXT>
