<FIRST>r i PM-China-Suicide     03-16 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Suicide,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suicide Kills 140,000 Chinese A Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 140,000 Chinese take their own lives every
year _ most of them women _ and suicide has become a particularly
serious problem among rural women, a Chinese sociologist says.
   Shan Guangnai of the China Academy of Social Sciences said
suicide is the leading cause of abnormal deaths in China, and 70
percent of all victims are female, the official China Daily reported
today.
   ``It used to be a taboo in China to study suicide. Yet in recent
years we are increasingly haunted by the rising problem,'' the paper
quoted her as saying.
   A survey of 10 million people taken by the China Preventive
Medical Science Institute found the suicide rate for urban women to
be 10.2 per 100,000, and for urban men 7.23 per 100,000.
   In rural areas, the suicide rate was 23.34 for women and 18.6 for
men.
   In the United States, the suicide rate is about 12 per 100,000.
   Shan said half the suicides among women are caused by family
disputes and marital problems. He noted factors such as the breakup
of the traditional extended family and lengthy separations as rural
people stream into cities looking for work.
   Rural women are still treated as dependents and men dominate in
the family, Shan said, adding that the psychological and emotional
needs of women are largely ignored.
   He said women also appear to have more difficulty adapting to
rapid changes in China's social values and moral standards brought
about by industrialization and improving living standards.
   Rural women who migrate to the cities looking for work often find
``the sharp contrast is too much for them,'' Shan said. Those who
return to their villages have difficulty adjusting again to rural
poverty.
   Tens of thousands of Chinese committed suicide as a result of
persecution during the ultra-leftist 1966-76 Cultural Revolution.
The more recent phenomenon of suicide, linked to changing social
conditions, has only recently begun to be a subject for study.
   In January 1988 the southern city of Canton opened the nation's
first suicide prevention and treatment center.
   In the first year it received about 140 phone calls, 600 letters
and dozens of visitors asking for help, the China Daily said.
   Beijing also opened a suicide prevention center last September.
</TEXT>
