<FIRST>r i PM-BerlinDeathPenalty     03-16 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berlin Death Penalty,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allies Abolish 44-Year-Old Death Penalty In West Berlin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three Allied military powers in West Berlin
have abolished a law allowing them to pronounce the death penalty,
erasing a controversial regulation adopted 44 years ago, officials
say.
   No one has ever been executed under the now-defunct law, said a
French military spokesman who requested anonymity. But the continued
existence of the regulation has irritated many West Berliners.
   ``The Allies are conscious of many Berliners' objections'' to the
law, said a statement issued by French military authorities on
Wednesday.
   ``Beginning today ... no person can be sentenced to death because
of violations against the Allies.''
   France, Britain, and the United States officially control West
Berlin under post-war treaties which left the Soviets in charge of
communist East Berlin.
   The French military spokesman said the three Allies were
abolishing the death penalty in West Berlin to ``bring their
regulations into accordance with German law.'' West Germany has no
death penalty.
   The spokesman said the law was aimed at preventing attacks
against Allied soldiers and officials in the years immediately after
Nazi Germany's 1945 defeat.
</TEXT>
