<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearSecurity     03-16 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Security,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins Seeks Tighter Air Security Over Defense Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department is urging aviation
authorities to restrict flights over its military nuclear reactors
to make them more secure against potential terrorist attack.
   ``We've got a lot to do in that area,'' Energy Secretary James D.
Watkins told a House Budget subcommittee Wednesday. ``It's going to
be some time before we get this completely closed.''
   The issue was raised by Sen. Jim Exon, D-Neb., during a hearing
in which Watkins pledged to give top priority to modernizing and
cleaning up the department's nuclear weapons complex, which includes
16 major facilities in 12 states.
   Exon said he was stunned to read a recent report that there are
no effective restrictions on airplane flights over the Savannah
River plant near Aiken, S.C., whose reactors are the nation's only
source of a gas used in nuclear warheads. Those reactors currently
are not operating because of safety problems.
   ``If there is one place where we have fallen down on what is A,
B, C in security, it is in this area,'' Exon said.
   Savannah River also includes an Energy Department research
laboratory, a plant that makes naval reactor fuel material, two
chemical separation plants and a facility that produces weapon-grade
plutonium.
   The only nuclear weapons plant that now has prohibited airspace
is the Pantex plant near Amarillo, Texas, which is the final weapons
assembly point.
   The Charlotte Observer reported in last Sunday's editions that
classified security reports obtained by the newspaper in a Freedom
of Information Act request showed Savannah River officials had
repeatedly urged the Federal Aviation Administration to ban
low-altitude flights over the 300-square-mile facility.
   The FAA said the Energy Department had failed to justify the need
for the restrictions, which the aviation agency views as excessive.
   Watkins said he was personally involved in trying to establish
the air restrictions, not only at Savannah River but also at other
sensitive weapons plants.
   ``We've got to take a look all around,'' he said, to find ways of
better protecting the weapons complex from possible air attacks by
terrorists or damage from a crash.
   ``I believe with the new secretary of transportation and with my
personal friend coming into the FAA, I don't see any problem getting
it reestablished,'' Watkins said.
   Although he was not more specific, Watkins, a retired admiral,
apparently was referring to recent reports that Adm. James D. Busey
IV, commander of naval forces in Europe since March 1987, would be
named FAA administrator.
   The FAA said Wednesday the Bush administration had not yet
nominated anyone for the job.
   The Observer report said that last September, the Energy
Department dropped its 1983 request to prohibit flights below 14,000
feet for Savannah River and eight other weapons sites. The agency
settled for a 2,000-foot minimum limit at Savannah River. That
restriction, however, is voluntary and not enforceable, the report
said.
</TEXT>
