<FIRST>r w PM-Baker-MiddleEast     03-16 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Middle East,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Plays Down Suggestion that Israel and PLO Talk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid Israeli complaints, Secretary of State
James A. Baker III is playing down his suggestion that direct talks
between Israel and the Palestine Liberation Organization may be
needed if alternate peace efforts fail.
   Baker told the Senate Appropriations subcommittee on foreign
operations Wednesday that an Israeli-PLO dialogue was difficult to
foresee but should not ``categorically'' be ruled out.
   This represented a shift in tone from Tuesday when he told a
House subcommittee that if talks between Israel and non-PLO
Palestinians do not prosper, ``I suppose we would then have to see
negotiations between Israelis and representatives of the PLO.''
   Baker's remark triggered a telephone call from Israeli Foreign
Minister Moshe Arens, who told the secretary that the statement was
``damaging'' to the prospects for a dialogue between Israel and
non-PLO Palestinians. Arens, here for official talks, disclosed the
phone call to Israeli reporters.
   At Wednesday's hearing, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said Baker's
statement was an ``open invitation'' for the PLO to engage in
terrorist activities against Palestinians who choose to bargain with
Israel.
   Baker replied that he only meant to say in his earlier remarks
that an Israeli-PLO dialogue should not be ``categorically,
absolutely, totally and completely'' ruled out ``under any and all
circumstances,'' because it might help the peace process.
   The comment did not repudiate what he had said Tuesday but there
was a clear change in emphasis.
   Israel has steadfastly refused to talk to the PLO and says the
dialogue the United States opened with the PLO last December has
strengthened the group's hand.
   Arens accused the PLO on Tuesday of committing the ``worst
atrocities we've ever seen since World War II.''
   In his remarks Wednesday, Baker seemed to hold out little hope
that an international conference on the Middle East, advocated by
many Arab states, could make a significant contribution to peace.
   What is needed instead, Baker said, are ``mutually reciprocal and
reinforcing steps'' by both Israel and the Palestinians to build
confidence.
   ``Both sides have to take steps,'' he said.
   The mood at the hearing was generally friendly but there were
some hints that President Bush may encounter some resistance,
especially on Central American policy.
   Subcommittee Chairman Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., said the only aid
package he could support for the Nicaraguan Contra rebels would be
one leading to their resettlement in Nicaragua or elsewhere from the
base camps where they now are housed in Honduras.
   Baker said he believes the Contras should remain intact at least
until national elections are held in Nicaragua next February. He
implied that the rebels could then be reintegrated into Nicaragua if
the elections are fair.
   The administration is expected to seek a humanitarian aid package
for the Contras in the $40 million to $50 million range in the next
few days.
   On El Salvador, Leahy said that if the rightist ARENA party wins
presidential elections there on Sunday, future U.S. aid to that
country should carry strict conditions because of the ties he said
ARENA has with death squad activities.
   Baker replied that it would be a mistake to exaggerate the size
of the death squad problem, contending that politically motivated
murders averaged 800 per month in 1981 and 1982 compared with 280
per year at present.
   He added, however, that the administration is aware of continuing
human rights problems in El Salvador, recalling that Vice President
Dan Quayle raised that issue with Salvadoran officials during a
visit there six weeks ago.
</TEXT>
