<FIRST>r p PM-PollClosing     03-16 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll Closing,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Uniform Poll Closing Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sponsor of legislation that would establish
a uniform closing time for polls in 48 of the 50 states says he
expects full House approval of the bill as early as next month.
   On Wednesday, the House Administration Committee approved the
measure on a voice vote.
   Rep. Al Swift, sponsor of the bill, said he expects the House to
approve the measure in early April, but House Speaker Jim Wright has
indicated passage could come before the Easter recess which begins
March 24.
   Election officials in the West have charged that the early
projection of the winner in the presidential race discourages people
from voting in their states and the drop in turnout had affected the
outcomes of close local races.
   Swift, D-Wash., has said previously that studies have shown voter
turnout can drop by as much as 2 percent in states where the polls
are still open but the winner in a presidential contest is known.
   ``With passage of this legislation we will be one step closer to
preserving the integrity of election day not only in the West, but
across the country,'' said Swift.
   Swift's bill was similar to ones approved by the House twice
before, but both times the Senate failed to act. A different version
of a uniform poll closing bill is before the Senate Rules Committee.
   Under Swift's bill, polls would close simultaneously across the
country at 9 p.m. EST on election day. In the Pacific time zone,
daylight-saving time would be extended for a maximum of two weeks in
presidential election years. The extension would allow polls in that
time zone to close at 7 p.m. PDT.
   Alaska and Hawaii are exempt from the legislation, but could
change their poll closing times if desired.
   Swift said the need for a uniform closing time became apparent
with the 1980 election when television networks projected the
results based on exit polling hours before the polls on the West
Coast closed.
   The networks have since agreed not to project election results in
a state where the polls haven't closed, but in 1988 the problem was
different as President Bush rolled up a large electoral college
majority before Western polls closed.
   Swift said his uniform poll closing bill ``will ensure that
voters in all regions of the country will be able to cast their
ballots without being told who won the election.
   ``The networks held to their part of the bargain last November,
now it is up to the House and Senate to send this legislation to the
president.''
   While a version of a poll closing bill cleared the Senate Rules
Commitee late last year, Congress adjourned before the the full
Senate had an opportunity to act.
   Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., has introduced legislation that avoids
a change in daylight-saving time and simply calls for the polls to
close at 7 p.m. Pacific time, 8 p.m. Mountain time, 9 p.m. Central
time and 10 p.m. Eastern time.
   Barbara Smith, an Adams spokeswoman, said the chairman of the
rules committee, Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., has indicated he expects
Adams' bill to clear the panel in early April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
