<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0254EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Mauldin-Vets     03-16 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mauldin-Vets,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cartoonist, Guest of Administration, Tweaks New Department, Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As his only non-family, non-official guest on
becoming secretary of veterans affairs, Edward J. Derwinski chose
World War II cartoonist Bill Mauldin, who says the new department
``sounds like the same old bureaucracy under a different name.''
   Mauldin, winner of the Pulitzer Prize, created the bedraggled
dogfaces Willie and Joe for the soldier's newspaper ``Stars and
Stripes.''
   ``Willie and Joe told the truth of the war, World War II, and the
fatigue, sadness, anxiety and humor of the period,'' Derwinski said
in his remarks on the White House South Lawn, with Mauldin close to
him on the podium.
   Mauldin, 67, was a constituent when Derwinski represented the
South Side of Chicago during 12 terms in Congress.
   During an interview before Wednesday's ceremony, Mauldin said he
knew Derwinski only slightly, and did not know whose idea it was to
make him a prominent part of the day's events.
   Mauldin carries a few more pounds and gray hairs than he did in
slogging his way up the Italian peninsula in 1943-1944, where he
collected a minor shoulder wound from a German mortar round that
inspired one of his best panels _ Soldier, standing, to medic,
seated at a table with boxes of medals before him: ``Just gimme the
aspirin. I already got a purple heart.''
   He told two reporters, one from Stars and Stripes, ``I can't help
thinking Derwinski knows my attitude'' as an opponent of the large,
main-line veterans groups and of what he saw as their grasping
attitude.
   ``We were against the special philosophy, if you're a veteran
you're a special case,'' he said. ``Just by virtue of being a
veteran, I don't think that entitles a guy to a gravy-train ride for
the rest of his life.''
   Mauldin belonged to the tiny American Veterans Committee, serving
two terms as chairman, and has not used any veterans benefits.
   ``We backed the GI bill, but our slogan was, `Citizens First,
Veterans Second,''' he said. ``I haven't paid dues for years, but
they still send me mail.
   ``There are millions of guys for whom the military experience was
the one great experience of their lives. I don't blame them for
wanting to sit around on a Saturday night with their friends and
tell lies about their experience.''
   Mauldin said he had not paid close attention to veterans affairs
recently, so his opinions had to be tentative.
   _Agent Orange: Veterans are being forced to try to prove
illnesses are connected to exposure to that defoliant, but ``the
burden of proof ought to be on the government. Those kids ought to
have it made up to them. I'm very much in favor of a liberal hand''
in compensation.
   _A Cabinet department replacing the old Veterans Administration:
``It sounds like the same bureaucracy under a different name. ...
maybe it will be entirely different.''
   He was not at all tentative on universal service.
   ``I think it's great, the idea of putting two or three years of a
young man's (or woman's) life into public service,'' he said.
   ``If you're not inclined to the military, then CCC-type work.''
   The CCC was the Civilian Conservation Corps, a depression-era
agency tha provided jobs, clothes and food for young men in camps
working on conservation projects.
   ``I think everyone owes his country a few years out of his life,
just a short period, two years, maybe three.''
   The point of this, he said, is to ``make better citizens out of
them .. bond them to their country.''
   Though many proponents of universal service have said the ending
of the draft in 1973 ended valuable lessons in democracy through the
military's mixing of classes, races and viewpoints, Mauldin said he
thought ``the sociology is obviously a side benefit.''
   Mauldin himself enlisted in the New Mexico National Guard in
1940, more than a year before the entry of the United States into
World War II, because, ``I had some friends in the unit I wanted to
be with. ... I wanted to get into something, not out of something.''
   Which started his cartoonist juices flowing: ``I don't want to
pick on Danny Boy,'' he said with a grin, recalling cartoons of last
fall's campaign lambasting the Vietam-era plunge into the Indiana
National Guard of Vice President Dan Quayle.
</TEXT>
