<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchProtest     03-16 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Protest,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troubled Church Reopens Without Incident; Priest Suspended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic church where
parishioners rebelled over the removal of a Polish priest has
reopened, but church authorities revealed that the priest has been
suspended by his superiors.
   Police have guarded St. Michael the Archangel church since it was
closed Feb. 18 by Bishop Edward Egan after a weeklong sit-in by
about 200 dissidents upset over the sudden, unexplained ouster of
the Rev. Roman Palaszewski.
   There were relatively few worshipers Wednesday at four early
morning Masses, two celebrated in English and two in Polish, said
the Rev. James Smyka, associate pastor.
   ``It was very, very emotional,'' Smyka said. ``The 6:30 Mass _ I
think I cried through half of it. It was just so good to be back in
the church. I mean, that's what our business is as priests.''
   Some parishioners said they were overjoyed by the church's
reopening. Some said they heard about it by word-of-mouth, or by
making daily drives by the church since the announcement that it
would reopen.
   Monsignor Nicholas Grieco, a spokesman for Egan, said Wednesday
that Palaszewski was suspended indefinitely for defying orders from
his Franciscan superiors in Krakow, Poland, to return to Poland last
month.
   ``He's still ordained, but he cannot function as a priest because
he didn't obey his superior who commanded him, under obedience, to
return to Poland,'' Grieco said ``He would not be able to say Mass
or administer the sacraments.''
   Palaszewski, who spent three years at the church under an
agreement between his superiors in Poland and Franciscan officials
in Baltimore, has been in seclusion in the Bridgeport area since his
removal in December.
   About 50 worshipers attended a Lenten prayer service Wednesday
evening. They entered the church under the watchful eye of a police
officer sitting in a van parked discreetly across the street.
   Four or five dissidents watched quietly from across the street
Wednesday evening as worshipers entered the church.
   They then gathered at a Polish club a block from the church to
plan a demonstration outside the church this weekend on Palm Sunday,
the start of the holiest week in the church year.
   ``They didn't heal our wounds _ everything is the same,'' said
Genevieve Kozlowski, a parishioner for 25 years and one of the
protest leaders.
   She was unaware of Wednesday's opening, but said she and many
other protesters plan to boycott services because they don't believe
their complaints have been addressed, Kozlowski said.
   The dissidents are demanding Palaszewski's return to the parish
and the removal of the church's pastor, the Rev. John Bambol, who
they claim engineered Palaszewski's removal because of his
popularity among recent immigrants.
   They also question Bambol's commitment to maintaining the
church's Polis traditions.
   Bambol's supporters have said Palaszewski paid scant attention to
parishioners who were not recent immigrants.
   A weeklong sit-in by about 200 dissidents who occupied the church
in shifts ended early Feb. 18 when church authorities summoned
police to expel them. Two who refused to leave voluntarily were
charged with trespassing.
   Egan suspended Masses indefinitely the same day.
   Bambol said after the prayer service that the dissidents are
welcome to return as long as they ``abide by the rules of the
church.'' He said he was ``very joyful, very happy'' that the church
had reopened.
   ``After all we were all suffering for so long unjustifiably ...
we are happy to be back in harness, so to speak,'' he said. ``This
is a period of reconciliation.''
</TEXT>
