<FIRST>r a PM-Shuttle-Edwards     03-16 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Edwards,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>200,000 Expected To Watch Discovery Land On Mojave Desert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200,000 spectators
will converge on this Mojave Desert military base to watch Discovery
land early Saturday, NASA predicted.
   National Aeronautics and Space Administration spokeswoman Nancy
Lovato said Wednesday that the crowd would be that big ``because
it's a weekend landing at the beginning of spring vacation.''
   The space shuttle and its five-man crew is scheduled to touch
down at 6:34 a.m., capping a five-day mission highlighted by
deployment of a $100 million communications satellite and
experiments aimed at developing new medicines and learning how bones
heal and chicken embryos develop in the weightlessness of space.
   Trouble with a valve on board Discovery had threatened to end the
mission a day early, but it was apparently fixed Wednesday and NASA
is aiming for a Saturday landing.
   NASA officials said Wednesday that because of a desire to perform
handling and braking tests, Discovery might land on concrete Runway
22 instead of on its normal landing strip, Runway 17, which is on
the unpaved, clay surface of Rogers Dry Lake.
   Runway 17 is roughly three miles from the public viewing site on
the lakebed's east shore. Runway 22 is about 4.5 miles, but ``it's
still a good view. You'll see `em fly right past,'' Lovato said.
   Meanwhile, five airmen playing the role of injured astronauts
were rescued Wednesday from a make-believe space shuttle fire in an
emergency drill by ground crews who will greet Discovery when it
returns Saturday. NASA routinely holds such simulations before real
shuttle landings.
   The east shore viewing site will be open to the public 24 hours
before the landing, and vehicle passes are not required. But gates
to the main parts of Edwards Air Force Base will be closed to anyone
not on official business.
   Access to the viewing site will be closed one hour before the
landing, Lovato said.
   Lovato said the two largest crowds for shuttle landings numbered
500,000, when Columbia landed here on July 4, 1982; and 410,000 on
Oct. 3 when Discovery glided to the desert floor to complete the
first shuttle flight since Challenger blew up after liftoff on Jan.
28, 1986.
</TEXT>
