<FIRST>r w PM-Housing-Homeless     03-16 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing-Homeless,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Housing Board Called Do-Nothing Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and congressional housing experts say a
federal panel charged with coordinating programs for the homeless
has done little or nothing to address the problem.
   Witnesses at a congressional hearing Wednesday lambasted the
Interagency Council on the Homeless, saying it has not met its
legislative mandate.
   The criticism came at a joint hearing of two House panels as the
Senate subcommittee on housing introduced legislation touted by
sponsors as ``the framework for a new national housing strategy.''
   The litany of the council's failures began in the opening
statement from Rep. Cardiss Collins, D-Ill., who chairs the
Government Activities and Transportation subcommittee.
   Collins said the council ``has failed almost completely to carry
out the mandates set for it by Congress,'' she said.
   The council was established in 1987 by Title II of the McKinney
Act to coordinate 20 new programs created by the act. It is supposed
to provide information on the programs and help state and local
governments and non-profit organizations implement them.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of the Employment and Housing
subcommittee, said much of the information that homeless providers
needed to apply for McKinney money was provided instead by the
National Governors Association.
   Wendy Adler of the NGA testified that after receiving numerous
questions from states, she developed a report on the status of
programs under the McKinney Act and related legislation. She said
the report has now been updated three times.
   ``This publication contains the type of information the council
should be disseminating,'' said Adler.
   Other witnesses said the council, in a year and a half since
enactment of McKinney, failed to hire a complete staff or identify
regional and field coordinators for programs. It focused too much on
the development of an electronic data base which housing providers
could not use, often sent information regarding application
deadlines late, met just five times and produced only three monthly
newsletters which contained useless information, the witnesses said.
   Cassandra Moore, the council's former executive director, blamed
a lack of resources. ``The duties with which the council is charged
and its ability to carry them out must be brought into balance,''
she said.
   Moore said Congress gave the council broad authority to develop
programs and issue timetables but not the power or resources to do
the job.
   She recommended increasing the staff size and removing the
council from the administrative wing of the Department of Housing
and Urban Development, which she said has been unwilling to share
information.
   The council, composed of the heads or their designees of 10
Cabinet departments and five independent agencies, was headed under
the Reagan administration by then-housing secretary Samuel Pierce.
The Bush administration has yet to choose his successor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
