<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-16 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Closes Up, Share Prices Off In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished higher Thursday against the
Japanese yen, while share prices erased earlier gains and lost
ground on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 130.73 yen, up 0.85 yen from Wednesday's
close of 129.88 yen. The currency opened at 130.68 yen and moved in
a range of 130.60-130.95 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
376.13 points the previous day, erased its gains earlier in the day
and lost 2.24 points, or 0.007 percent, to finish at 32,098.24.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's rise to a report
Wednesday by the U.S. Commerce Department that the nation's trade
deficit fell to $9.49 billion in January from a revised December
shortfall of $10.99 billion.
   After opening higher in Tokyo, following similar trends on
overseas markets overnight, the market's dollar-buying interest
remaind strong, said a dealer with a commercial bank in Tokyo,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Trading companies and foreign banks bought the currency, boosting
the dollar's rise, he said.
   The dollar is unlikely to continue to rise although a majority of
market players were in a dollar-buying mood, another dealer said
anonymously.
   Dealers said share prices fell due to profit taking in a
directionless trading Thursday.
</TEXT>
