<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Airwaves     03-16 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Airwaves,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fears Of Violence Kept Campaign On Airwaves, Off Streets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Images of violence, catchy music
and casual character assassination were among the dominant features
of an election campaign that tried to stick to the airwaves and stay
off of the streets.
   For one thing, radio and television advertisements were much
safer than public appearances in this country, where expressing your
political preference can be lethal.
   The campaign ended Wednesday with a burst of such advertistments
and a rally by the leftist Democratic Convergence. No campaigning is
permitted from today until Sunday's presidential balloting.
   The political parties knew that more than 85 percent of
Salvadorans homes have radios, the most pervasive medium in a
country where personal messages from one town to another are relayed
between songs on music stations.
   There are 51 AM stations in the country of 5.5 million people _ 3
million radio receivers and 4.5 million daily listeners.
   Now Salvadorans are being asked to go to the polls to pick a
president under the threat of violence by the leftist guerrillas of
the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, whose nine-year war
against the U.S.-supported government has claimed 70,000 lives.
   The rebels, as in previous elections, have threatened violence
and urged voters to stay home on election day.
   In 1984, nearly 75 percent of the voters cast ballots. They chose
Christian Democrat Jose Napoleon Duarte as president and gave a
strong second place to a surging right-wing party _ the Republican
Nationalist Alliance _ that now threatens to wrest power from the
Christian Democrats.
   Political parties avoided big rallies both in the capital and in
the countryside during this year's four-month campaign. A Republican
Nationalist Alliance rally on Saturday was the largest of the
campaign, drawing more than 20,000 people in the capital.
   Most election work was carried out by party volunteers working
city blocks and at so-called ``carnivals,'' where party leaders
mingled with the people while local bands played and liquor flowed.
   Several people were killed in the early days of the campaign. The
leftist guerrillas threatened city mayors, then killed nine of them,
and leaders of the two dominant parties accused each other of
political slayings.
   As a result, all the parties took the lion's share of their
campaigns to the airwaves.
   Several sectors of society, principally the Roman Catholic
church, harshly criticized the mudslinging that marked the ads.
   The Christian Democrats ran a television ad that showed a
blood-covered man's body on the floor, followed by an image of a
similarily butchered woman.
   ``This is the kind of violence Arena brought to the country,''
says a guttural voice over a horror movie soundtrack, playing on
accusations that Republican Nationalist Alliance, known as Arena, is
linked to right-wing death squads who killed thousands of reputed
leftists in the early 1980s.
   Arena ran radio ads alleging that Christian Democrat candidate
Fidel Chavez Mena embezzled or squandered millions of dollars, some
of it destined for victims of the 1986 earthquake.
   Both parties denied each other's accusations.
   The leftist Democratic Convergence ran television ads showing
soldiers firing on crowds while a voice sang, ``Let me not be
indifferent to pain.''
   The three parties flooded the airwaves on Wednesday, but the
well-funded rightist party had by far the most broadcast time.
   ``Of course, not only do we benefit from the propaganda, but we
block others,'' said an Arena campaign organizer, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   But the airwaves aren't reserved for the parties.
   The rebels spoke to voters with their clandestine Radio
Venceremos, taking credit for an attack on the presidential palace
and threatening election workers in an effort to enforce their
election boycott.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
