<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0648EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Cop-KillerParole     03-16 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cop-Killer Parole,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parole Officials: McGivern May Be Released Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted cop-killer granted clemency in
1985 may go free as early as Friday, said state parole officials who
voted to release him.
   A three-member panel of the state Board of Parole voted
unanimously Wednesday to release Gary McGivern, who some saw as an
unrepentant murderer.
   But McGivern also had some well-known supporters, including folk
singer Pete Seeger, conservative columnist William F. Buckley and
civil rights lawyer William Kunstler.
   ``It's been a long haul. I've been in this for 13{ years,'' said
Kunstler. ``I'm happy for Gary, his wife and his family.''
   Michael Kavanagh, the prosecutor who won the 25 years to life
sentences handed McGivern, 44, and co-defendant Charles Culhane,
said the parole board's decision was ``a sad commentary on our
criminal justive system.''
   Gov. Mario Cuomo's grant of clemency for McGivern on New Year's
Eve 1985 was denounced by many New York law enforcement officials
and by then Vice President George Bush. At the time, Cuomo was
considered a potential 1988 presidential contender.
   Although Cuomo's clemency made McGivern immediately eligible for
parole consideration, the state board twice refused to free him
before Wednesday's hearing at Otisville state prison where McGivern
was being held.
   The board's executive director, Edward Elwin, said McGivern could
be freed as early as Friday.
   Through three trials, McGivern and Culhane steadfastly maintained
their innocence in the 1968 shooting death of William Fitzgerald, a
Westchester County deputy, during an escape attempt.
   Maurice Fitzgerald, the 86-year-old brother of the slain deputy,
said McGivern should have been kept in prison for life.
   ``But what are you going to do?'' he said after the parole board
decision. ``There's nothing I can do about it.''
   McGivern wasn't granting interviews Wednesday, but Culhane said
his friend's parole was ``wonderful.''
   Culhane said he felt the parole board's decision might help his
bid for early release. Thus far, Cuomo has refused to grant Culhane
clemency and he's not eligible for a parole hearing until late 1991.
That's when McGivern would have been first eligible for parole
without Cuomo's clemency.
   In the past, the board had cited the serious nature of the crime
in keeping McGivern behind bars. On Wednesday, the board noted
McGivern's ``outstanding record'' while in prison.
   Leading the effort to win McGivern's freedom has been free-lance
writer Marguerite Culp, a former newspaper reporter who met McGivern
while he was in prison and married him on the 10th anniversary of
the shooting.
   Elwin said McGivern and his wife planned to live at her home in
Woodstock.
   That's not far from where McGivern, Culhane and inmate Robert
Bowerman, according to prosecutor Kavanagh, tried to escape while
being transported from state prison to a court appearance. At the
time, McGivern and Culhane were serving state prison sentences for
the armed robbery of a gas station. Bowerman, a jailhouse lawyer,
was helping them appeal their convictions.
   Fitzgerald and Bowerman were fatally shot and McGivern and
Culhane were wounded. Kavanagh said it was McGivern who fired the
shot that killed Fitzgerald.
   Even though McGivern and Culhane have maintained Bowerman acted
alone, a second deputy in the car, Joseph Singer, said they were
involved. Singer has since committed suicide.
</TEXT>
