<SECOND>PM-Mrs Letterman,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Who Broke Into Letterman Home Ordered To Undergo More Exams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman charged with breaking into the home
of talk show host David Letterman shrieked in court she has ``had
enough,'' and a judge ordered her to undergo further psychiatric
exams.
   Norwalk Superior Court Judge John J.P. Ryan on Wednesday ordered
a three-member panel to examine Margaret Ray to determine whether
the 36-year-old woman understands the charges against her.
   Ray's attorney, Anita Y. Cason, requested the additional tests
after a report by Dr. James Alexander found that Ray was competent
to stand trial. The psychiatrist examined the woman last week.
   Ray, who faces charges of criminal trespassing, burglary,
possession of marijuana and larceny, yelled out to reporters as she
entered the courthouse and spoke out in court, although warned not
to by the judge.
   Ray shrieked: ``I'm ready to talk. I've had enough. I've seen
enough.''
   Under Ryan's order, a panel made up of a psychiatrist, a
psychologist and a social worker from the state psychiatric hospital
in Newtown will examine Ray at the Niantic state prison for women.
   Ray has been held at the prison in lieu of $5,000 bail since her
arrest for breaking into Letterman's home in New Canaan on Feb. 28,
the second time in five days she was found inside Letterman's
unoccupied house. She was allegedly wearing one of Letterman's
watches and told authorities she was there cleaning.
   Ray also was arrested twice last spring for breaking into his
home in the exclusive community about 40 miles north of New York
City.
   Prosecutor Robert Hall told the judge Wednesday that ``Mr.
Letterman is most concerned'' about the break-ins.
   An attorney representing Letterman, host of NBC's ``Late Night
with David Letterman,'' attended the court proceeding, but didn't
speak.
   Ray is due back in court March 28, when the judge is expected to
determine whether she is competent to stand trial.
