<FIRST>r a PM-CruseTrial     03-16 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cruse Trial,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Say Gunman Methodical During Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Witnesses recounted brushes with death and
identified a 61-year-old retired librarian as the gunman who killed
six people and wounded 10 in a 1987 shooting rampage.
   During an emotional third day of testimony in Circuit Court
Wednesday, eight witnesses said William Bryan Cruse was purposeful,
precise and without emotion during the shootout at two Florida
supermarkets in Palm Bay on Florida's eastern coast.
   ``It wasn't a zombie-type look,'' said Robert Jones, who helped
usher people to safety during the April 23, 1987 attack and came
within about 15 feet of the gunman at one point. ``It (was) more or
less like somebody who had a job to do.''
   Cruse is charged with six counts of first-degree murder, 28
counts of attempted murder and two counts of kidnapping.
   Lawyers for Cruse, who could face the death penalty, do not deny
he was responsible. But they say he was temporarily insane at the
time. The trial was moved inland to this central Florida town
because of heavy local news coverage.
   To deflate the insanity claims, prosecutors asked each witness in
detail how Cruse acted during the shooting, hoping to prove his
actions were deliberate.
   Publix store manager John Brubaker, employee Babetta Peterson and
shopper Douglas Pollock all said the gunman appeared to be in
control as he methodically took aim with his semiautomatic rifle at
human targets.
   Mrs. Peterson and her daughter arrived at the store as Cruse sped
into the parking lot and got out of his car with what appeared to be
a rifle, she testified.
   Then she saw the gunman shoot two young men who were coming out
of the store. As the men crumpled to the ground, the gunman
approached them and shot again, Mrs. Peterson said.
   ``He was holding it up like so and pointing it downward to where
they were, she said, crying on the witness stand as she described
how the gun was handled.
   Pollock said he saw two men lying motionless on the ground, and a
third man running away yelling in a foreign accent: ``Oh, God. Oh,
God.''
   The three men were Kuwaiti students. Two died, and the third was
seriously wounded.
</TEXT>
