<FIRST>r a PM-TiltedArc     03-16 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tilted Arc,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artist: Feds Broke Covenant of the Arc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Work crews gathered to dismantle ``Tilted Arc''
just hours after the creator of the steel sculpture ended a
last-ditch effort to keep it at a federal office plaza.
   Richard Serra, who has maintained that merely moving the 73-ton
work from the site would destroy its artistic integrity, said
Wednesday that the removal is ``a very thoughtless and barbaric
act.''
   ``This country pays lip service to (Salman) Rushdie, and turns
around and destroys my piece,'' said Serra, referring to the British
author who had a price put on his head in Iran because of his book
``The Satanic Verses,'' which many Moslem leaders labeled
blasphemous.
   Hours earlier, Serra's lawyer, Jay Topkis, announced: ``We're
dropping all of our efforts to do anything about their destroying
Tilted Arc.''
   Serra has been battling in and out of court for the last four
years to prevent the government from removing the sculpture from
Federal Plaza in lower Manhattan where it was unveiled in 1981.
   Workmen were ready to dismantle and remove the 120-foot-long,
12-foot high, wall of curving, rusty steel over the weekend until
the government agreed to wait, pending further legal maneuvering by
Topkis.
   Topkis previously sought a delay, to which federal lawyers
consented, to research whether the work was protected under the
``moral rights'' clause of a 19th-century international copyright
treaty.
   But he said he concluded that the treaty from the Berne
Convention, which the United States joined two weeks ago, does not
bar the government ``from destroying this work of one of our
country's most distinguished artists.''
   Previously, Serra lost a $30 million damage suit against the U.S.
General Services Administration, which commissioned the work for
$175,000 in 1979.
   GSA decided to remove the work after numerous complaints that it
was an eyesore that bisected the plaza, preventing its use for large
public gatherings, said William J. Diamond, regional administrator
of the agency.
   ``This is an important victory for the people of lower Manhattan,
who will now be able to regain the use of the plaza, which has been
denied to them for seven years by `Tilted Arc,''' said Diamond.
   Diamond said the work would be stored under guard at a government
parking lot in Brooklyn. GSA plans an outdoor cafe, trees and other
greenery for Federal Plaza, he said.
   No permanent relocation site for the sculpture has been picked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
