<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--LaunchPostponed     03-16 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Launch Postponed,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>Satellite Launch Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers today were troubleshooting
two rocket problems that forced postponement of the launch of a
satellite designed to test sensors for the ``Star Wars'' missile
defense system.
   The Air Force scrubbed the effort Wednesday night just 2 minutes
56 seconds before the planned liftoff because of a bad sensor
reading and a buildup of gaseous helium in a vibration-suppression
system on the Delta rocket.
   ``The launch team is currently evaluating the turnaround,'' said
Lt. Col. Ron Rand, an Air Force spokesman. ``We don't know whether
it will be 24 hours or longer.''
   The satellite sensors are designed to help develop the technology
for spotting and tracking hostile missiles launched at the United
States. It is a project for the Strategic Defense Initiative,
commonly known as Star Wars.
