<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0735EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchBugging     03-16 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Bugging,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawsuit Over Sanctuary Bugging May Be Revived</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Churches won a court victory over the
government's electronic war against the Sanctuary movement, but four
Arizona churches must meet another test to keep their lawsuit alive,
a federal appeals court ruled.
   In a dispute that grew out of the federal government's use of
electronic surveillance to track the Sanctuary movement, the court
ruled unanimously Wednesday that churches have the right to sue over
the issue.
   ``Of course, we're delighted,'' said Susan Parrott, a member of
the Southside Presbyterian Church in Tucson, Ariz. ``We've always
felt that the infiltrators in our church were a disgrace.''
   But in order to keep their lawsuit alive, the churches must prove
that the surveillance is continuing or likely to resume, according
to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruling. A federal judge in
Phoenix must weigh the evidence, the court said.
   Peter Baird, a lawyer for the churches, called the 3-0 ruling ``a
great stride forward toward protecting worship services from
electronic surveillance.''
   Justice Department spokeswoman Amy Brown declined to comment.
Patrick Kane, Phoenix district director of the federal Immigration
and Naturalization Service, said he had not seen the ruling and
could not comment.
   The court did not say whether government infiltration and secret
recording of church services, without a search warrant, would
violate freedom of religion or the constitutional ban on
unreasonable searches.
   That is a key issue in the pending appeal of eight Sanctuary
movement workers, including five members of the clergy, convicted in
Tucson in 1986 of a variety of immigration charges, including
illegally harboring and transporting Central American refugees.
   It was disclosed in that case that paid government informants had
secretly recorded worship services and Bible classes. A federal
prosecutor said the surveillance was proper because the church was
the site of a criminal conspiracy.
   The criminal appeal was argued before another panel of the 9th
Circuit last December and has not yet been decided.
   The civil suit that led to Wednesday's ruling was filed by
churches in Phoenix and Tucson. They said informants working for the
Immigration and Naturalization Service attended and secretly
recorded their services between March 1984 and January 1985.
   Once the surveillance was disclosed, church officials said, their
attendance declined, a Bible study group was canceled, and members
became more reluctant to seek pastoral counseling and less open in
their prayers and confessions.
   The suit sought a ruling that the surveillance was improper and a
court order banning it in the future.
   U.S. District Judge Charles Hardy dismissed the suit without a
trial, saying that even if all the allegations were true, the
churches as organizations had not been harmed. But the appeals court
disagreed.
   ``When congregants are chilled from participating in worship
activities, when they refuse to attend worship services because they
fear the government is spying on them and taping their every
utterance ... we think a church suffers organizational injury
because its ability to carry out its ministries has been impaired,''
said the opinion by Judge William Norris.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890316-0047 </DOCNO>
