<FIRST>r a PM-HarborCleanup     03-16 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harbor Cleanup,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Calls on Bush to Free Funds for Boston Harbor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is being asked to back up his
presidential campaign rhetoric blasting Gov. Michael S. Dukakis for
failing to clean up Boston Harbor.
   Dukakis, for whom the polluted harbor became a political
liability, asked the Bush administration Wednesday to put ``its
money where its mouth was.''
   ``When you make the kind of statements that were made in the
campaign, you've got an obligation to make good on them,'' Dukakis
said.
   The governor faulted Bush for proposing cutbacks in federal
wastewater construction programs that would cost Massachusetts $40
million. In addition, he charged that while Congress has earmarked
$59 million for the Boston Harbor project, the Bush administration
has not included those funds in its budget.
   Dukakis said he was confident the Massachusetts congressional
delegation would reverse those decisions.
   Bush, as the Republican candidate for president, staged a
surprise cruise in September on Boston Harbor to criticize Dukakis
for pollution.
   Dukakis supporters argued that the governor was primarily
responsible for the legislation designed to end the pollution by the
next century.
   But the charges, reinforced by a Republican campaign TV
commercial, stuck to Dukakis, leaving the Democrat on the defensive.
   ``I'm proud to say that as of today, we're right on schedule _
and that's the way we're going to keep it,'' Dukakis told reporters
Wednesday, flanked by Environmental Affairs Secretary John DeVillars
and Massachusetts Water Resources Authority Executive Director Paul
Levy.
   The governor ticked off a series of steps already taken to
address the harbor pollution, beginning with the creation of the
water resources authority.
   Noting that the agency has already spent $350 million of the
projected $6.5 billion cost, Dukakis said the state water authority
has stopped the discharge of ``floating scum'' from its aging
treatment plants at Nut Island and Deer Island.
   Dukakis promised that families will notice cleaner beaches this
summer in the metropolitan area.
</TEXT>
