<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     03-16 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Free Market Premier, Government Sworn In In Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ante Markovic was installed today as
premier and promised a series of democratic-oriented economic and
political initiatives to roust this Communist country from a
nine-year economic slide.
   Markovic said in his inaugural speech that a free-market economy
is the ``ultimate achievement of mankind _ for which no alternative
has yet been found.'' A new Cabinet was also sworn in.
   ``There is no solution to the economic crisis without the
strengthening of political democracy in the country,'' he said,
urging the creation of ``a new modern socialist system.''
   The new premier said this Balkan country of 23 million people has
to undergo ``a fundamental change'' in order to revive the economy.
Yugoslavia is burdened by 346 percent annual inflation and a $21
billion foreign debt.
   Markovic indicated he would seek closer links the West, including
greater economic cooperation with the European Economic Community.
   He advocates reshaping the country's banking system along Western
lines, creating a stock market and ending state subsidies to
money-losing companies.
   Yugoslavia, which split from the Soviet bloc in 1948, is a
founding member of the non-aligned movement, and both superpowers
vie for its good graces.
   Markovic, a successful businessman, called for an immediate
introduction of shares and bonds, private initiative and
entrepreneurship and an end to state interference in the operation
of businesses.
   Markovic, a former president of the Croatian republic, succeeds
Branko Mikulic, who, together with his entire Cabinet, resigned Dec.
30.
   Mikulic's government was the first to resign since the Communist
Party took power after World War II. He stepped down following his
government's failure to solve the country's daunting social and
economic problems, including a dramatic rise in social and ethnic
unrest.
   Economic problems have been accompanied by a resurgence of
historic ethnic rivalries a this loose federation of six republics
and two autonomous provinces.
   Much of the recent unrest has centered on the southern province
of Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians form a majority of 90 percent.
   Markovic's 19-member Cabinet, the smallest in postwar history, is
a mix of prominent politicians and technocrats, with only two
ministers retaining the seats they occupied in Mikulic's government.
   Foreign Minister Budimir Loncar and Defense Minister Gen. Veljko
Kadijevic remained in the new administration, while Dobrosav
Culafic, Interior Minister in Mikulic's government, lost his job.
   Culafic was replaced following severe public criticism of his
handling of tensions in Kosovo, where emergency measures were
imposed last month in order to prevent clashes between ethnic
Albanians and Slavs living there.
   The important Interior Ministry went to Gen. Petar Gracanin,
president of the largest republic of Serbia, of which Kosovo is an
administrative part.
   Markovic named as vice premiers Aleksandar Mitrovic, Serbia's
vice president, and Zivko Pregl, executive secretary of the Slovene
Communist party.
   The choice of vice premiers indicates Markovic took a balanced
stand between Slovenia, which advocates a market economy and more
political pluralism, and Serbia, which strives for more centralism
and political orthodoxy.
   In his choice of Cabinet members, Markovic has for the first time
abandoned the principle of absolute parity among the republics and
autonomous provinces _ which, strictly adhered to in the past,
provided for equal Cabinet representation of all regions.
   Yugoslavia is run by a state presidency, a collective nine-man
body whose chairmanship rotates annually. It is the supreme
commander of the armed forces and executes foreign policy.
   The government is responsible for executing economic policy,
while the Communist Party Presidium, or Politburo, has 23 members to
oversee state activities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
