<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial     03-16 0116</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial,0118</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Of Two Dissidents Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two dissidents imprisoned since
October for inciting anti-government demonstrations went on trial
today, the latest in a series of crackdowns on leading activists.
   Hana Marvanova and Tomas Dvorak, both members of the Independent
Peace Association, were arrested just prior to an Oct. 28 march
marking the 70th anniversary of Czechoslovak independence.
   The two also are accused of inciting a mass demonstration on Aug.
21 in Prague's Wenceslas Square.
   The charges against the two have been changed several times
during their pretrial detention. But the London-based emigre
publishing house Palach Press said they face incitement charges that
could jail them for up to five years.
</TEXT>
