<FIRST>r a PM-Vincennes-Bomb     03-16 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vincennes-Bomb,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caller Claims Responsibility For Van Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI says it is checking into claims by a
radio station caller that a group called Guardians of the Islamic
Revolution planted the bomb that destroyed a van driven by the wife
of the USS Vincennes skipper.
   Meanwhile, trustees at the private school where the skipper's
wife teaches scheduled an emergency meeting today in response to
parents' concern about student safety if Sharon Rogers returns to
her fourth-grade classroom.
   The caller, who spoke with a Middle Eastern accent and claimed to
be a member of the group, linked Friday's car bombing to last July's
downing of an Iranian jetliner by a missile fired from the
Vincennes, the radio station said.
   All 290 people aboard of the jet were killed when Capt. Will C.
Rogers III gave the order to fire in the belief the aircraft was an
attacking warplane.
   The caller to Los Angeles radio station KNX on Wednesday also
threatened additional attacks against Rogers' wife and ``all the
American officers and officials,'' said Roger Nadel, the station's
executive news producer.
   ``We're looking into (the claim),'' said Fred Reagan, an FBI
spokesman in Los Angeles. He declined to elaborate.
   Terrorist expert David Hoffman of the Rand Corp. said he doubts
the validity of the call because it came five days after the bombing
and wasn't phoned to a news wire service like most legitimate claims
for such acts.
   Guardians of the Islamic Revolution has told international news
organizations it was responsible for the Dec. 21 bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, that killed 270 people.
   The Islamic group also has claimed credit for a July 1987 car
bombing in England that killed a former minister in the government
of Iran's deposed Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, and the October 1987
slayings of two opponents of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's regime.
   Mrs. Rogers escaped uninjured in Friday's bombing of the family
van. The FBI said the bomb was a non-military device, possibly a
pipe bomb.
   FBI spokesman Ron Orrantia has said no possible motives for the
attack on the van have been ruled out, including retribution for the
airliner downing.
   Mrs. Rogers' future at La Jolla Country Day School may be
discussed at today's board of trustees meeting, which was called
after the school received a bomb threat Tuesday, board member
Houshmand Aftahi said.
   Police found no explosives, but the incident apparently caused
concern among parents that such threats will continue if Mrs. Rogers
returns to the school, where students will be off the next two weeks
for spring break.
   ``I hear that some parents are concerned and they want to know
what the school is going to do about it,'' Aftahi said.
   ``We're all concerned about the security of our children, and we
feel that her presence on the campus, at this point, is not good,''
an unidentified parent told the Los Angeles Times. ``I think parents
would prefer that she stay away for the rest of the school year.''
</TEXT>
