<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Namibia     03-16 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Namibia,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa Questions Impartiality Of U.N. In Namibia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa said today that
U.N. fundraising efforts to benefit the SWAPO guerrilla movement
have raised doubts about the U.N.'s impartiality in monitoring the
Namibian independence process.
   The United Nations has been soliciting funds for the
International Day for the Elimination of Racial Discrimination, set
for March 21, said Neil van Heerden, South Africa's director general
of foreign affairs.
   He said some of the money raised will go into four funds that are
spent for the benefit of the South-West African People's
Organization. The U.N. spent about $30 million on SWAPO from these
funds last year, van Heerden said.
   SWAPO has waged a guerrilla war since 1966 in a bid to win
independence for the territory, which has been ruled by South Africa
since World War I.
   Last year, South Africa agreed to a U.N. plan that calls for the
independence process to begin April 1, leading to elections in
November. SWAPO is favored in the elections, but other political
parties will be competing.
   Van Heerden said there would be ``hell to pay'' when these
parties learn that the U.N. was raising money that would benefit
SWAPO.
   Van Heerden also accused SWAPO of inflating the number of its
supporters living as refugees outside Namibia. SWAPO has said there
are 80,000 refugees, while the U.N. has put the figure at around
60,000, and South Africa has suggested there might be as few as
15,000. SWAPO receives funds from various countries and
organizations on a per capita basis.
   The U.N. operation in Namibia involves 4,650 peacekeeping troops
and will cost in excess of $400 million.
   One of the major Namibian political parties today accused
Australian peacekeepers of attending a party of SWAPO supporters and
wishing the organization well in the elections.
   The Democratic Turnhalle Alliance said about five Australian
peacekeepers went to the party Tuesday evening in the northern town
of Grootfontein. At one stage, one of the Australians went to the
microphone and wished SWAPO success in the elections, the alliance
said in a statement.
   The alliance, a multiracial coalition, is expected to be SWAPO's
main competitor in the elections.
   About 170 peacekeepers from Canada, Denmark and Ireland arrived
in Namibia today to join the U.N. forces. More than 20 nations are
sending troops and administrative personnel to participate in the
U.N. effort.
</TEXT>
