<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings 1stLd-Writethru a0451 03-16 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impeached Judge Fights to Save Job in Dramatic Appeal to Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Moves pvs 14th graf, In an, up to 6th graf to clarify that Bryant
was speaking in role as prosecutor; rewords pvs 10th graf, Rep. John, to
conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge impeached by the House fought
to hang onto his job in a dramatic personal appeal on the Senate
floor and then sat in silence as lawmakers denounced him for
``inexcusable breaches of the public trust.''
   Standing before the Senate, District Judge Alcee L. Hastings of
Miami declared Wednesday he had been acquitted by a jury in 1983 of
charges of plotting to get a $150,000 bribe and said ``five years of
post-acquittal investigation has produced no new evidence.''
   ``I proclaimed my innocence then as I have from the outset and as
I do now,'' said Hastings, the first black federal judge in Florida
history.
   Nearby sat Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, who resigned
as a federal judge to come to the Senate, his expression alert but
noncommittal. A few desks away, Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., former
chief justice of the Alabama Supreme Court, thumbed through law
books and leaned forward from time to time to gaze at Hastings.
   The Senate planned a closed-door session today to consider the
appeal from Hastings and his attorney, Terence J. Anderson, for
dismissal of all but one of the 17 articles of impeachment approved
by the House 413-3 on Aug. 3.
   In an impeachment trial, House members serve as the prosecutors
and the Senate acts as the judge and jury.
   A decision to go ahead with the impeachment trial would move the
proceedings to a special committee for hearing evidence, followed by
a floor vote on whether to convict Hastings of conspiracy, perjury
and disclosing secret wiretap information in an investigation of
South Florida corruption.
   Hastings, 52, would remain free if convicted but would lose his
seat on the federal bench and his $89,500 annual salary.
   Packed galleries were ordered by Sergeant-at-Arms Henry K. Giugni
to ``keep silent on pain of imprisonment'' as Hastings took the
floor to address an extraordinary Senate session with attendance
among lawmakers unusually high.
   ``The jury heard all the evidence and argument on both sides,''
Hastings said. ``They were attentive. The prosecutors never
complained about either the quality of the jurors or the attention
they gave. Those jurors deliberated carefully. They reached a
conclusion. All 12 of them agreed that I was not guilty.''
   Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, one of the prosecutors, scoffed at
Hastings' position. He said a double-jeopardy defense did not apply
in an impeachment trial but that the judge was seizing on it anyway
``to shield himself from the consequences of his inexcusable
breaches of the public trust.''
   ``Over five years, Judge Alcee Hastings engaged in a clearly
discernible pattern of misbehavior,'' Bryant said.
   ``He conspired to sell his public office for personal gain, he
subverted our judicial process by repeatedly lying under oath and he
divulged confidential information in violation of his own court
order,'' House Judiciary Committee Chairman Jack Brooks, D-Texas,
told the Senate while Hastings sat silently at the defense table
with his attorneys.
   ``Today, Judge Hastings asks you to ignore his corrupt conduct,''
Brooks said. ``In doing so, he asks you to rely on a tainted jury
verdict.''
   In addition to asserting the double jeopardy defense, Hastings
says he cannot get a fair trial because of numerous delays between
the 1983 criminal trial and now. House members say the judge himself
caused 18 months of delays by fighting a rearguard action to prevent
lawmakers from getting their hands on evidence.
   Hastings, a 1979 appointee to the federal bench, was arrested the
night of Oct. 8, 1981, in Miami, hours after a close friend,
Washington attorney William Borders, was caught with a garment bag
containing $125,000 in cash that he had received from an undercover
FBI agent.
   The undercover agent had been posing as Frank Romano, one of two
brothers already under a three-year sentence from Hastings after
being convicted of skimming from a Teamsters pension fund loan.
   The Romano brothers, who have since died, had balked when
approached about paying a bribe in exchange for a better sentence.
The FBI, which had been investigating Borders, set up a sting
operation with the undercover man masquerading as Romano.
   Borders, at the time a politically influential Washington
criminal lawyer, was convicted of promising that Hastings would
change the prison time to probation in exchange for the $150,000
payoff. He was sentenced to five years and went to prison after his
appeals failed.
   Hastings was in Washington for a testimonial dinner for Borders
the day the FBI sprang its trap. Informed that agents wanted to
question him, he left his suite in the plush L'Enfant Plaza Hotel
without packing or checking out and told a friend he was taking a
cab to National Airport, four miles away.
   Instead, he traveled more than 30 miles to Baltimore-Washington
International Airport and caught a flight to Miami but deplaned in
Fort Lauderdale and rented a car to drive to Miami. His own auto at
the time was parked at the Miami airport.
</TEXT>
