<FIRST>r w PM-HowardProtest     03-16 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Howard Protest,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Trustees Said Concerned About Administrators' Performance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trustees of Howard University have expressed
concern that the institution's administration may be incapable of
resolving pressing problems and agreed to closely monitor top
administrators, it was reported today.
   Board members also told administrators Wednesday they hold them
responsible for student demonstrations at the predominantly black
university that subsided only after the intervention of Mayor Marion
Barry Jr. and civil rights leader Jesse Jackson, The Washington Post
said.
   John E. Jacob, chairman of the board of trustees, told reporters
that in a board meeting with President James Cheek and others, ``We
expressed our expectation that the administration will manage this
institution as efficiently and effectively as possible and correct
the inadequacies that exist. The board wants to make sure we don't
get a recurrence (of the demonstrations) in the future.''
   The Poat quoted one unidentified trustee as saying: ``There is a
deep concern on the part of the trustees that our recent troubles
are a result of the fact that there is no one at the helm. We will
be meeting over the next two to three months to determine if there
is any way to address Howard's problems with the present
(leadership) team.''
   Roger D. Estep, vice president for university relations who has
been acting as spokesman for the administration, said he could not
comment on the criticisms raised about Cheek or his deputies.
   For more than three days last week, 3,000 students, about
one-fourth of the student body, occupied the Howard administration
building to protest the appointment of Republican National Chairman
Lee Atwater to the board of trustees.
   Atwater's nomination, while made by another trustee, was
wholeheartedly supported by Cheek, who has been president of the
federally subsidized university since 1968.
   Students said Atwater's management of President Bush's election
campaign had had racist overtones, and that his appointment showed
how insensitive university administrators are to their concerns.
They demanded and received Atwater's resignation.
   They also got assurances that the school would consider an
African-American graduate studies program, and work on severe
housing inadequacies, speedier processing of financial aid and
security improvements.
</TEXT>
