<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-writethru a0520 03-16 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-writethru, a0520,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shells Hit Port, Residential Areas In Lebanese Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with shelling of residential areas. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christians and Moslems battled with
artillery across Beirut today, and Moslems staged a nationwide
strike to mourn victims of the worst round of civil war fighting in
four years.
   Police said Moslem gunners fired rockets from west Beirut's
seaside Zeitouni district into the Christian-controlled Beirut port,
damaging installations but causing no casualties.
   In retaliation, Christian batteries fired on the Moslem
residential districts of Sabra and Kasskass near Beirut's dividing
Green Line, a police spokesman said. There were no immediate reports
of casualties, according to the police spokesman, who requested
anonymity.
   Loudspeaker vans toured west Beirut after the bombardment, urging
people to remain indoors.
   Sniper fire crackled in the old commercial district straddling
the Mediterranean harbor and around the Christian-held town of Souk
El-Gharb, southeast of the capital, police said.
   The two locations were the main battlefronts in the past eight
days of fighting that left 49 people dead and 161 wounded, by police
count.
   The clashes occurred between Christian units of army commander
Gen. Michel Aoun and Syrian-backed militiamen of Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party.
   The fighting began after Aoun on March 6 imposed an air-and-sea
blockade on illegal harbors run by Moslem militias south of Beirut
in a bid to choke off their main source of revenue.
   The blockade angered Jumblatt, whose party runs two illegal port
facilities south of Beirut, and Shiite Moslem leader Nabih Berri,
whose Amal militia operates one port in south beirut.
   The militias use the ports to bring in weapons and supplies as
well as imported goods sold in areas under their control. As a
result, the state treasury loses an estimated $100 million a year in
customs duties.
   The one-day strike in west Beirut and other Moslem areas was
called by Jumblatt and his Moslem and leftist allies ``in mourning
for the victims of the massacre committed by Gen. Aoun.''
   Most casualties in the latest round of the 14-year-old civil war
were victims of a 24-hour shelling duel in Beirut on Monday and
Tuesday.
   Schools, shops, cafes, restaurants, banks and other businesses
were closed in west Beirut in response to Jumblatt's call for a work
stoppage.
   The police spokesman said Moslems in cities in north, east and
south Lebanon also joined the strike.
   Aoun heads a Christian military Cabinet that has been vying for
legitimacy with a rival Moslem Cabinet under acting Prime Minister
Salim Hoss since President Amin Gemayel's term ended Sept. 22.
   Minutes before stepping down, Gemayel named Aoun to head an
interim military Cabinet, but his appointment was rejected by
leftists and Moslems who declared allegiance to Hoss.
   Aoun, 53, accused Syrian peacekeeping troops stationed in west
Beirut of causing the two-day bombardment.
   He declared that his 20,000 regular troops were involved in a
``war of liberation'' against Syrian occupation forces.
   The Syrians, with 40,000 troops deployed in predominantly Moslem
sectors of the country, are Lebanon's main power brokers and support
Hoss' cabinet.
   In Syria, the Al-Baath daily newspaper, which is controlled by
President Hafez Assad's ruling party, denied Aoun's charges and said
they were aimed at ``devastating Syria's constructive role in
Lebanon.''
</TEXT>
