<FIRST>r w PM-O'Connor-Christians     03-16 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-O'Connor-Christians,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Criticized for Letter on `Christian Nation' Rulings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor is
being criticized for sending a letter used by conservative Arizona
Republicans to support their claim that the United States is ``a
Christian nation.''
   Arthur J. Kropp, president of People for the American Way, said
the letter has lent support to a movement that is ``a force for
religious intolerance.'' The liberal activist group supports strict
separation of church and state.
   O'Connnor said in a brief statement Wednesday that she was sorry
the way her letter was used.
   ``I regret that a letter I sent to an acquaintance in response to
her request for information was used in a political debate,'' said
O'Connor, a former state legislator from Arizona.
   ``It was not my intention to express a personal view about the
subject of the inquiry, but merely to attempt to respond
appropriately to one of the many requests for information which come
across my desk.''
   She declined further comment.
   O'Connor's May 19, 1988 letter was sent to Annetta Conant, author
of a resolution characterizing the United States as a Christian
nation that was adopted last January by the Arizona Republican Party.
   The resolution is a rallying point for backers of the state's
former GOP governor, Evan Mecham, who was removed from office last
year. Moderate Republicans and prominent Jewish Republicans in the
state expressed dismay over the resolution.
   O'Connor said in her letter to Ms. Conant, ``You wrote me
recently to inquire about any holdings of this court to the effect
that this is a Christian nation. There are statements to such effect
in the following opinions.''
   The letter cited three high court rulings. In one, handed down in
1892, the court said, ``We are a Christian people and the morality
of the country is deeply engrafted upon Christianity.''
   But two more recent opinions do not refer to the United States a
a Christian nation in the pages cited by O'Connor.
   One opinion, written by liberal Justice William O. Douglas in
1952, said, ``We are a religious people whose institutions
presuppose a Supreme Being. We guarantee the freedom to worship as
one chooses.''
   The other, a concurring opinion by Justice Felix Franfurter in
1961, said religious beliefs in America ``shall continue ... to
exist, to function ... free of the dictates and directions of the
state.''
</TEXT>
