<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     03-16 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Palestinian Houses Destroyed, Two Sealed in Gaza Strip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops today destroyed or sealed four
homes owned by Palestinians linked to a guerrilla group and
reportedly opened fire on Palestinian youths who threw stones in the
occupied Gaza Strip.
   Throughout the narrow coastal strip, Palestinian youths burned
tires, raised outlawed Palestinian flags and hurled rocks at troops,
who responded with gunfire, Arab reports said. There were no reports
of casualties.
   Protests by stone-throwing Palestinian school children prompted
Israeli authorities to close two Palestinian junior high schools in
Gaza City and the nearby village of Bani Suheila, reports said.
   Palestinian witnesses said troops used dynamite to blow up two
homes in the Rimal and Tufah neighborhoods of Gaza City after
imposing curfews and ordering family members to remove their
belongings.
   The homes were owned by two brothers who were arrested earlier
this month for allegedly belonging to a guerrilla squad linked to
PLO chief Yasser Arafat, the army said. The squad is accused of
killing two Palestinians suspected of cooperating with Israeli
authorities.
   ``This house belonged to my husband's 75-year-old father,'' Nadia
Abukhari said. ``My six children and I are now homeless.''
   Troops also sealed the homes of two other alleged squad members,
the army said.
   In the Jabaliya refugee camp, troops late Wednesday bulldozed the
home of a Palestinian lawyer wanted by Israeli authorities for
allegedly heading Jihad Islami, a fundamentalist Moslem group backed
by Fatah, the army said.
   The timing of the demolition appeared linked to an attempted
infiltration from Egypt on Wednesday by two Palestinian teen-agers
who said they belonged to Jihad Islami and were operating with the
backing of Fatah.
   Since the December 1987 start of the uprising, the army has
destroyed or sealed nearly 200 houses belonging to Palestinians
suspected of anti-Israeli violence. Usually, the houses are
demolished or sealed before a suspect stands trial. The United
States has condemned the practice, saying it violates the right to
due process before the law.
</TEXT>
