<FIRST>r w PM-DCHomicides     03-16 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC Homicides,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Dead in Capital Shootings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three homicides within six hours raised the
District of Columbia's homicide toll to a record pace of 110 for the
year, authorities said today.
   The deaths were the first fatal shootings here in at least 91
hours, police said, and compared with 67 homicides at this time last
year. The names of the victims were not released.
   The first victim died Wednesday night in what police described as
an execution-style slaying in the northwest section.
   The second victim was shot four times between two buildings at an
apartment complex in the city's southeast quadrant, according to
neighbors and police.
   The victim was pronounced dead at the Washington Hospital Center
a short time later. A nursing supervisor said, ``He was riddled with
bullets.''
   The third shooting death occurred early today in northeast
Washington when a man was found dead in a four-wheel-drive truck, a
vehicle that police say is popular with drug dealers.
   Police said they have no suspects or motives for the deaths, but
most previous homicides had been linked to the drug trade.
   The fatal shootings late Wednesday and early today were the first
since four men were killed within six hours Friday night.
</TEXT>
