<DOCNO> AP890316-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Flight103 4thLd-Writethru a0561 03-16 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flight 103, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0561,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Gave Secret Alert Before Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Subs 13th graf pvs, ``A New...'' with 1 graf and grafs 20-23,
``Gerladine Busar...'' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with more reaction from relatives.
No pickup. ^By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain secretly alerted airlines and airports
about a possible terrorist attack two days before a bomb blew Pan Am
Flight 103 out of the sky over Scotland, the Transport Department
has announced.
   It said in a statement Wednesday night the alert gave precise
details of a new type of bomb, hidden in a radio-cassette player,
similar to the device that on Dec. 21 destroyed Flight 103, killing
all 259 people aboard the jumbo jet and 11 on the ground in
Lockerbie.
   The alert was similar to an earlier warning sent out on Nov. 22,
but included a photo of the radio-cassette player, the department
said later.
   Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt, West Germany, then changed
planes at London's Heathrow airport before heading for New York.
   A radio-cassette player containing plastic explosives and a
device that could be set to detonate the bomb at a given altitude
was found in October during raids by West German authorities in
which 13 alleged members of the Syrian-backed Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command guerrilla group were
arrested.
   Pam Hanlon, a Pan Am spokeswoman in New York, said today: ``There
is indeed a memo dated Dec. 19, but we did not receive it until Jan.
17. I am not going to say more than that.'' She said she did not
have the memo in front of her so she would not talk about what it
contained.
   Trans World Airlines was advised by the U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration on Nov. 18 of a bomb device found in Germany, and was
told the same thing by the British Department of Transport on Jan.
16, said Charles Adams, a senior vice president of TWA's
international division.
   Adams today said in London that ``people are reading an awful lot
of things into'' the fact that some airlines received the
information from the Departnent of Transport on Jan. 16. ``We had
received the same information from the FAA a month earlier,'' he
said.
   A British Airways spokesman said the airline received a telex on
Nov. 22, ``the day it was sent'' but refused to go into details of
what it said. He also said the airline received an alert on Dec. 19.
   ``We had full details, which we passed onto security staff,'' he
said. He declined to be named.
   Lawmaker John Prescott, the opposition Labor Party's spokesman on
transport, accused the government of mounting ``what can only be a
cover-up.''
   Two Americans who lost family members aboard Flight 103 today
said the plane should have been searched for a bomb before it left
for New York.
   The Transport Department said the alert from its principal
aviation security adviser, Jim Jack, followed an initial warning in
November of a possible bombing.
   It said: ``The barometric timing device indicated it was intended
to sabotage an aircraft. We sent advice to the relevant security
authorities. They were told what to look for. The American
authorities would have done the same for American airlines.''
   Asked why Transport Secretary Paul Channon had not mentioned the
Dec. 19 warning after the bombing, a department spokesman, who in
accordance with British practice declined to be further identified,
said: ``These are things that Mr. Channon may want to answer on in
due course.
   He said an initial warning was sent on Nov. 22, or 17 days before
a Dec. 9 warning by U.S. intelligence sources that a group planned
to bomb a Pan Am jet from Frankfurt within two weeks.
   The spokesman said some members of the group arrested in Germany
were still being detained while investigations continued into the
Lockerbie bombing.
   ``The case of the terrorist group in Frankfurt is being looked at
in relation to Lockerbie,'' he said.
   The London tabloid the Daily Mirror today called the latest
disclosure ``a huge embarrassment'' to Channon and Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, who have come under pressure ``from anguished
relatives and members of Parliament to disclose how much the
government knew.''
   Raymond Germain, a Staten Island, N.Y. man whose 20-year-old
daughter Kathleen was killed aboard the plane, said the plane should
have been searched for a bomb.
   ``It's unconscionable. This plane should have never left the
ground until it was thoroughly checked,'' he said in an telephone
interview.
   Geraldine Buser of Glen Rock, N.J., told WCBS Radio: ``How the
hell am I supposed to feel if they knew this (the bomb) was going to
be there.''
   Ms. Buser, who lost her husband, Warren; son, Michael; and
daughter Lorraine Howe, said: ``If it's going to save a planeload of
people and you have a report that this thing might happen, it's
worth (waiting) two hours.''
</TEXT>
