<FIRST>r a PM-CarCurfew     03-16 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Car Curfew,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas Offering Motorists Car-Curfew Decals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists in Dallas will soon be offered a window
decal allowing police to stop their car after hours to see if it is
stolen.
   Under a plan Police Chief Mack Vines is expected to reveal
Thursday, the sticker will be made available for free to interested
motorists and will alert police that the car should not be on the
street in the early morning.
   Under the law, police cannot normally stop a car without
``probable cause'' to believe a crime has been committed.
   More than 24,000 cars, worth $130.4 million, were stolen last
year in Dallas, a 22 percent increase over 1987. During January and
February of 1989, the auto theft rate was 38 percent higher than the
same months in 1988, police said.
   The stickers will serve as both a deterrent to auto theft and a
tool to catch thieves in the act, said Deputy Police Chief Richard
Schifelbein.
   Lt. Randy Jones of the department's auto theft division said the
decals will be designed like inspection stickers so they can't be
peeled off.
   ``A good auto thief won't want to take five minutes scraping off
a sticker so he can steal a car,'' he said.
</TEXT>
