<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-writethru a0481 03-16 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-writethru, a0481,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Halt Traffic, Attack Soldiers in El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with buses stopped, power outages, rebel
attacks. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas paralyzed bus services, sabotaged
power lines and staged sporadic attacks today in a stepped-up
campaign to disrupt Sunday's presidential election.
   Most bus drivers refused to work because rebels warned bus
companies to keep their vehicles off the nation's streets and gas
stations to remain closed. Many gas stations were guarded by troops
to prevent rebel attacks.
   ``It does not matter that we have the soldiers here. We can't
work because the workers have not come in,'' a watchman at one gas
station said.
   Much of the capital and the eastern half of the country was
without power after rebels destroyed electricity poles, the power
company said.
   Schools were closed throughout El Salvador, while army
helicopters and planes flew over the capital.
   One soldier was killed and four were wounded during a pre-dawn
guerrilla attack in Entre Rios, 40 miles east of San Salvador, the
military said.
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the umbrella group
for the leftist guerrillas, also launched morning attacks in the
towns of Cinquera and Tejutepeque in the eastern department of
Cabanas and in the provincial capital of Zacatecoluca, officials
said. No casualties were immediately reported.
   In the capital, an army convoy waited outside the eastern bus
terminal to transport passengers to San Vicente, 30 miles to the
east, but few customers were seen early this morning.
   ``No one has come in. The owners are afraid. So are the people,''
said dispatcher Lazaro Lopez at San Salvador's western bus terminal.
Lopez said there normally are 300 bus departures and arrivals daily.
   The rebels have called for an election boycott and warned they
would sabotage any vehicle ignoring the transport ban. Such threats
have stopped about 90 percent of the nation's transport in the past.
   Private operators used flatbed and pickup trucks to transport
people throughout San Salvador, and some vehicles carried white
flags. News reports said citizens were offering similar transport
services in other cities.
   On Wednesday, when campaigning officially ended, rebels attacked
the presidential palace with grenades and bombs and killed a
prominent rightist political adviser in the capital.
   Also Wednesday, a civilian judge indicted two military officers
on charges of massacring 10 peasants. It was the first time in El
Salvador's nine-year civil war that officers have been indicted in a
human rights case.
   In Wednesday night's attack on the palace, shrapnel from a
rocket-propelled grenade injured a palace guard and six civilians
who live nearby, authorities said. The leftist rebels claimed
responsibility in a radio broadcast.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte was not present when the grenades
and catapult-launched homemade bombs began landing, said Col.
Ricardo Casanova, commander of the Zapote garrison next door.
   Unidentified gunmen on Wednesday killed Francisco Peccorini, a
political adviser to the Arena party. Peccorini was shot three times
while being driven in his car, authorities said.
   Alfredo Cristiani of Arena, or the Republican Nationalist
Alliance, is favored to win Sunday's vote, with Fidel Chavez Mena of
the Duarte's centrist Christian Democrats second and Guillermo Ungo
of the leftist Democratic Convergence third. If Arena wins, it would
be the first time in Salvadoran history that voters dumped an
incumbent party in favor of another.
   The military said it would provide armed escorts Sunday to
vehicles taking voters to the polls.
   The rebels have boycotted every election this decade as a farce,
accusing the government of ignoring the fundamental economic and
social problems of this Massachusetts-sized nation of 5.5 million
people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
