<FIRST>r a PM-MobFuneral     03-16 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mob Funeral,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Mobsters Shun Funeral for Reputed Chicago Crime Boss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the disappointment of curiosity seekers and law
enforcement agents, Chicago's top mobsters stayed away from the
funeral of reputed mob boss Joseph Ferriola.
   About 150 mourners, including two dozen women in furs and jewelry
and men in expensive tailored suits, paid their respects Wednesday
in a flower-filled salon at the Salerno Galewood Chapel on the
city's far West Side.
   But ``the big boys ... the people who are supposed to take over
(the crime syndicate in Chicago) didn't show up,'' said a man who
was comparing with another man the number of out-of-state licence
plates they had counted.
   ``This was a bustout,'' he said, ``and you can call me an
`informed source.'''
   The two men declined to identify themselves.
   The FBI and the Chicago Crime Commission, a private watchdog
group, would not comment on who attended the service or the burial
in suburban Hillside.
   Ferriola, who authorities said rose through the ranks and had run
the crime syndicate's day-to-day operations since 1973, died
Saturday in Houston after two heart transplants. He is survived by
his wife and five children.
   The prospect of a gangland funeral attracted dozens of
journalists, photographers and law agents.
   People watched from across the street in a restaurant parking lot
where Ferriola's fellow mobster, Charles ``Chuckie'' English was
gunned down in 1985.
   ``When they put the casket in the hearse, I thought that he is
really just an ordinary person and I felt sorry for his family,''
said Susan Trella, a neighborhood resident.
</TEXT>
