<FIRST>r a PM-FlagArt 2ndLd-Writethru a0534 03-16 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Art, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0534,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversial Exhibit Draws to a Close, Leaving Ledger Legacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd graf pvs, `Since the ...' to UPDATE
with exhibit opening.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American flag made its final appearance on the
floor at a student art exhibit today, with three ledgers offering a
handwritten history of the rage, pain, sympathy and support that the
work provoked.
   The stage for the four weeks of heated debate was set by
``Dread'' Scott Tyler, 24, with his work ``What is the Proper Way to
Display the U.S. Flag?''
   Since the show opened at the School of the Art Institute, the
work has triggered demonstrations, debate on Capitol Hill, censure
by the state House, submission of tough new flag-protection
legislation in the state Senate and a lawsuit seeking the flag's
removal that was promptly dismissed by a judge.
   The exhibit opened this morning without incident, said school
spokeswoman Beth Sullivan. ``We expect it to be pretty quiet
today,'' she said.
   President Bush said Wednesday that he thought the
flag-on-the-floor exhibit is ``disgraceful'' but added that he would
be ``very wary'' of proposed legislation that would jail anyone for
setting up such a display.
   ``I'm always worried about the right of free speech,'' Bush said
in an Oval Office interview with the Chicago Sun-Times and five
other newspapers.
   Bush said he was disgusted by the exhibit because ``there's a
certain respect for the flag that American people have.''
   The controversy is all there in the ledgers that are part of the
work: anger and pain from veterans, comment on First Amendment
rights, opinions about Tyler's use of the flag as a powerful symbol,
and more.
   The authors number in the hundreds, with myriad viewpoints.
   A sampling:
   ``A cheap publicity stunt, not art. It's sad you had to desecrate
our flag to achieve recognition.''
   ``Well, Scott, you got what you wanted.''
   ``You should be put on the floor and walked on.''
   ``Good work at provoking a reaction. That's what art is supposed
to do.''
   ``Dude, you think this is cool well, it's not.''
   ``This took guts. If you believe in what you did, good for you.''
   ``If you don't like this country, move to a communist one.''
   ``You skunk _ my father's flag was drapped (sic) over his coffin
...''
   ``I think this is a lot of fuss over nothing.''
   ``Becky call Ed.''
   One visitor congratulated Tyler on enlisting viewers to complete
the piece with their comments _ ``living history.''
   Another bemoaned the ``myopia'' of visitors who ``neglect all the
art that surrounds them'' at the juried exhibit, which featured 66
minority-student works, mostly paintings.
   Viewers Wednesday were admitted in small groups for security
reasons and allowed about 10 minutes at the school's public gallery.
Many returned to the short line for another look.
   Security guards sighed with relief at the prospect of an end to
the exhibit that drew hostile visitors and even threats.
   And in front of the Art Institute, a downtown showcase, a handful
of protesters proudly waved American flags.
   Tyler intended the flag to be spread on the floor beneath a
framed, black-and-white montage featuring flag-draped coffins and
Third World anti-American protest, and the shelf containing the
ledgers.
   Protesters contend the arrangement invites visitors to walk on
the flag, a claim disputed by school officials.
   Tyler has called his work revolutionary and says he had no
apologies, despite death threats he said he and his mother have
received.
   ``The bad news is that the flag doesn't mean to the Scott Tylers
of this country what it means to so many of us,'' Robert Mars, Art
Institute vice president for administration, said earlier this week.
``The good news is that our system worked. The student was allowed
to make his statement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
