<HEAD>Angolan Fighter Jet Crashes, Pilot Killed; New Fighting Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Angolan air force jet crashed while
landing at Huambo airport in central Angola, and the pilot was
killed, Angola's state-run news agency reported Thursday.
   The Soviet-built MiG-21 was destroyed in the crash Wednesday,
said the ANGOP agency in a report monitored in Lisbon. It identified
the dead pilot as Lt. Augusto Lourenco and said the crash occurred
while the jet was approaching the runway at Huambo.
   According to ANGOP, a commission set up to investigate the crash
ruled out the possibility rebels shot down the plane.
   The town of Huambo was once the main base of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola rebel movement, and there have
been reports of heavy fighting in the region.
   ANGOP reported Thursday that forces of Angola's Marxist
government claimed to have killed 89 rebels and freed more than 200
civilians held by the rebels in clashes in Huambo province and other
parts of the country in the past week.
   In addition, seven rebel fighters and 25 of their civilian
supporters turned themselves over to government troops, ANGOP quoted
an army statement as saying.
   Four government soldiers died and 17 were wounded in the
fighting, and two were missing in action, ANGOP reported.
   The agency also said six civilians died and five were wounded
Monday when a mine planted by rebels exploded in the Cacola region,
South Lunda province.
