<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Population     03-16 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Population,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widespread Defiance of Birth Control Policies Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's policy of one child per couple and
restrictions on early marriages are being widely ignored, according
to a State Planning Commission survey released Thursday.
   Results of the survey said that since the one-child policy was
started in 1980, about 9 million babies a year have been born
outside the state plan.
   Family Planning Commission head Peng Peiyun said the survey was
an ``alarm bell.'' She said the average Chinese couple between 1980
and 1987 had 2.47 children.
   Last year there were approximately 23 million births and 7
million deaths in China, pushing the nation's population close to
1.1 billion.
   The two-year survey, which covered 2 million people, found that
women bearing two or more children accounted for 40 percent of the
unauthorized births. About one-fifth of the unauthorized births were
to women under 20, which is the legal age for women in China to
marry, the People's Daily said in reporting results of the survey.
   The survey found that less than 60 percent of women of
child-bearing age practice birth control.
   The government has had substantial success in limiting family
sizes in cities but has met strong resistance in the countryside.
Rural couples, wanting boys in particular to help in the fields and
to care for them when they become old, have been willing to pay
steep fines for violating the one-child policy.
   The government has acknowledged that its target of limiting
population to 1.2 billion in the year 2000 is not possible.
Estimates for the number of Chinese at the turn of the century have
jumped to 1.3 billion, about 20 percent of total world population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890316-0080 </DOCNO>
