<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe-Smuggling     03-16 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe-Smuggling,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomats, Businessmen Smuggle Out Millions of Dollars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign diplomats and wealthy executives
are smuggling more than $10 million of gold and emeralds out of the
country every year, a newspaper reported Thursday.
   To curb the trafficking, the independent Chamber of Mines is
pressing for tougher laws, and the government is considering setting
up a special police unit, The Herald said.
   Most of the smuggled gold is bought from prospectors illegally
panning from rivers and streams, Chamber chief executive Derek Bain
was quoted as saying.
   The Harare Mining Commissioner estimates panners yield 1,653
pounds of gold a year, but only 3{ pounds are sold to the state
Minerals Marketing Corporation, according to the report.
   Under Zimbabwean law, all gold from the country must be sold only
to the Corporation or the Reserve Bank.
   Zimbabwe's main emerald mine, Rio Tinto, exports $2 million of
the gems each year, according to the Minerals Marketing Corporation.
But a similar amount, stolen from Rio Tinto or illegally mined
elsewhere, is believed to be smuggled out, the corporation said.
   The mining executives did not identify the nationalities of the
diplomats reported to be involved in the racket.
