<FIRST>r w AM-Satellite-Earthquakes     03-16 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satellite-Earthquakes,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Satellite Facing Budget Ax Helps Locate Earthquake Faults</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have discovered a series of unknown
earthquake faults thanks to pictures from a satellite that has been
facing the budget ax.
   The faults are located in the central and eastern parts of
California's Mojave Desert and were found using images taken by the
Landsat satellite, according to the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
   The faults were discovered by studying a series of images taken
in differing optical and infrared spectra, according to scientists
at NASA`s Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena, Calif., and at
Louisiana State University.
   Some of the faults are inactive, but others may still be
seismically active, the scientists said. The faults form part of a
complex fault region between Death Valley and the San Andreas fault
region.
   Without the Landsat images, the faults would not have been
discovered, said John Ford of NASA.
   His announcement was made even as scientists and politicians were
struggling over financing to keep the Landsat system going.
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration announced
recently that it would have to shut down the Landsat system at the
end of this month because of a lack of money to operate it.
   Subsequently Vice President Dan Quayle began encouraging other
government agencies to chip in funds to keep the system going and
the cutoff has at least been delayed.
   Landsat, which studies the Earth's surface for mapping, mineral
studies and other research, still faces a tenuous financual future,
however.
</TEXT>
