<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1256EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-DalaiLama Bjt   03-16 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dalai Lama, Bjt,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetan Leader Optimistic Chinese Will Negotiate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHARMSALA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tibetans' spiritual leader, the Dalai
Lama, said Thursday he believes Beijing is ready for negotiations
that would grant greater freedom to his people and the land he fled
30 years ago.
   In an interview at his exile headquarters in the remote Himalayan
foothills of north India, the Dalai Lama admitted he has had no
recent indication of this from Chinese authorities.
   In fact, the Tibetan capital of Lhasa has been under martial law
since bloody anti-Chinese protests there last week.
   But the Dalai Lama adhered to his belief that change is sweeping
China, that the new concept of reform in the Soviet Union will soon
come to the world's other major communist power.
   ``Within a few months, talks may start,'' the Dalai Lama said.
   In the meantime, he said, he will continue to support non-violent
protest in Tibet.
   ``Peaceful demonstrations _ that I am supporting. That is the
only way to make (our situation) known to the outside world,'' the
Dalai Lama said.
   Tibetans ``should not indulge in damaging and burning property.
They should not indulge in stoning. Even if the Chinese open fire,
they should not retaliate,'' he said.
   The Dalai Lama spoke at midafternoon in the hilltop compound that
houses his residence, offices, Thekchen Choeling Temple and Namgyal
Monastery where maroon-robed monks debate ancient scriptures and
venerate this bespectacled, 54-year-old farmer's son as a living
god-king, the 14th reincarnation of the earthly manifestation of
Buddha.
   On another March 16 afternoon, exactly 30 years ago, the Dalai
Lama was in a more remote and far grander Himalayan compound, in
Lhasa. Surrounded by Chinese troops who had moved their artillery
within range of his palace, the Dalai Lama and his advisers were at
the brink of the decision that would propel him and eventually
110,600 other Tibetans into exile.
   By the night of March 17, he had slipped out of Lhasa's
Norbulinka Palace disguised as a Tibetan soldier and shouldering a
rifle. By April 18, 1959, he was safe in India, free to speak
against China.
   But the Tibetans' uprising had failed. The Chinese guns had
bombarded Norbulinka, and thousands of Tibetans were dead.
   It was the approach of this anniversary that resulted in more
bloodshed in Lhasa last week.
   By official count, 16 people were killed when police opened fire
during a pro-independence demonstration in Lhasa in which
Chinese-owned shops and vehicles were set afire. Western travelers
said as many as 20 or 30 were killed.
   China's subsequent ban on foreigners entering Tibet makes it
impossible for the outside world to know with any certainty what is
happening in the ancient kingdom, which Chinese troops entered in
1950.
   Beijing maintains Tibet has traditionally been part of China. The
Dalai Lama and his government in exile say Tibet has been
independent for centuries.
   ``In the last few days, you see a sad situation within Tibet,''
the Dalai Lama said, a long shawl of finely spun wool protecting him
from the mountain chill.
   ``In the last 30 years, they (the Chinese) have used every
repression,'' he said, speaking in English. ``We lost everything in
the last 30 years, but we still remain. We are the same Tibetans the
Chinese bullied 30 years ago.''
   Despite the imposition of martial law, the Dalai Lama said he
thought China's eagerness to open its economy to the outside world
would bring greater awareness and greater tolerance to political
problems at home.
   Reflecting a sense that time may be running out, that an influx
of Chinese settlers in Tibet would obliterate the separate Tibetan
identity, the Dalai Lama last June made his biggest concession to
date.
   He proposed his homeland become ``a self-governing democratic
political entity . . . In association with China.''
   In return, he said China could retain troops on Tibetan soil and
handle Tibet's foreign policy.
   China rejected the proposal, saying it failed to relinquish the
concept of Tibetan independence, but it said it was willing to talk
to the Dalai Lama.
   The Dalai Lama on Thursday repeated that talks should start at a
lower level, in a neutral spot outside Chinese control.
   ``If the Chinese do not want to talk, OK. The last 30 years we
spent like this,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
