<DOCNO> AP890316-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpringBreak-Lawsuit     03-16 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spring Break-Lawsuit,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Religious Group Can Hand Out Literature During Spring
Break</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today ordered South
Padre Island to let a Christian group hand out religious literature
on the beach during the annual exercise in excess known as spring
break.
   The group had sued the resort town after being warned of an
ordinance against solicitation on the beach.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela said today that ``the public
beaches are a public forum,'' and he advised the town that
distribution of religious literature is protected under the
Constitution.
   He ended the hearing by telling both sides, ``God bless you,
gentlemen.''
   South Padre officials have estimated that 200,000 to 300,000
students will converge on the island resort near the mouth of the
Rio Grande in March. A rock concert on the beach is scheduled for
Friday.
   Kevin Pitt, a minister at Brownsville's interdominational Word of
God Family Church, said his Youth Ministry Network wants to provide
an alternative to the companies promoting beer and condoms to the
spring-breakers.
   City Manager Eddie Campirano said the town had not tried to
single out any one group with its ordinance, which he said applies
to commercial as well as religious solicitation.
   ``When the public is out there on the beach, they have a right to
be out there and enjoy it and be left alone,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
