<SECOND>AM-BRF--Disorientation Death,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Man Dies After Apparently Becoming Disoriented In Storm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN VALLEY, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 83-year-old man believed to have
become disoriented while driving during a snowstorm strayed 40 miles
from his destination and died, possibly from a heart attack.
   The body of Henry Petrie of Golden Valley was found Wednesday in
his burned-out truck, which was in a ditch near the central
Minnesota city of Monticello, police said.
   Petrie had been on his way to pick up his wife at work in St.
Louis Park, seven miles from their home, during a storm that dumped
more than 7 inches of snow Tuesday.
   Authorities speculate Petrie, who had a heart ailment, became
disoriented in the rush-hour storm, took the wrong route and had a
heart attack, causing the vehicle to veer into a ditch.
   One theory is that the truck's accelerator pedal stuck, causing
the tires to spin then heat to the point of catching fire.
   The body was found about 13 hours after Petrie's wife, Delores,
filed a missing-person report, said Golden Valley police Sgt. Gary
Quarnstrom.
