<SECOND>PM-Groundskeepers Strike, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0578,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crew Pickets Cubs Park Over Proposed Pay Cut</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with statement from the Cubs, CORRECTS that
talks were with the Cubs sted the Tribune Co. No pickup. A version also
moving on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Groundskeepers at Wrigley Field went on strike
today, and laborers installing skyboxes at the Chicago Cubs ballpark
honored the picket lines.
   The National League team assured fans that the walkout will not
disrupt operations at the ballpark this season, which opens in three
weeks.
   The groundskeepers began picketing outside the field at midnight
after contract talks with the Cubs broke down Monday, said Richard
Malkowsky, union secretary-treasurer. The old contract expired Dec.
31.
   Construction workers getting skyboxes ready for the National
League opener April 4 joined the picket line when they arrived for
work in the morning, said police Sgt. Ed Kehoe. He estimated more
than 150 persons picketed or honored the lines.
   Malkowsky said about 300 building-trades workers refused to cross
picket lines. The 24 groundskeepers are paid an average of $21,000 a
year, he said.
   ``They (Cubs management) didn't have enough time to slot us in
for scheduled talks because they were busy giving millions of
dollars away to the ballplayers,'' he said.
   Union attorney Don Cohn said the ballplayers union also will be
asked to join in when they return from spring training in Mesa,
Ariz., but Malkowsky said, ``I'm hoping we can resolve it before the
season starts.''
   The groundskeepers walked out over a management effort to cut
nearly in half their $14-an-hour wage and win other concessions,
said Sam Bongiorno, a 23-year veteran of the groundskeeping crew.
   The team said in a statement, ``The Cubs are certainly willing to
continue negotiations but, in any event, we assure our fans that
this will not disrupt operations at the ballpark this season.''
   Cubs officials declined to discuss the strike further.
   No new talks were scheduled, Cohn said.
</TEXT>
