<DOCNO> AP890316-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     03-16 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Magistrates Arrested, 2 Policemen Suspended in Torture Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested three town
magistrates and suspended two Asuncion police officers accused of
torturing prisoners during the dictatorship of Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner, officials said Thursday.
   The arrests and suspensions are part of a campaign launched by
Gen. Andres Rodriguez, who toppled Stroessner in a Feb. 3 coup.
   The magistrates, who have executive and judicial powers akin to
those of a mayor or justice of the peace, were accused in the 1979
deaths of 24-year-old Adolfo Irala and his brothers, Victor, 19, and
Sindulfo, 27. They died in Tebicuarymi, a town 80 miles southeast of
Asuncion.
   The mother of the three, Leonora Irala, told human rights lawyers
her sons were tortured by electric shock and had their teeth pulled
out with pliers.
   ``My sons' cries and screams for help could be heard in the whole
town,'' Mrs. Irala was quoted as telling the Asuncion newspaper El
Diario.
   She said her sons were detained and tortured for five days in
connection with the slaying of the son of the local ward president
of the ruling Colorado Party.
   Formal charges have not been filed against Tebicuarymi
magistrates Elvio Reyes, Ruben Fernandez and Salustiano Gimenez,
authorities said.
   Police announced the suspension of Asuncion officers Augusto
Caceres Spelt and Camilo Almada Saprissa, who have been accused of
torture during the Stroessner regime.
   Lawyers for human rights organizations said dozens of formal
complaints were filed against those two and others but never were
acted upon.
   ``I know of at least 100 different suits against Almada Saprissa
for torture,'' said Francisco Vargas, a human rights lawyer for the
Committee of Churches.
   Interior Ministry spokesman Artemio Nunez said, ``They will be
given the opportunity to defend themselves.''
   ``We can't be unjust even with those who are unjust with us,'' he
added.
   The campaign against torture began a month ago when Interior
Minister Orlando Machuca Vargas pledged to eliminate torture
chambers in police stations and urged citizens who had been tortured
to file legal complaints.
   Stroessner ruled Paraguay 34 years before being overthrown in a
bloody coup by Rodriguez, who had been his second-in-command in the
army. Stroessner was accused of brutal repression of opponents
during his rule, and the Reagan administration in 1976 labeled his
government a dictatorship.
   He has lived in Brazil since the coup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
