<HEAD>Man Buys Confiscated Equipment For School Chemistry Lab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUNCAN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school has new science equipment
courtesy of a businessman who went to a sheriff's auction and bought
beakers, scales and other items seized in a raid on a drug lab.
   Tom Goodner, owner of the three local supermarkets, purchased the
flatbed load of equipment for $1,400 and donated it to Duncan High
School ``so it can be put to good use instead of bad use.''
   District Attorney Melvin Singleterry suggested the idea to
Goodner, who beat out a couple of others bidding Wednesday on the
material, which was seized in town in 1987.
   Principal Larry David estimated the equipment would have cost
$15,000 if the school tried to buy it new. He said the items should
be enough for several years.
