<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SolarRace     03-16 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solar Race,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teams Getting Ready for Vermont-to-Massachusetts Solar Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the best engineering students in New
England are busy trying to build cars that will take them 200 miles
over four days.
   That won't be so easy as it sounds, because the cars will have to
be powered only by the sun. The Montpelier, Vt.-to-Cambridge, Mass.,
race, called the American Tour de Sol, is set for May 25-28.
   The race is patterned after a competition in Switzerland that has
attracted hundreds of entries since it began in 1985, including
several from the schools involved in the New England race this year.
   ``There's a very high interest level,'' said Dartmouth Professor
Robert Wills, who is coordinating the race. ``At Dartmouth, the
solar car project has attracted the most interest of any engineering
project that I've seen.''
   The winning team will get a trip to the European race, also
called the Tour de Sol, this summer.
   Solar-powered cars use photovoltaic cells to collect energy from
sunlight that power their electric motors. The cars can reach speeds
of more than 60 mph.
   Doug Fraser, coordinator of the Dartmouth team, said it is
redesigning parts of the car that entered last year's European race
but was disqualified because of a technical problem in the drive
system. Changes will include a new drive system and a new computer.
   ``We did pretty well, considering we were using a back-up drive
system,'' Fraser said.
   The other four schools participating are New Hampshire Technical
Institute, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, the University of
Lowell and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
   ``I don't know of any single activity on campus that has created
as much enthusiasm as the solar car project,'' said David Larrabee,
president of New Hampshire Tech.
   Wills said the race will be run along back roads and will take
the competitors through each of the five campuses. The times for the
four daily legs of the race will be compared to calculate the winner.
   ``We managed to hit all the campuses, and that's a big selling
point for us,'' he said. ``Everyone on the campuses will be able to
see the cars.''
   Though the Tour de Sol cars are designed with the hope that one
could someday be used commercially, for now their cost is too high.
Fraser said the Dartmouth car, for example, cost about $80,000.
   Wills said students get their schools or companies to sponsor the
cars, but the cost is worth it because students learn about many
engineering problems.
   ``Even the professors learn a lot,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
