<SECOND>PM-Inmate Death, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0602,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corrections Officers Charged In Death Of Inmate; Inmates Protest
Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead and 9th graf pvs, `The defendants ...' to ADD details
of jail's closing and CLARIFY that the city hasn't decided what to do with
the jail.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The county jail boiled with rage after a
deputy warden and two guards were charged with beating to death an
inmate, and the men were held today in a closed municipal jail for
their safety.
   Inmates of the Hudson County Jail shouted from their cells and
smashed windows, and one set a bedsheet on fire outside a window as
about 75 relatives and friends of the victim, Arnaldo Ortega,
rallied outside on Wednesday.
   Bedsheets and toilet paper flapped from the windows of some cells.
   ``People are out here to pay their respects,'' said John Jones,
25, a protester. ``And we're here for justice. Everybody makes
mistakes, but they made a big one. That boy had a family and now
he's in his grave.''
   At least six police officers stood guard outside the jail during
the demonstration, and about 20 others watched the crowd. There were
no confrontations.
   Earlier in the day, corrections Officers Thomas Murphy, 39, and
David Michael Dumers, 35, and Deputy Warden Raymond Murray, 52, were
charged with murdering Ortega, who was in jail on a burglary charge.
   Hudson County Prosecutor Paul M. DePascale said Ortega, 28, was
beaten for 15 to 20 minutes in a jail elevator and left for 16 hours
in a basement holding cell before guards summoned medical help.
   He died Saturday at a hospital where he was brought two days
earlier in a coma. A coroner's report said he was beaten in the
head, arms and body. Ortega's brother, Angel, said inmates told his
family that guards used nightsticks on Ortega.
   The defendants were unable to raise $50,000 bail and were sent to
the Bayonne City Jail, which was ordered closed by the state a month
ago because it had no cameras to watch for suicide attempts.
Officials are deciding whether to install cameras.
   Superior Court Judge Kevin Callahan said he would not send the
three to the Hudson County Jail for fear of exposing them to attacks
from other inmates.
   The county board of freeholders, in response to protests over the
killing, said it would investigate allegations about the existence
of a ``goon squad'' of corrections workers who routinely beat
inmates.
   DePascale said there is a special unit that responds to crises
but that there was no evidence of unprovoked attacks. No other
criminal charges are planned, he said.
</TEXT>
