<SECOND>AM-Palm Beach-Cameras,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palm Beach Considers Putting Cameras At Town Entrance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Council members hoping to keep
undesirables off their wealthy island are considering installing
closed circuit cameras to monitor bridges and the main highway into
town.
   Town Manager Robert Doney said the cameras would enable
authorities to film ``vehicles, pedestrians and cyclists ... anyone
coming to Palm Beach to do anything of an illegal nature.'' He said
he thought the cameras could have ``a very good psychological effect
on deterring crime.''
   Town Attorney John Randolph said the constitutionality of the
proposal, submitted Tuesday by a resident, should be studied before
the council votes on it, and council members asked the town's Public
Safety Committee to study the matter.
   Council President Nancy Douthit said the idea was ``definitely
worth the research.''
   ``The only people who might be bothered by this are those with a
guilty conscience,'' Douthit said. ``You are photographed any time
you go into a bank, any time you go through a toll booth on the
turnpike and in many retail establishments and condo buildings. I
don't see this as being any different.''
   The proposal would place cameras on four bridges and on the
town's approach on Highway A1A from South Palm Beach.
