<FIRST>r a AM-JailSmoking     03-16 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jail Smoking,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smoking Bans In Jail Proposed In Two More Counties In Michigan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSKEGON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Future inmates at the Muskegon and Ottawa
county jails may have to give up more than their freedom to pay
their debts to society. They may also lose their cigarettes.
   ``People in jail give up quite a bit,'' said Patricia Rehfield,
medical director in Ottawa County, where a committee has recommended
a cigarette ban in the jail and other county buildings. ``Smoking
certainly can be part of that.''
   In Muskegon County, the sheriff's department has proposed that
the county council make the entire department and jail smoke free
May 1, said Capt. Robert Baker, jail administrator.
   ``It is not going to be easy for anyone,'' Baker said, estimating
that more than half the inmates smoke.
   The Ottawa and Muskegon county proposals are inspired in part by
an experimental ban begun six weeks ago at the Grand Traverse County
jail. Officials in the two counties are monitoring that program
before deciding whether to approve their own.
   Some officials are concerned a smoking ban could trigger more
tension in the overcrowded jail system.
   ``We are thinking about issuing hard candy with dinner,'' Baker
said. ``We might also put a popcorn machine in for the evenings.
That might take the edge off of it.'' Muskegon officials also plan
to offer stop-smoking classes to inmates and employees.
</TEXT>
