<FIRST>r a AM-NoMen     03-16 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-No Men,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Oppose Admitting Men To All-Women College</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 students at Colby-Sawyer
College sat in Thursday at the administration building, singing ``I
Am Woman,'' to protest the possible admission of men.
   The protest gave way after about four hours to an emotional
meeting between the students, nearly one-quarter of the school's
roughly 450 enrollment, and two administrators.
   ``This institution runs because of our money. We should be put on
the task force'' studying coeducation, one student told President
Peggy Stock and Trustee Chairman Peter Danforth at the meeting. ``We
deserve that.''
   In addition, the students asked Stock to scrap separate meetings
scheduled with staff, administrators and students in favor of a
campuswide meeting, and to delay by a month the April 1 trustees'
vote on admitting men.
   Students complained that coeducation has been discussed, partly
in response to the prospect of a dwindling applicant pool, since
October, but that students learned of it only recently. Students,
one told Stock, feel ``segregated and manipulated.''
   Stock and Danforth responded that the administration has not
meant to keep anyone in the dark.
   ``There's been no effort at all to divide and conquer. Rather,
just the opposite _ to let everyone know at the time we know,''
Danforth said.
   The liberal arts school has been all-women for more than 60
years. The school traces its roots to a small academy chartered in
1837.
