<SECOND>AM-Police-Rape Charge,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policeman Cleared of Raping Child Is Charged Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer who was acquitted last summer
of sexually abusing a 6-year-old girl was charged Thursday with
raping the same child, after police allegedly found a tape of the
crime in his apartment.
   Patrolman Warren A. Poole, 45, was acquitted in June when the
girl, placed on the witness stand in front of the defendant,
recanted her story of abuse.
   Several months later, however, the girl told police that Poole
had molested her again. After obtaining a search warrant, police
raided Poole's apartment Wednesday and confiscated a videotape that
prosecutors said shows the policeman having sex with the girl.
   Poole, who was suspended without pay after the raid, pleaded
innocent at arraignment in Lynn District Court.
   Judge Joseph Dever set bail at $350,000 with double surety,
meaning Poole must put up bonds worth at least $700,000 to secure
his release.
   Poole's attorney, Alan Karahalis, did not respond to telephone
messages requesting comment.
   Poole, a divorced father of six children, has served for 14 years
on the police force in Lynn, a industrial city of 78,500 people
about 15 miles north of Boston.
   During his trial last summer, the child talked about visits to
Poole's apartment on weekends but did not accuse him of any sexual
misconduct.
   Stephen O'Connell, a spokesman for Essex County District Attorney
Kevin Burke, said the girl had previously given investigators a
detailed account of abuse but ``froze up'' on the witness stand.
   Following his acquittal, Poole was reinstated to the police
department with back pay.
