<SECOND>AM-Shoplifting Sentence,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Given Probation, Ordered To Introduce Herself To Store Owners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Nosrat in 2nd graf cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge placing a shoplifter on five years
of probation also ordered her to introduce herself to merchants and
receive permission before shopping in their stores.
   Nosrat Smith, 51, of Norfolk faced up to a year in prison as a
repeat offender. But during sentencing Monday, Madison County Judge
Phillip Riley said there is evidence Mrs. Smith had been diagnosed
as suffering from kleptomania, a persistant impulse to steal.
   In asking the court for probation, Mrs. Smith's attorney, Ross
Stoffer of Norfolk, said, ``It's a situation where she has no
control. This is not a lady who is personally dishonest.''
   Deputy County Attorney Joseph Smith argued for a one-year
sentence, saying previous probation sentences had not kept Mrs.
Smith from repeat offenses.
   As conditions of probation this time, Riley ordered that Mrs.
Smith continue receiving therapy for kleptomania, introduce herself
to local merchants, shop with an adult escort, list any stores she
may have taken items from during the past two years, make
restitution to those stores, complete 200 hours of community service
work, continue to improve her English-speaking abilities and take a
lie detector test every six months.
