<FIRST>r a AM-SharkSuit     03-16 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shark Suit,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Denies Award to Shark Attack Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surfer bitten by a shark at a public beach has
lost a lawsuit against the county in which he charged that as in the
movie ``Jaws'' authorities failed to warn bathers because of a
holiday weekend.
   A jury deliberated 77 minutes Wednesday before rejecting a
$63,000 claim by Jonathan Popper against Dade County over a leg
injury he received in the May 21, 1983, attack.
   Popper, 22 when he was bitten, had argued that sharks were
sighted off Haulover Beach in the days prior to his attack, but no
warning was issued, even though lifeguards commonly post signs
advising of dangerous currents and poisonous jellyfish.
   ``Why would Dade County make the decision to expose people to
sharks rather than expose sharks to people?'' Popper's attorney Jay
Rothlein said in his summary. ``There can be only one reason _ there
was a holiday weekend coming up and sharks are bad for buisiness.''
   Assistant county attorney Ron Bernstein called those arguments
absurd.
   ``As this trial went on, it became apparent these men were trying
to orchestrate the sequel to ``Jaws,'' Bernstein said.
   In the Peter Benchley novel ``Jaws'' and the movie made from it,
the mayor of a fictional beach town fails to heed warnings about
shark dangers for fear it will hurt businesses awaiting a holiday
weekend crowd.
   Bernstein also noted that Popper had been surfing in the area for
10 years prior to the attack and was back surfing in the same spot
six months later.
</TEXT>
