<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     03-16 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hill Negotiators Detect Move Toward Compromise with Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional negotiators on the federal budget
said Thursday they detected a move toward compromise with the Bush
administration on which taxes should be raised.
   President Bush's recommended $1.16 trillion budget for fiscal
1990, which opens Oct. 1, proposed to bring in about $14 billion
through higher taxes, fees for government services, and sales of
government assets. The White House contends its specific proposals
don't violate Bush's ``no new taxes'' campaign pledge.
   Lawmakers said there was little chance of enactment for many of
the president's tax proposals, such as expanding the Medicare tax to
all state and local employees and cutting the capital-gains tax rate.
   ``I think they recognize the problem that the revenues that are
presented right now, that there's some difficulty in achieving
those,'' said Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House
Budget Committee. But it was important that the overall total of $14
billion still be raised, he said.
   Panetta and other congressional budget-writers met Thursday with
Bush budget director Richard Darman, Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady, and the senior members of Congress' tax-writing committees.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said the Democrats were not proposing to raise more money
than Bush proposed.
   ``I think they understand revenues are needed and they've
outlined a number of revenues,'' he said. ``My message was whatever
we do has to be credible, that we have to show the financial markets
that we've seriously addressed the problem'' of the deficit.
   ``Yes, I think there is some movement,'' he said, when asked if
progress was made in the meeting.
   Brady declined to answer reporters' questions. Darman said there
was no change in the administration's position but he did not want
to comment on what the lawmakers said.
   The Gramm-Rudman law mandates that the federal deficit, which is
expected to exceed $163 billion this year, be reduced to $100
billion in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   Panetta, in a breakfast speech at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
said the scope of the budget talks would be limited by President
Bush's willingness or unwillingness to discuss raising taxes. He
said taxes needed to be raised and spending cut to produce a serious
deficit-reduction plan.
   With the budget negotiators looking for places to cut spending,
pressure continued to increase spending.
   The Senate Armed Services Committee by voice vote approved a
recommendation that Congress adopt Bush's plan to increase military
spending next year to keep pace with inflation, and boost it 1
percent above inflation the next two years.
   Rep. Rep. G.V. ``Sonny'' Montgomery, D-Miss., chairman of the
House Veterans Affairs Committee, told a House budget task force
that spending on veterans' health programs must increase faster than
Bush is proposing.
   ``What the budget committee decides in the next few weeks will
probably be long remembered,'' he said, citing a crisis in the
system and the contribution he said the programs make to the
nation's defense.
   ``So if we must delay the procurement of one or two bombers in
order to insure that our veterans receive needed health care, then
we must do it. It's an easy choice for me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
