<DOCNO> AP890316-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 2051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HousingStarts     03-16 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Starts,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Sags After Mild-Weather Surge in January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction plummeted 11.4 percent in
February, the government reported Thursday, with analysts blaming
the sharp decline on harsher weather last month and the bite of
higher mortgage interest rates.
   The Commerce Department said new homes and apartments were built
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.5 million units last month
as the weather turned cold again after an unseasonably mild January.
   February's pace was down from a rate of 1.69 million units in
January, the highest level in nearly two years.
   Analysts said a longer-term slowdown in the housing market is
being caused by the steady upward climb of interest rates.
   ``We don't expect housing to suddenly fall off the cliff this
year, but we do expect it to progressively weaken with higher
interest rates,'' said economist David Berson of the Federal
National Mortgage Association.
   Interest on fixed-rate mortgages averaged 10.86 percent last
week, up from 9.84 percent a year earlier, according to a survey by
the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Initial rates on adjustable-rate mortgages were up even more
sharply, with the starting rate on a one-year ARM averaging 8.93
percent last week, up from 7.53 percent a year earlier.
   Kent Colton, executive vice president of the National Association
of Homebuilders, said rising interest rates were the ``dominant
factor'' behind the association's forecast for a 7 percent slowdown
in housing construction this year.
   An increase of 1 percent in the interest charged on a $100,000
mortgage adds $62 a month to a homeowner's payments, Colton said.
   ``That has a big impact on affordability,'' he said.
   Housing construction reached a post-recession peak in 1986, when
1.81 million units were built, then began sliding. Last year, the
level was 1.49 million units.
   Single-family homes were built in February at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.05 million units, down 13.1 percent from
the pace in the previous month and the biggest drop in five years.
   Apartment construction, meanwhile, was down 7.2 percent in
February to an annual rate of 453,000 units. Construction of
multifamily housing peaked in 1985 and then began a sharp slide,
largely the result of changes in the tax code that made such
projects less attractive to investors.
   Berson said recent data on apartment construction have been more
encouraging, suggesting that ``the depressing effects of tax reform
and overbuilding may be behind us now.''
   Housing permits, a bellwether of future housing activity, fell
6.8 percent last month to a rate of 1.4 million units after dropping
3.8 percent during January. February's decline in permits was the
biggest drop since a 9 percent fall in January 1988.
   ``The building permits data for both months suggest that rising
rates have taken a greater toll on housing than is suggested by the
starts numbers,'' said John A. Tuccillo, chief economist for the
National Association of Realtors.
   The Federal Reserve Board for a year has been nudging interest
rates upward in an effort to slow the economy and restrain
inflation. Most analysts expect interest rates to peak at mid-year
and then gradually decline again.
   Colton, of the homebuilders, said the Fed has been reacting to
``inflation paranoia'' and risks driving the country into a
recession by pushing interest rates too high.
   ``We think that at a minimum the Federal Reserve needs to be very
careful,'' Colton said.
   Housing activity dropped last month in all four regions of the
country, with the biggest decline in the Northeast, where starts
fell 22.6 percent to 229,000 units after surging 47 percent in
January.
   Construction was down 13.7 percent in the Midwest to 277,000
units, and fell 8.7 percent in the West to 400,000 units. In the
South, starts were down 6.8 percent to 592,000.
</TEXT>
