<FIRST>r w AM-TelemarketingFraud     03-16 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Telemarketing Fraud,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Steps Up Efforts to Combat Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Federal Trade Commission said
Thursday his agency has substantially stepped up its efforts to
combat telemarketing fraud.
   FTC Chairman Daniel Oliver told a House panel that the commission
``fully supports the objectives'' of legislation intended to bring
greater state resources to bear on telemarketing fraud.
   ``It is estimated that consumers may lose over a billion dollars
a year to telemarketing scam artists,'' he said. ``Recognizing this
threat, the commission has greatly increased its enforcement efforts
in this area in recent years.''
   Oliver testified that, since 1982, the FTC has opened more than
80 investigations of telemarketers and has brought 33 fraud cases in
federal court.
   ``In these cases, the commission obtained injunctions against
companies having aggregate sales of over $628 million,'' he said.
   Rep. Thomas A. Luken, D-Ohio, chairman of the Energy and Commerce
subcommittee on transportation and hazardous materials, said that
``a combined federal, state and private attack on telemarketing
fraud will bring quicker and more effective enforcement, save scarce
federal dollars and provide for more uniformity in enforcement.''
   He noted that in fiscal 1983 the FTC spent about $410,000 on
telemarketing cases. This rose to $2.3 million in fiscal 1988, and
the FTC has told the panel that its staff expects to spend $4.8
million on telemarketing investigations this fiscal year.
   Also testifying at Thursday's hearing was Nevada Attorney General
Brian McKay, who said that ``boiler room telemarketing is a
difficult problem for state law enforcement. These operators are
cheap and mobile. A boiler room essentially requires only leased
office space and a leased telephone.''
   McKay said Nevada ``has been a center for boiler room activity.
Over 50 percent of all complaints received by the Nevada Consumer
Affairs Division in 1987 concerned telemarketing. In 1988, over 54
percent of complaints were related to telemarketing.''
</TEXT>
