<FIRST>r a AM-PesticidePollution     03-16 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pesticide Pollution,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Pesticide Pollution At Denver Arsenal Is Hurting Wildlife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army report obtained by the Rocky Mountain News
says pesticide pollution at the Rocky Mountain Arsenal is harming
and killing wildlife, and posing a threat to humans who may eat the
tainted game.
   The report was based on a three-year study of the pollution's
effect on animals and plants at the 27-square mile superfund cleanup
site north of Stapleton International Airport, the newspaper said in
Thursday's editions.
   The report probably will determine the extent of the cleanup at
the site, a federal official said Wednesday.
   The report was compiled by Environmental Science and Engineering
Inc., an Englewood, Colo., consulting firm hired by the Army. It
found that:
   _ The flesh of game such as deer, rabbits and pheasants contained
contaminants in higher concentrations than U.S. Food and Drug
Administration levels for safe human consumption.
   _ Grasshoppers eaten by waterfowl and raptors contained mercury
and high levels of aldrin and dieldrin, pesticide components known
to cause thinning of egg shells and weight loss in birds.
   _ Dangerous levels of dieldrin in prairie dogs.
   _ A minimum of 20,000 waterfowl died during the 1950s after
landing on polluted ponds at the arsenal.
   ``Dead coyotes, owls and hawks found all over the Rocky Mountain
Arsenal had significant concentrations of pesticides in tissues,''
the report said.
   The Army manufactured chemical weapons at the facility from 1942
through the 1960s. Shell Oil Co. leased a portion of the arsenal for
pesticide production through the early 1980s. Waste from both
operations are known to have polluted groundwater, surface water and
soil at the facility.
   Use of the old arsenal has been a subject of controversy. Federal
and state officials, including Gov. Roy Romer, have suggested
turning the land into a park or wildlife preserve.
   Health officials have warned, however, that extensive cleanup
work must be completed in order for the animals to survive. If
contaminated water and soil are left untreated, pollutants will
continue to be absorbed by plants, ingested by insects and carried
up the food chain to large game animals, they say.
   ``If they continue to eat in contaminated areas, the problem is
only going to worsen,'' said Jeff Edson, a spokesman for the
Colorado Department of Health.
   The Environmental Protection Agency's project manager at the
arsenal said Wednesday the report will have an impact.
   ``It looks like the study might drive the decisions regarding how
clean it must be made,'' said Connally Mears. ``We'll pay particular
attention to the implications from the study to determine what needs
to be done to ensure protection of both public health and the
environment.''
   Army spokesman Bill Thomas in Denver said Wednesday the Army
didn't want to comment because the report was still in draft form.
</TEXT>
