<FIRST>r a AM-WhaleRescue     03-16 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whale Rescue,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fog Hampers California Whale Rescue Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Biologists stalking a 35-foot California gray
whale lost the migrating beast in fog before they could cut away a
tangle of fishing nets that could kill it, officials said Thursday.
   The northbound whale was spotted Tuesday off Dana Point with
netting wrapped around its flukes. Wildlife experts fear it will
eventually drown, said Joe Cordero of the National Marine Fisheries
Service.
   ``We don't know how much netting is trailing underwater.
Eventually, the whale will probably tire out and die,'' said
Cordero. Biologists participating in the rescue estimated the whale
was trailing about 70 feet of netting.
   A team of biologists from the Long Beach-based Whale Rescue Unit
followed the whale from Dana Point to the Crystal Cove area off
Laguna Beach, trying several times to get close and cut away the
nets. They lost it in fog near Newport Beach, 45 miles southeast of
Los Angeles.
   ``The whale is moving at a pretty good clip and the rescuers
couldn't catch up with it,'' said Cordero.
   Agent Ray Sautter, another National Marine Fisheries Service
spokesman, said it was extremely difficult to catch a whale moving
in the water.
   ``By the time you get a small boat over there they go down
again,'' Sautter said. ``It also stresses the animal and it may do
more harm than good.''
   Another California gray whale was reported ensnared in fishing
nets early Thursday off Point Conception, 120 miles northwest of Los
Angeles, said Sautter.
   ``We are trying to get someone up there and free it,'' he said.
   Whales began migrating from the warmer waters in Mexico earlier
this month and will continue their northward treks through May.
   ``Our real problem time is really next month and into May because
the cow-calf pairs are the last to leave,'' said Sautter. ``The
young frequently get separated and get into trouble.''
</TEXT>
