<FIRST>r w AM-BRF-SovietInspectors     03-16 0144</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF-Soviet Inspectors,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Arriving for Nuclear Inspection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has notified the United States
that two 10-member teams of nuclear weapon inspectors will conduct
``short-notice inspections'' at East Coast facilities starting
Friday, a Pentagon spokesman said Thursday.
   The inspections, authorized by the Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces Treaty ratified last year, will be the eighth and ninth such
inspections of the 20 allowed each side this year.
   ``In accordance with the INF Treaty, the teams will announce
which two sites they intend to inspect on Friday morning. And the
U.S. will then transport them to the sites where they will begin the
24-to-32 hour inspections,'' said Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard.
   The INF Treaty requires the United States and Soviet Union to
cease production, and destroy all existing stocks, of nuclear
missiles with a range of roughly 300 to 3,000 miles.
</TEXT>
