<HEAD>Democrats Will Draw Up Family Issues Agenda</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of more than a dozen House Democrats
will draw up a family issues agenda for their party and serve as
watchdogs to make sure President Bush keeps his promises in that
area, Speaker Jim Wright said Thursday.
   Wright said the group, led by Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., would
draw up a list of legislative goals for the 101st Congress,
including improvements in the Women's, Infants and Children feeding
program, child immunization, day care, Head Start, parental leave
and school dropout prevention.
   The group also will recommend an initiative aimed at barring
``inappropriate'' television programs during children's viewing
hours and enriching programming at those times, Wright said.
   The panel will give the House Budget Committee figures on
financing levels needed for such programs and will monitor the Bush
administration's progress in keeping campaign commitments for
education and other family programs, he said.
