<FIRST>r a AM-SpringBreak-Lawsuit     03-16 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spring Break-Lawsuit,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge: Christian Group Has Right To Distribute Literature On Beach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town of South Padre Island agreed
Thursday to allow a Christian group to pass out its tracts on the
beaches during spring break after a federal judge defended the
rights of the evangelists.
   Ministers had sued the resort town after an official sent them a
letter advising that distribution of the literature would violate an
anti-soliciting ordinance.
   U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela, however, advised the town at a
hearing that ``the public beaches are a public forum'' and that
handing out religious literature was protected by the Constitution.
   Ministers Kevin Pitt and Jerry Davis, and Davis' Street Reach
Ministries sued here Tuesday after receiving a letter from Gary
Becher, public works director for the island.
   In the Feb. 3 letter to Pitt, Belcher wrote, ``I interpret
preaching the word of God as soliciting and (it) therefore falls
under these ordinances.''
   After Vela's remarks, South Padre Island officials agreed to
leave the ministers alone as long as they did not solicit funds on
the beaches, said Paul Cunningham, town attorney.
   Vela said the agreement obviated the need for a restraining order
against the town.
   Attorney Jay Sekulow, representing the Christian group, said,
``It's unfortunate that it did have to come to court, because
frankly all that was involved was the distribution of free religious
literature and sharing Jesus on the beaches of South Padre Island.''
   Pitt, youth minister at Brownsville's non-denominational Word of
God Family Church, said the group wants to provide an alternative to
companies promoting beer and condoms to the 200,000 to 300,000
students expected to visit the island 25 miles northeast of
Brownsville during the month of March.
</TEXT>
