<FIRST>r a AM-MandatorySalute     03-16 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mandatory Salute,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Board Makes Flag Salute Mandatory Despite State Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YERMO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students will be required to salute the flag
under a school board decision directing district administrators to
delete a section of the state education code stating that a salute
is not mandatory.
   ``Communism comes from liberalism,'' Silver Valley Unified School
District board president Bob Woltman said Wednesday, adding that he
is ``tired of liberalism in public schools.''
   ``It's good for kids to honor our flag, as it shows love for a
country that offers the greatest opportunity in the world for people
of all faiths and races,'' said Trustee Carl von Badinski.
   A part of the education code allowing school boards to conform
with a federal court ruling on individual freedom states:
``Individuals shall not be required to participate in the salute to
the flag.''
   Trustees of the district in the middle of the Mojave Desert
ordered administrators to delete the paragraph when the policy comes
up for final board review on March 27.
   According to the district's assistant superintendent, William
Maybee, other provisions of the education code require elementary
school classes to begin each day with the Pledge of Allegiance and
``an appropriate patriotic exercise'' in secondary school classes.
   The U.S. Supreme Court in 1943 ruled that the government may not
compel citizens to salute the flag.
   ``Freedom of religion has nothing to do with saluting the flag,''
von Badinski said. ``In this country, people have the right to
worship any religion they desire, but it doesn't give them the right
not to salute the flag.''
</TEXT>
