<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-DemocraticAgenda     03-16 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democratic Agenda,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Democrats Privately Debate Legislative Agenda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats debated in private on Thursday
over a broad agenda for the 101st Congress that pledges not to
``oppose the (Bush) administration automatically, but to propose new
policies and pursue them cooperatively.''
   A 10-page draft ``agenda for action'' that served as the basis
for the closed-door discussion shied away from specifics on many of
the major issues confronting Congress. It omitted any mention of the
possible use of higher taxes to reduce the deficit, and skipped over
details of any effort to resolve the savings and loan crisis.
   At the same time, it called for enactment of a lengthy list of
legislation that seemed certain to spark combat with the Bush
administration, ranging from a hike in the minimum wage to a program
of national volunteer service, strengthened environmental
enforcement and widespread, affordable health care.
   It also called for an expanded commitment to education, research
and development, agriculture and trade.
   ``It is not a political platform,'' said the draft that produced
debate two days in a row at closed party caucuses just off the
Senate floor. ``Neither can it include every item of interest to
every senator, or accommodate every difference of emphasis and
viewpoint.''
   Democrats initially hoped to make a public release of the
material on Friday, but officials indicated the date was likely to
slip past the two-week Easter recess that begins at the end of the
week. They said some changes had been made in the draft, a copy of
which was made available to The Associated Press, but declined to
discuss them.
   Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, who was in charge of the effort
to produce the agenda, said the discussion had been a ``healthy
debate,'' that centered in part on the concerns by some senators
that the draft was short on specifics. Other senators said Democrats
might try to come up with a second, more concrete set of promposals
later in the year.
   The proposed agenda grew out of a commitment by Sen. George
Mitchell of Maine, the newly elected majority leader, to consult
widely with other Democrats and produce a set of legislative
guidelines for Democrats to adhere to during the two-year Congress
that convened in January.
   Mitchell appointed Daschle to coordinate the effort, and the
result of Daschle's conversations with Democratic senators was
reflected in the draft agenda that he and the majority leader
presented to the 55-member Democratic caucus on Wednesday and
Thursday.
   ``With this report we offer the president our hand,'' said the
draft. ``We do not expect the administration to accept every item.
We seek only cooperation and progress.''
   It says that the job for Democrats in Congress is ``not to oppose
the administration automatically, but to propose new policies and
pursue them cooperatively.''
   The draft agenda committed Democrats to ensuring a prosperous
economy, protecting the national security, preserving the
environment and defending ``essential family values,'' and outlined
specific legislation to accomplish each of those goals.
   But on many of the most contentious issues, Democrats shied away
from specifics in their draft. ``It is imperative that we
significantly reduce budget and trade deficits,'' they said. But the
only two specific steps mentioned for deficit reduction are a demand
for ``realistic economic projections'' and insisting on ``accurate
calculations of budget numbers.''
   When it comes to the faltering savings and loan industry, the
draft agenda called for taking legal action against those who
committed fraud and abuse and urged unspecified ``tough new
regulatory reform.''
</TEXT>
