<FIRST>r w AM-Marshals'Audit     03-16 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marshals' Audit,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marshals Defend Against Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Marshals' Service said Thursday a
critical audit commissioned by Attorney General Dick Thornburgh
didn't accurately represent the agency's operations.
   U.S. Marshals Service spokesman Stephen Boyle said the finding
that the agency's financial management system was only ``marginally
adequate'' was ``not supported by the specific findings in the
report.''
   ``That language is taken from their coversheet, their
generalization of their findings,'' Boyle said.
   He said the study actually found that ``files and paperwork were
not located in a form or fashion the auditors thought was
desirable.''
   ``That didn't suggest there was anything unaccounted for,'' Boyle
said.
   Neither Boyle nor the Justice Department would release the audit,
which was disclosed in The Washington Post.
   But Boyle offered a point by point rebuttal of the findings
reported in the Post, saying: ``to the extent that the auditors
found nothing to suggest failure in meeting our operational
requirements, nothing suggesting fraud or misuse of funds is a very
positive result.''
   ``An audit is an exercise to find fault. They found fault but
what they found we think was of minimal signficance to our principal
mission,'' he said.
   ``We consider the entire audit a declaration that the Marshals
Service is in extremely good shape except for the fact that some of
the auditors who did the audit would like to see us with a larger
bureaucracy.''
   Boyle cited a finding that the agency's procurement staff still
had not begun efforts recoup overcharges by private security firms
that were uncovered in a 1987 audit.
   The staff responsible for collecting the money overcharged by
security firms in eight judicial disticts had postponed that effort
while renegotiating contracts with private contractors hired to
guard courthouses and prisons.
   ``It's not as matter of the money disappearing,'' Boyle said.
``The bills are in hand. We simply have to devote the contracts
personnel to go back and pursue the collections which we will be
doing.''
   A finding that several of the agency's small airplanes used for
hauling prisoners were not designed for that purpose ``was a
particularly good example of the auditors reflecting bad
information,'' Boyle said.
   Seven of the 13 small planes are being refurbished so they can be
used to transport prisoners, Boyle said. The Federal Aviation
Administration gave the Marshals Service the surplus aircraft last
year, he said.
   The audit also found the Marshals' Service has not conducted
adequate background checks of people hired to protect courthouses or
guard prisoners.
   Boyle said private security firms are responsible for checking
the backgrounds of guards it furnishes under contracts. Off-duty
policemen hired to guard prisoners in hospitals are usually provided
by local police departments, he said.
   ``It isn't a matter of people walking in off the street in police
uniforms,'' he said. The gaurds are hired as result of ``formal
contacts with official representatives'' of local police departments.
   The audit also found the agency once leased an airplane for
$10,000 to transport director Stanley E. Morris and two other people
from Washington to Oklahoma City after a Marshals' Service plane
broke down.
   Boyle said the plane was leased because Morris and seven other
senior officials could not have traveled by commercial airlines in
time to attend the ceremony.
</TEXT>
