<FIRST>r a AM-People-Chapman     03-16 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Chapman,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orlando Woman Named Disabled American Of The Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An activist who got Florida to pass a law
waiving tolls for disabled drivers has been named 1989 Disabled
American of the Year. ``This is the most important recognition I've
had,'' Beverly Chapman said Wednesday. She was Miss Wheelchair
America in 1977 and has received numerous local awards.
   ``There are 38 million disabled Americans, many of them
outstanding individuals, and to be selected above all the others is
overwhelming,'' she said.
   Chapman, 40, has been paralyzed almost totally by muscular
dystrophy. She breathes with the help of a respirator attached to
her wheelchair and drives a van equipped with hand controls.
   In 1986, she began running tollbooths in an effort to get the
highway authority to accommodate disabled drivers who had trouble
tossing coins into toll baskets.
   Last year, the Legislature passed the Bevery Chapman Act, which
waives tolls for severely disabled drivers at all state tollbooths.
   The award will be presented May 10 in Tampa at the annual
convention of the President's Committee on Employment of People With
Disabilities, with Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole as the keynote
speaker.
