<FIRST>r w AM-ArcticDrilling     03-16 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arctic Drilling,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Alaska Oil Exploration Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee on Thursday approved
legislation that would allow oil exploration in the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge but no drilling leases until after a
government-financed study considering alternative energy sources.
   The Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee defeated an
amendment offered by Sens. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo., and Dale Bumpers,
D-Ark., that would have delayed any possibility of oil exploration
until a comprehensive energy conservation plan was submitted to
Congress by the interior secretary.
   The energy plan language the committee accepted was presented by
Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., and is identical to a compromise
included in the same legislation last session.
   While the previous bill also passed the energy committee, it
failed to get to either the House or Senate floor for a vote. The
House has not taken up the measure yet this session.
   Opponents say the United States needs to have a plan for saving
energy and finding alternatives to fossil fuel before it starts
drilling for more oil, especially in a part of the country that is
the breeding ground for one of the largest herds of migrating
caribou in North America and home to many other forms of wildlife.
   Supporters say oil exploration is necessary for national security.
   ``The closest we've come to nuclear war is in the Middle East to
protect our oil supply,'' said Hatfield.
   But he also spoke of a need for conservation, saying: ``No matter
what the actual oil find in Alaska, our national energy needs will
require the development of alternative sources of energy. ... The
spotlight trained on energy conservation efforts during the late
'70s and early '80s has suffered a blackout.''
   His amendment requires the departments of interior and energy,
the Council on Environmental Quality and the National Academy of
Sciences to prepare a national energy plan within 15 months after
the bill is enacted.
   The plan must consider all potential energy sources and projected
energy demands. Bids for oil leases could be taken while the study
was under way, but no leases could be granted until Congress had had
six months to study the report.
   The amendment also requires that the energy secretary establish a
grant program to promote research, development and marketing of
conservation techniques and alternative fuels. This program would
get its money from the sale of oil found in the refuge.
   Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., called the Bumpers-Wirth proposal
``a killer amendment'' because it not only said oil exploration must
be delayed until the energy plan was established, but that pursuing
oil exploration would take another act of Congress.
   The American Petroleum Institute applauded the passage of the
bill, saying the refuge may provide as much as 1 million barrels of
oil to the United States every day for as long as 30 years.
   The institute said more than 6 billion barrels have been produced
at Prudhoe Bay since 1977 when drilling began there. Another 3
billion barrels are still believed to be available from Prudhoe.
   Oil companies want to start drilling at the refuge, which is just
east of Prudhoe, so that oil will continue to flow from Alaska when
the fields in Prudhoe are dry.
</TEXT>
