<FIRST>r w AM-US-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0618 03-16 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Official Encouraged by Baker's Remarks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 8 grafs, bgng ``Meanwhile, the,'' with Redman remarks on
Arab League</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of the PLO on Thursday welcomed
what he said were encouraging signs of a new willingness by the
United States to meet Palestinian demands for a Middle East
settlement.
   Nabil Shaath, an adviser to Palestine Liberation Organization
leader Yasser Arafat, cited remarks made this week by Secretary of
State James A. Baker III and other developments.
   ``The last three days show a lot of progress _ small progress,
but important, significant progress. Many people are so skeptical
they are not even willing to see that progress.
   ``The future is going to come up with all kinds of surprises for
all of us _ happy surprises,'' Shaath told reporters at the National
Press Club.
   Baker on Tuesday told a House subcommittee that if talks between
Israel and non-PLO Palestinians do not prosper, ``I suppose we would
then have to see negotiations between Israelis and representatives
of the PLO.''
   The next day, however, he told the Senate Appropriations
subcommittee on foreign operations that an Israeli-PLO dialogue was
difficult to foresee but should not ``categorically'' be ruled out.
   Shaath, one of three PLO officials who attended a seminar in New
York last weekend, has been meeting with private groups in
Washington and was seeing at least two members of Congress.
   He said that he had had no contact with U.S. officials during his
visit but that he took heart from Baker's remarks.
   ``So far there has been very little substance,'' said Shaath.
   But he said that talks between the PLO and the United States
would resume March 22 in Tunis and that the PLO had been assured
U.S. Ambassador Robert H. Pelletreau would be able to discuss
substantive issues. He said these would include the Palestinians'
demands for the right to self-determination and for a Palestinian
state.
   Shaath said that President Bush had told Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak in Tokyo last month that the U.S.-PLO talks in Tunis would
become substantive. ``We've had assurance in Tokyo in the meeting
that President Mubarak held with President Bush where they discussed
really nothing but the Palestinian question,'' Shaath said. ``Mr.
Bush committed himself to Mr. Mubarak then that the dialogue would
be resumed and would be made substantive, and we learn now that this
is going to be the case on the 22nd.''
   ``I think we are very close'' to U.S. recognition of the
Palestinian right to self-determination, Shaath said.
   Shaath said he wasn't discouraged by Israeli Foreign Minister
Moshe Arens' criticism of Baker's initial remarks or Arens'
hard-line rejection of talks with the PLO.
   Shaath said the Israelis would not be able to ignore the
Palestinian uprising, or ``intifadeh,'' and would have to come to
terms with Palestinian demands.
   Meanwhile, the United States, citing latest battles in Beirut,
urged the Arab League on Thursday to continue its reconciliation
attempts between Moslems and Christians in Lebanon.
   ``The United States government is deeply concerned over the heavy
exchange of shelling and consequent loss of life'' in eight days of
warfare which have left 49 people dead, said State Department
spokesman Charles Redman.
   ``We urge all sides to exercise restraint and to avoid civilian
casualties at all costs,'' he said.
   ``We call on General Aoun and Doctor Hoss to cooperate and
coordinate directly with one another, to work together to restore
and invigorate Lebanon's legitimate national institutions,'' Redman
said.
   Michel Aoun heads a Christian military Cabinet that has been
vying for legitimacy with a rival Moslem Cabinet under acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss since President Amin Gemayel's term ended Sept.
22.
   Minutes before stepping down, Gemayel named Aoun to head an
interim military Cabinet, but his appointment was rejected by
leftists and Moslems who declared allegiance to Hoss.
   Redman said the latest fighting threatens to destroy the Arab
League's peace initiative in Lebanon.
   ``The United States actively supports this initiative and
encourages the Arab League to continue its effort,'' he said.
</TEXT>
