<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1718EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Greece     03-16 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Shake-up Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou on Thursday
accepted the resignations of all 54 ministers in his Cabinet,
preparing for a government shake-up in a political crisis over a
bank scandal.
   The Socialist government also proposed a law allowing more
representation for smaller parties and raising the parliamentary
majority required to form a government, making governing coalitions
more likely.
   The main conservative party said the law is aimed at keeping it
out of power.
   The Cabinet reshuffle will be the second since the $200 million
fraud, forgery and embezzlement scandal involving a fugitive Greek
banker broke five months ago, leading to the resignations of eight
Cabinet ministers.
   It will also be Papandreou's 16th Cabinet reshuffle in eight
years.
   Government sources indicated Papandreou intends to use the
reshuffle to purge the Socialist government of ministers implicated
in the scandal and attract waning support for his governing
Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK).
   Papandreou's party has come under heavy fire for its handling of
the Bank of Crete scandal, in which Papandreou and senior government
officials have been accused of taking payoffs.
   A statement issued by government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos
said the new Cabinet would be appointed and sworn in Friday.
   The draft electoral law is to be submitted to Parliament on
Friday, and lawmakers are to vote on it within the next few weeks.
   The main conservative opposition New Democracy Party accused the
government of trying to hamper its efforts to win a clear majority
in the upcoming June elections.
   ``The government has admitted that it has ceased to contest power
and its exclusive concern is how to prevent us from acquiring an
overall majority,'' New Democracy leader Constantine Mitsotakis said
in a statement.
   Interior Minister Akis Tsochatzopoulos said the proposed
electoral law would allow smaller parties to have more seats in the
300-member single-chamber Parliament.
   According to Kostopoulos, the premier asked his ministers to
resign in order to go ahead with the reshuffle.
   ``All the ministers have been asked and verbally submitted their
resignations,'' the spokesman said.
   Banker-publisher George Koskotas, 34, was indicted in the scandal
and fled Greece on Nov. 6. He was arrested in the United States,
where he is jailed awaiting a decision on extradition requested by
Greece.
   The banker has alleged that Papandreou and other senior Socialist
officials received millions of dollars in payoffs and authorized
plans to loot millions from the Bank of Crete while he was its
chairman.
   The draft bill proposes a new proportional system for electing
deputies and increases the margin needed to elect a government from
45 percent of the vote, the previous level, to about 48 percent, an
electoral analyst said.
   The analyst said on condition of anonymity that the new law would
open the way for coalition governments.
   Under the country's present reinforced proportional system, large
political parties are heavily favored in seat distributions.
   In the 1985 elections, the system gave PASOK 45.8 percent of the
vote and 161 seats. New Democracy received 40.8 percent and 126, the
Greek Communist Party got 9.89 percent and 12 seats, and the
Eurocommunists polled 1.84 percent and one seat.
   Political defections have left PASOK with 154, the conservatives
with 111 and the Communists with nine. The Eurocommunists retain
their one seat and the rest are independents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890316-0152 </DOCNO>
