<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103-Chronology     03-16 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103-Chronology,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight 103: Chronology of Warnings, Terrorist Threats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flight 103 Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some key dates in the chronology of
warnings and terrorist threats surrounding the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   OCTOBER _ West German authorities conducting raids discover a
radio-cassette player containing plastic explosives and a barometric
timing device that could be set to detonate a bomb at a given
altitude. Thirteen alleged members of the Syrian-backed Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command guerrilla
group are arrested.
   NOV. 18 _ The date Trans World Airlines says the Federal Aviation
Administration told it of the bomb found in West Germany.
   NOV. 22 _ The British Department of Transport issues a bulletin
via telex to ``relevant security authorities'' reporting discovery
of bomb in West Germany. It now says that warning would have been
circulated by the Federal Aviation Authority to U.S. airlines and
other agencies that would need to know.
   DEC. 5 _ The U.S. Embassy in Helsinki is warned in a telephone
call of a plot to bomb a Pan Am airliner on a Frankfurt-U.S. flight
during a two-week period in December. The Federal Aviation
Administration issues an ``intelligence alert'' that there might be
a bomb attempt against a Pan Am flight from Frankfurt.
   DEC. 9 _ U.S. authorities notify the British government of the
Dec. 5 warning to the U.S. Embassy in Helsinki.
   DEC. 19 _ The British Department of Transport repeats its Nov. 22
warning, with additional details and a photo of the radio-cassette
recorder as it would look if it was wired to explode. The bulletin
is addressed to all British airports plus British and American
airlines, and El Al of Israel, Air India and South African Airways.
   DEC. 21 _ Flight 103 is destroyed over Lockerbie, Scotland,
killing all 259 people aboard and 11 on the ground.
   DEC. 23 _ A British official says the government issued no public
warnings about the Dec. 5 threat made against Pan Am flights because
the information was considered confidential. British airports were
not told about the information passed on by U.S. authorities,
apparently because the threat did not specifically mention Britain.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   JAN. 17 _ The date Pan Am says it received a memo by mail from
the British Department of Transport dated Dec. 19.
   MAR. 15 _ The British Department of Transport first announces it
alerted airlines and airports on Dec. 19 about a possible terrorist
attack with precise details similar to the device that destroyed
Flight 103.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
