<FIRST>r w AM-Koop-Abortion     03-16 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koop-Abortion,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weiss: Questions About Koop Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., said Thursday he was
concerned that Surgeon General C. Everett Koop appears to have
misstated the extent of evaluation that went into Koop's decision
not to issue a report on the health effects of abortion.
   At a hearing of the Government Operations subcommittee on human
resources, Weiss and other members of the panel questioned Koop for
more than two hours, mostly about Koop's conclusion that there is
``insufficient scientific and statistical evidence on which to base
an unimpeachable report.''
   The report had been requested by former President Reagan, but in
a Jan. 9 letter to the then-president, Koop said 250 studies dealing
with the psychological aspects of abortion have been reported in
scientific literature.
   He said in the letter that ``all of these studies were reviewed
and the more significant studies were evaluated by staff in several
of the agencies of the Public Health Service ... and were found to
be flawed methodologically.
   ``In their view and mine, the data do not support the premise
that abortion does or does not cause or contribute to psychological
problems,'' his letter said.
   However, under questioning, Koop acknowledged that only a report
by a pro-life group received written evaluations by reviewers and
that all other studies referred to health service experts for review
were only discussed orally.
   ``I am disturbed by what seems to be a conclusive statement based
on evaluations of studies which turn out not to have been ...
reduced to writing, (that were) discussed orally, whatever that
means,'' said Weiss, chairman of the panel.
   Koop, who is a staunch abortion foe, said he reviewed some of the
articles himself, but he said could not detail how much time he
spent on the task. But, he said, as examples of flawed
methodologies, most of the studies looked at only a short period of
time after abortion, from three to six months.
   ``I know very well from my own experience that many of the
problems that do occur after abortions ... occur at a considerable
time after abortion,'' he said.
   ``I know that women, many times for a period that seems
inordinately long to me, have apparently no reaction adversely to
the psychological effects of abortion and then something triggers it
in their mind and they become severely depressed or anxious or
sometimes incapable of carrying on their work,'' he said.
   But Koop said scientific data is lacking on the topic.
   Pro-life groups maintain that many women who have abortions
suffer many years later from a stress disorder similar to that
suffered by Vietnam War veterans.
   Weiss also said he was concerned about allegations made by a
former Centers for Disease Control scientist who said his work at
the Public Health Service center in Atlanta was ``censored.''
   David A. Grimes, now a professor of obstetrics and gynecology at
the University of Southern California School of Medicine, told the
subcommittee he left the Atlanta facility in the summer of 1986
after twice having papers he was having published ``censored''
because of their references to abortion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
