<FIRST>u a AM-LaserBaby 1stLd-Writethru a0666 03-16 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Laser Baby, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0666,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lasers Shrink Facial Tumor on Two-Year-Old British Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `After the ...' with 5 grafs with father's comments,
girl's reaction; Picks up 6th graf, `Later surgery ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The small birthmark on newborn Faye
Watling's left cheek grew so large so fast, her parents sometimes
feared waking her in the morning for fear they'd see the deformity
had spread across her entire face.
   But Jayne and Brian Watling said doctors in the Skelmersdale,
England, area where they live warned that corrective surgery had to
wait until Faye turned 7, despite the danger that delay could
destroy the sight in her left eye.
   News about pioneering laser surgery being done in similar cases
with children at the Palo Alto Medical Clinic gave them hope for
their daughter, who turns 2 on March 24.
   And a series of heartwarming, albeit wacky, fund-raising stunts
on Faye's behalf gave them the money for the series of operations,
which climaxed on Thursday when Dr. David Apfelberg used a laser to
cut away the bulk of the orange-sized tumor, called a hemangioma.
   After surgery at Stanford University, Faye was wrapped in a head
bandage covering her face.
   ``She's dressed up like an Egyptian mummy,'' Watling said from
his daughter's side in the recovery room. ``But the growth is gone.
There's no growth there anymore.''
   And how did Faye deal with the experience?
   ``I don't think she understands too well,'' Watling said. ``All
she knows is that any time someone in white comes near her, it
hurts.''
   Additional reconstructive surgery can be done in another six
months or so, Apfelberg said, adding that ``she's always going to
have some residual.''
   Later surgery will be required to reconstruct the left side of
Faye's face and cover the scar.
   About one in every 500 to 800 children have some form of
birthmark, Apfelberg said, although 90 percent disappear by the age
of 6 to 8. The cause is unknown, he said, although it probably
occurs during the first three months of pregnancy when a fetus
develops its facial features.
   But the doctor said Faye's hemangioma, which at one point almost
completely covered her left eye, is ``one of the most severe that
we've seen.''
   British doctors lack the technology and training for the laser
procedures pioneered and developed at the Palo Alto clinic in the
1970s, Apfelberg said.
   Mrs. Watling said that when she heard about the California
techniques, she and her sister, Maureen Gledhill, immediately began
looking for ways to collect the $425,000 necesssary for the surgery
and other treatments.
   From that point, she said, things ``snowballed.''
   British sailors in the middle of the Atlantic chipped in,
long-haired women staged public head-shaving exhibitions in exchange
for donations and inmates in a local prison played 24-hour badminton
games. The prison warden had himself locked up for 24 hours, while
other officials staged a mock breakout and women prisoners gave Fay
money they had saved to buy a VCR. American Airlines donated airfare
for the family's trips to Palo Alto.
   ``If people hadn't been so generous, there was no possibility of
us coming here,'' Mrs. Watling said.
   In three other treatments, Apfelberg sealed some blood vessels to
halt tumor growth and start the shrinking process as Faye's body
began reabsorbing the cells. The operation also caused 90 percent of
the mark to change from red to a normal skin color.
   Additional treatment did more of the same, and Faye was fitted
with a pressure face mask in England that, worn 18 hours a day, also
worked to achieve the same end.
   Thursday's laser surgery had been set for mid-January, but
doctors discovered Faye was anemic and sent her home to gain
strength.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
