<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 2207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-MexicoDrugs     03-16 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mexico Drugs,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helms Says Mexico Does Little to Cut Drug Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jesse Helms accused Mexico on Thursday of
``a dismal record'' in helping the United States battle illicit
drugs, launching a bid to deny the country any U.S. economic aid or
trade benefits.
   ``It appears that Mexico is planning to conduct business as
usual. And up to this time, Mexico has been in the business of
protecting drug kingpins,'' Helms, a North Carolina Republican.,
charged.
   Mexico is this country's top source for heroin and its No. 2
source of marijuana, according to statistics compiled by the
Department of State.
   Helms' comments came as he introduced a measure in the Senate to
remove Mexico from a list of nations granted continued U.S.
financial aid because they have been ``fully cooperating'' with the
U.S. government in its war on drugs.
   The measure is co-sponsored by Sens. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.;
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and Trent Lott, R-Miss.
   Under the law, President Bush is required to formally certify
that each nation, while it may be a major drug producer or transit
point, is cooperating against the war on illicit narcotics.
   In a report accompanying the list, the State Department earlier
this month praisd Mexico for its efforts in the drug war, even
though Secretary of Sate James A. Baker III admitted that the
international war on illegal drugs was ``clearly not being won'' and
might even be ``slipping backwards.''
   The State Department cited Mexican President Carlos Salinas'
``strong public stance'' against drugs, as well as the efforts of
his new deputy attorney general. But corruption was seen as a
continuing problem.
   Last year, the Senate voted 63-27 to punish Mexico for its lack
of cooperation in the battle against drugs, but the House killed a
similar measure.
   ``I am very concerned that the entire certification process has
become a sham,'' Helms said. ``I do not accept the argument that
decertification of a non-cooperating country will hurt U.S. economic
or diplomatic interests. That is pure poppycock.''
   Helms charged that Mexico has had a ``dismal record of
non-cooperation in the drug war in the past year.''
   He faulted Mexico for, among other things, corruption at the
highest levels of government, for failing to allow overflights and
hot-pursuit actions by U.S. law enforcement aircraft, for denying
access to air surveillance flights, for denying access to bank
records to assist drug investigations and for its failure to
prosecute the principal suspects in the murder of U.S. drug agent
Enrique Camarena.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890316-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-NorthTrial     03-16 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Trial,1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Trial Told Reagan Approved Air Drop of Weapons to Contras</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates in top 12 grafs with McFarlane's closing testimony,
picking up in 4th graf pvs, As McFarlane, trims at end</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in Oliver North's trial was told
Thursday of a daring plan, said to have been approved by
then-President Reagan, that involved an air-drop of recoilless
rifles to help the Nicaraguan Contras sink arms-carrying ships.
   Whether the air drop was ever attempted was not brought out in
the fifth and last day of questioning North's former White House
boss, Robert C. McFarlane. After he left the stand, the jury was
dismissed until Monday.
   McFarlane said that although he had pleaded guilty to four
misdemeanor counts of withholding information from Congress he felt
he should not have been charged.
   ``I felt quite passionately about the fact that I had not
willfully lied to people,'' he said. But he added that ``it was
quite clear I withheld information'' and ``I had to accept the
consequences of what I had done.''
   Prosecutor John Keker, referring to papers introduced while
MFarlane was on the stand, said, ``What those documents show is that
during the period of the Boland Amendment you and the NSC did a lot
of things to aid the military activities of the Contras.''
   ``Yes,'' said McFarlane. The Boland Amendment, in force between
1984 and 1986 prohibited U.S. help to the guerrillas.
   The jury learned in the course of McFarlane's testimony that _
despite Boland and with North's encouragement _ money was solicited
from other countries, tactical advice was offered the Contras,
efforts were made to open a new military front in Nicaragua, plans
were drawn to shoot down Soviet-made helicopters and consideration
was given to seizing and sinking a ship carrying ammunition to the
Nicaraguan government.
   Also, McFarlane testified, Reagan approved $110 million worth of
inducements to Honduras in exchange for giving sanctuary to the
Contras and allowing military aid to pass through.
   ``All this was done because the president said `keep the Contras
together, body and soul?''' Keker asked.
   ``Yes,'' said McFarlane.
   He also replied ``yes'' when asked if people who were likely to
be called before Congress were kept ignorant of certain information
so they wouldn't have to lie under oath.
   Approval by Reagan of the air-drop plan was noted by North
co-defendant John M. Poindexter on a ``top secret'' Oct. 30, 1985,
memo drafted by North, according to a description offered in court
by the chief defense lawyer.
   As McFarlane examined the memo on the witness stand, attorney
Brendan Sullivan said that Poindexter had signed the approval line
and written ``President approved.''
   Sullivan read portions of the memo and told the jury that under
the line ``what to tell the president'' were these words: ``We
intend to air drop intelligence along with two ... recoilless rifles
which will be used to sink one or both of the arms carriers.''
   McFarlane said recoilless rifles are ``designed to knock out a
very hard target such as a tank, a bunker or a plane on the ground.''
   ``Or sink a ship as it says here,'' added Sullivan.
   Sullivan asked McFarlane: ``You understand Colonel North had the
ability to air-drop weapons and intelligence of this sort and this
was part of his job at the National Security Council?''
   ``Yes,'' McFarlane said.
   McFarlane, who was Reagan's national security adviser at the
time, said the memo did not come to him. Poindexter was then
McFarlane's deputy and later became his successor. North, a Marine
lieutenant colonel attached to the National Security Council, worked
for both men.
   North is on trial on 12 charges including lying to Congress. His
defense has been designed to convey to the jury that he had
authority for all the actions charged against him as crimes.
   Meanwhile on Thursday, Poindexter was in another courtroom for
housekeeping matters in his case. He faces trial on charges similar
to North's, and U.S. District Judge Aubrey Robinson said he hoped
that trial can get under way in summer or early fall, after North's
ends.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh told the judge he does not
know yet whether the government will follow its action in the North
case and drop two key charges _ conspiracy, and theft of government
property _ that are still lodged against Poindexter.
   McFarlane resigned his job as Reagan's top national security aide
on Dec. 4, 1985, although he undertook a trip to Tehran with North
the following May to press Iran for the release of Americans held
hostage in Lebanon. The trip was a failure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
