<FIRST>u i AM-India-GandhiInquiry     03-16 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Gandhi Inquiry,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Lawmakers Walk Out Of Parliament Over Assassination Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition politicians angrily walked out
of Parliament on Thursday over a secret report allegedly linking a
leading government aide to Prime Minister Indira Gandhi's murder.
   All but one of the 93 opposition lawmakers in the 245-member
Rajya Sabha, the upper house of Parliament, decided to boycott
proceedings through Friday. They walked out after Chairman Shankar
Dayal Sharma refused to ask the government to release the report on
the 1984 slaying.
   Some of the 63 opposition members who were suspended Wednesday
from the Lok Sabha, or lower house, for demanding disclosure of the
report met with President Ramaswamy Venkataraman and urged him to
direct the government to turn over the report to Parliament.
   The government has said the report will remain classified, citing
national security interests. Parliament passed a law in July 1986,
five months after the report was completed, empowering the
government to suppress sensitive reports.
   Government sources said on condition of anonymity that the report
has been seen only by the slain leader's son and successor, Rajiv
Gandhi, and two senior Cabinet ministers who have taken an oath of
secrecy.
   The opposition's demand was first raised Tuesday after the Indian
Express, the country's largest English-language newspaper, published
excerpts from the report and sought to link a powerful government
official to Mrs. Gandhi's assassination four years ago.
   The Bombay-based newspaper quoted the inquiry as saying that
Rajendra Kumar Dhawan, Mrs. Gandhi's personal secretary for more
than 20 years, had ``consciously or unconsciously ... facilitated
the commission of a crime.''
   Dhawan, 52, left the post after the assassination but was brought
back into the government last month as a key aide to the prime
minister.
   Dhawan has refused comment on the allegations, but other
government officials have said he is innocent of any wrongdoing.
   But in their memorandum to the president, opposition leaders
argued the report apparently ``contains findings adverse to Mr.
Dhawan. ... Otherwise, the question of his exoneration would not
have arisen.''
   The inquiry, ordered by the government and conducted by Supreme
Court Judge M.P. Thakkar, ran parallel to police investigations into
the assassination. It was submitted to the government in 1986.
   Opposition members in the upper house shouted slogans and pounded
on their desks Thursday, demanding the government make the report
public.
   When Sharma refused to consider the issue, opposition legislators
walked out and said they would not return this week. They then
marched to the Presidential Palace and delivered copies of Tuesday's
Indian Express to the president and demanded he order the government
to release the report.
   The Indian Express, which has a nationwide circulation of 1.1
million, is frequently critical of Rajiv Gandhi.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot and killed by two Sikh bodyguards on Oct.
31, 1984, as she walked through the garden of her New Delhi
residence to a television interview.
   One of the guards was killed in a shootout with other guards. The
other was convicted of murder and hanged Jan. 5, along with a third
Sikh who was convicted of conspiracy.
   In its report, the Indian Express said the government report
accused Dhawan of altering the time of Mrs. Gandhi's appointment
with the television crew and that Dhawan, who was walking with Mrs.
Gandhi, fell back ``in the nick of time as they were approaching the
scene of the assassination.''
   The government has said Mrs. Gandhi was killed in revenge for an
army raid she ordered in June 1984 on the Golden Temple, the Sikhs'
holiest shrine.
</TEXT>
