<FIRST>r a AM-InmateDeath     03-16 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inmate Death,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney Hopes Lawsuit In Inmate's Death Answers Questions Officials
Won't</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit being filed in response to the
beating death of a jail inmate could shed light on allegations that
a ``goon squad'' of corrections officers routinely beat prisoners, a
lawyer said Thursday.
   ``There's a lot of unanswered questions in that lockup,'' said
Patrick G. Patel, attorney for the family of Arnaldo Ortega. ``I'm
curious as to how they're going to answer why no medical treatment
was given to Mr. Ortega for between 16 and 18 hours.''
   Two corrections officers and a deputy warden at the Hudson County
Jail were charged Wednesday with Ortega's murder. They remained
Thursday in the Bayonne City Jail in lieu of $50,000 bail each.
   Ortega, 28, died Saturday at University Hospital in Newark. He
was brought there two days earlier in a coma, and a coroner's report
showed he was beaten about the head, arms and body.
   County Prosecutor Paul M. DePascale has acknowledged that Ortega
did not receive medical treatment for 16 hours after the three
guards allegedly beat him for about 20 minutes with a blunt object.
   DePascale said, however, that the lack of medical treatment did
not warrant criminal charges and he would not comment on the delay
in taking Ortega to the hospital.
   Patel said he filed a notice to sue at the county clerk's office
Thursday.
   State law mandates a six-month waiting period between the notice
to sue and the actual filing. Patel said he will seek to subpoena
corrections officers who had any connection with Ortega. Testimony
could help expose abuses, he said.
   The death prompted outrage in the community, where some have come
forward with stories of a ``goon squad'' that has existed for years.
   County Executive Robert C. Janiszewski said there is no evidence
that the group exists but said his office would investigate.
   ``I'm getting five or 10 calls an hour from people telling me
they know of the goon squads and that they've been beaten,'' Patel
said. ``Maybe this suit can help do something about it.''
   Omar Aziz, a Moslem chaplain at the jail for eight years, told
the Jersey Journal that inmates have repeatedly complained to him
about abuse by corrections officers, particularly during the
midnight to 8 a.m. shift.
   The targets of the beatings are usually Hispanics and blacks,
Aziz said.
   The three officers charged worked the midnight shift, DePascale
said.
   Corrections officers Thomas Murphy, 39, and David Michael Dumers,
35; and Deputy Warden Raymond Murray, 52, all of Jersey City, were
arrested after surrendering to DePascale. Murray was in charge of
the shift at the time.
</TEXT>
