<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0654 03-16 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Resume Military Airlifts To Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs with Tass reports, Soviet accusations; picks
up 10th pvs `Observers believe...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORTEN HVAAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union said Thursday it has
resumed flying arms to Afghanistan because of a guerrilla offensive
around Jalalabad, the first major battle since the Red Army
completed its withdrawal Feb. 15.
   Moslem guerrillas claimed Thursday they had shot down two more
aircraft in heavy fighting for Jalalabad, a strategic eastern city
that is the nation's third-largest. The communist government claimed
470 insurgents killed in the previous 24 hours.
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri Vorontsov said the airlift resumed
Wednesday, a month after the Red Army left the Kabul government to
fight the insurgents on its own.
   He said the weapons included medium-range Scud B missiles, which
are said to have been fired from Kabul at guerrilla positions around
Jalababad, 75 miles to the east and 40 miles from the Pakistan
border.
   Sources said at least 40 Ilyushin-76 transport planes had landed
at thge Kabul airport since Wednesday with military supplies and
food.
   Vorontsov accused Pakistan of sending hundreds of its own
soldiers with the guerrillas in the intense, 10-day battle for
Jalalabad.
   ``We have discussed the situation with the Pakistanis and they
know what our reaction will be if their involvement continues,'' he
said. ``We are not threatening the Pakistanis, but they must stop.''
   Pakistan supports the guerrillas, along with the United States,
but denies any of its soldiers are fighting in Afghanistan. The
Foreign Ministry called Vorontsov's allegation ``fictitious.''
   In Moscow, the official news agency Tass said Pakistani forces
were coordinating the attack on Jalalabad and forcing teen-age
refugees to take up arms.
   ``Units of Pakistani mercenaries were ordered to carry out forced
mobilization starting from age 14 in the Afghan refugee camps near
Peshawar,'' Tass in a dispatch from Kabul.
   ``Eyewitness accounts indicate that hundreds of refugee families
have decided to return to Afghanistan on learning about the order,''
it said. ``Protests against the arbitrary actions of the Pakistani
military flared up in several camps.''
   Tass said Afghan insurgents and Pakistani soldiers fired on
protesters, killing seven people and wounding 12 others.
   A separate Tass dispatch from Kabul accused Pakistani
intelligence officers of coordinating the guerrilla attack.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting in Afghanistan after a communist
coup in April 1978. Soviet military forces arrived in December 1979,
and an estimated 115,000 were in the country when the U.N.-mediated
withdrawal began May 15, 1988.
   Observers believe a guerrilla victory at Jalalabad, along the
main highway from Pakistan to Kabul, could lead to the fall of the
capital.
   The guerrilla-run Afghan News Agency said insurgents downed a
helicopter gunship near Jalalabad's television station and an
airplane outside the city on Wednesday.
   The latest guerrilla claim brought to seven the number of
government aircraft reported destroyed this week in the fight for
Jalalabad.
   There was no immediate comment from the Afghan government, and it
was not possible to confirm the claims.
   Kabul radio claimed Thursday that 470 insurgents were killed in
the last 24 hours around Jalalabad, bringing the total for two days
to 1,030. Guerrillas call the Kabul claims widely exaggerated.
   It said only six of its troops were killed in the Jalalabad
fighting in the last 24 hours. It also said the guerrillas fired
``thousands of rockets and artillery shells'' into Jalalabad during
this period, killing four civilians and injuring 18.
   The guerrilla-run Afghan News Agency said 25 Afghan troops were
killed and 32 captured in Jalalabad on Thursday.
   Guerrillas have overrun the city's most important garrison,
Samarkhel to the east, and were closing in on the airport.
   But Afghan soldiers retaliated with unexpectedly aggressive
aerial and artillery bombardments that reportedly have stalled the
guerrillas' progress.
   Fighting centers north, west and south of the city, according to
reports reaching Pakistan.
   Leaders of the U.S.-supported guerrillas have predicted an early
collapse of the Kabul government in the absence of its Soviet
backers, but President Najib has insisted his forces are strong
enough to survive.
</TEXT>
