<FIRST>r a AM-Shuttle-BushCall     03-16 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle-Bush Call,0878</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Invites Discovery Astronauts To White House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush talked with the
Discovery astronauts Thursday from the Oval Office on a
television-telephone connection that let him see the spacemen.
   Here is a transcript:
   Bush: Hello.
   Discovery commander Michael L. Coats: Good morning, Mr. President.
   Bush: How are you, sir. We just called up to congratulate you and
your crew of Discovery. Sitting next to me is our vice president who
is now head of the space council and who, incidentally, will be down
in Houston in about two weeks. But what I really wanted to do is to
congratulate you and then hear about how things are going. We are
certainly proud of the mission.
   Coats: Thank you very much, sir. We have a very fine orbiter and
a very fine crew here and an awful lot of people on the ground
worked very hard to get this flight off, the first one of your
presidency, and the first one of very many to come.
   Bush: It looks to me like you made that crew clean up. I'm
watching you. I can see you sitting here in the Oval Office. Amazing
technology. There are five of you looking pretty clean and pretty
fresh. How is everyone feeling on the flight?
   Robert C. Springer: We're all feeling very well, Mr. President.
It's been an exciting time for us. Of course three of us on the
flight are rookies in space. I think the cleanliness and the smiles
you see is just a reflection of the fun that goes along with the
hard work. We're doing an awful lot of good things, but we're really
enjoying what we're doing.
   Bush: We're following it carefully and glad that the TDRS
(Tracking and Data Relay Satellite) had a successful operation
there. How's the camera? How's that IMAX camera gonna be? (IMAX is a
70mm camera used to photograph the Earth.)
   John E. Blaha: The IMAX camera has been working out really well,
sir. We're getting a lot of great film that will show a lot of
people around the world how fragile the planet Earth is in this big
vastness of space and maybe help everybody to work to improve that.
   Bush: Well, it's a good focus. There's so much interest today on
the global environment and I think a lot of people will see just
from your important mission the contribution that space exploration
can make to the world's environment. We're grateful on that. A
couple of more questions, I was interested because of the history of
this, about the student experiments and how that was going.
   James P. Bagian: Well, Mr. President, the student experiments are
going very well. Both of them are very well thought out. They have
been going just as we expected. ... The data is looking very good
and I think the students will have a lot good information to get out
when we get back. (A student experiment by John C. Vellinger of
Lafayette, Ind., studies effects of weightlessness on chicken
embryos. Another by Andrew I. Fras of Binghamton, N.Y., uses injured
rats to study the effect of space on healing bones.)
   Bush: It is an inspiration to the Americans, I'll tell you, all
of us. Today's pioneers. We're seeing you right now pointing the way
for the young Americans to build our nation's future. Listen, all of
you down there at NASA, I heard what Mike said, and while we're on
the air to space, let me say to everyone at NASA that you have our
strong support. I know I speak for the vice president. The space
program, especially space station Freedom, is an investment in our
future. We living in a tough budgetary times, but I am determined to
go forward with a strong active space program. And I want to
congratulate you commander Coats and all of them for this wonderful,
wonderful mission. We look forward to your safe return. And I think
it wonderful that two Marines can get along with a guy from the Navy
and the Air Force and a civilian. That shows a broad minded approach
to life in space. Did you read that?
   James F. Buchli: Yes sir, we did. Obviously the Marines can get
along with the other services, but just in case, we have them
outnumbered. There's two of us on board. (Buchli and Springer are
Marine colonels. Coats is a Navy captain, Blaha an Air Force
colonel, and Bagian is a civilian physician.)
   Bush: (Laughing) I got the message. Sorry to start it going up
there. But listen, congratulations and best wishes. You've been an
inspiration to all of us. So long and God bless.
   Coats: Thank you, Mr. President, and give our regards to Mrs.
Bush. Tell her we are flying something for the new first lady.
   Bush: She'll be thrilled. You better come up here and give it to
her personally.
   Coats: That would be nice, sir.
   Bush: You're in. You're invited right as of now. So when you get
back, head this way. Over and out.
   Coats: Yes sir. Have a good day.
</TEXT>
