<FIRST>r w AM-OlderWorkers     03-16 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Older Workers,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Metzenbaum: Corporations Shouldn't Make Older Workers Sign Away Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Older workers have been coerced into signing
away their rights as corporations try to get rid of better-paid
employees in favor of younger, lower-paid newcomers, three early
retirees told a Senate hearing Thursday.
   ``It is difficult for me to believe that an employee who works in
America today ... who has been a loyal and successful worker for one
employer for a long time, can be fired from his or her job and
forced to sign away their rights under the law,'' said Kenneth
Lancaster of St. Paul, Minn.
   ``If I had known more about the equal rights laws, and had known
on Dec. 31, 1983 that my replacement was 28 years old, I would not
have signed anything,'' he told the Senate Subcommittee on Labor.
   The subcommittee, headed by Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, is
considering Metzenbaum-sponsored legislation to forbid employers
from asking older workers to waive their rights under the law as a
condition of taking advantage of early retirement incentives.
   ``Three-fourths of employers don't use waivers. Why do the other
25 percent have to?'' Metzenbaum said.
   A General Accounting Office survey of 60 ``Fortune 100''
companies showed 24 percent of the companies that had early
retirement incentives required workers to sign waivers in order to
get beefed-up benefits. The use of waivers has tripled over the past
10 years, the GAO's Joseph Delfico told the committee.
   The chairman of the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission told
the panel no new law is needed because of regulatory action taken in
1987 aimed at accomplishing the same goal.
   But the GAO survey showed 1987-88 was a peak period for the use
of waivers.
   The companies surveyed by GAO, the investigative arm of Congress,
reported they used the waivers ``to avoid having terminated
employees file claims and lawsuits after receiving enhanced benefits
from exit incentive programs,'' Delfico testified.
   Lancaster said he was one year from being vested in his pension
plan when the car dealership for which he was service manager fired
him after 12 years on the job. In a New Year's Eve meeting, the
dealership offered six months' severance pay in exchange for a
signature on a release of all claims, Lancaster said.
   ``I was given no reason for my termination. They had already
hired someon in my place,'' Lancaster told the panel. ``I was told I
had to sign the release letter immediately in order to get the
severance pay.
   ``I asked to take the documents home to review them, but they
said no. I asked for time to talk to an attorney, but they said I
didn't need to because the dealership's lawyers had already gone
over everything,'' he said.
   Robert Patterson, a draftsman, said he was told by his manager at
Xerox Corp. there was a ``99 percent sure chance you will be laid
off'' if an early retirement offer was refused.
   ``I had only seven working days to make a decision,'' Patterson
said.
   Gerald Clay of Peoria, Ill., said he was offered a year's salary
if he signed documents waiving his rights under the Age
Discrimination Employment Act.
   ``What happened to me shouldn't happen to anybody,'' he said.
   A law partner in a national firm testified that Metzenbaum's
proposal could hurt companies that haven't discriminated.
   ``The real effect of (the bill) in individual cases would be to
create a system whereby disputes could not be settled without the
intervention of EEOC or a court, and would put an end to many
internal company grievance programs that have been developed over
the years to deal with employee complaints,'' said attorney Cathie
A. Shattuck, who's represented both employers and disgruntled
employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890316-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 2048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WishesEnd     03-16 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wishes End,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Non-Profit Group For Terminally Ill Children Closes Office Amid Questions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who founded a national group that
grants wishes of dying children has closed an office and dropped
from sight, raising questions about the status of the charity and
the way she handled donations.
   Better Business Bureau officials say they haven't spoken with
Mary Girardin since December, shortly before she closed the two-room
offices of A Child's Wish Come True Inc.
   ``I don't know where she is,'' said Barbara Sinnott, president of
the Better Business Bureau of Central New England.
   In 1985, the last year the charity filed financial statements
with the state, the group reported it took in $400,000 but gave only
one-third of the money to terminally ill children, Sinnott said. The
BBB recommends that 60 percent of revenues should go to the stated
purpose of the charity.
   ``We have just consistently reported that it has not measured up
to the recommended amount of giving,'' she said.
   Girardin apparently has disconnected her telephone in Worcester
and could not be reached for comment by The Associated Press on
Thursday.
   Sinnott said she sent three letters to Girardin asking for
updated information on the organization but never received the
information.
   The group has in the past sponsored trips for ill children to
Disneyworld.
   Several groups such as A Child's Wish Come True have sprung up in
the past decade. While most of the groups are legitimate, the
powerful fund-raising appeal of brightening a dying child's last
days has posed some problems, charity officials said.
   ``Unfortunately, people have very open hearts and when you have a
cause that sounds good and they get any kind of good publicity and
people don't check, then they tend to open their wallets,'' Sinnott
said.
   In Pennsylvania, a group called the Sunshine Foundation was
investigated by the state attorney general's office, which
criticized the foundation's handling of $34,000 in fund money.
   No charges were filed, but a new executive director was selected
for the charity after a meeting between the foundation's board of
directors and state officials.
   ``They're making progress towards bringing their accounting
procedures in line with those of a responsible, not-for-profit
corporation,'' Deputy Attorney General Mollie McCurdy said.
   In Texas, the attorney general's office filed a civil suit in
1986 against a group called Rainbow Foundation, after an
investigation showed little of the money raised went to children,
said Rose Ann Reeser, deputy attorney general in charge of the
charitable organizations division.
   ``The problem that we have with those organizations, as with a
lot of organizations like this, (is) you can't track down your
money,'' Reeser said. ``Anytime you deal with a dying child, it's a
very compelling thing.''
   The suit against Rainbow Foundation was dismissed after its
founder died, Reeser said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
