<FIRST>r w AM-BeefDispute     03-16 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beef Dispute,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Heads Study Idea of Shipping U.S. Meat to Commissaries
in Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If European countries don't end a ban on
America's hormone-treated beef, U.S. military commissaries there
could stop buying Europe's meat, two House committee chairmen said
Thursday.
   Reps. Kika de la Garza, D-Texas, chairman of the Agriculture
Committee, and Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the Armed Services
Committee, said they are looking into the idea of shipping U.S. beef
and dairy products to the 131 U.S. commissaries on military bases in
Europe instead of letting them buy European products.
   ``The United States shouldn't be buying from European sources
while the Europeans are closing their markets to our products,''
said de la Garza. ``The armed services and agriculture committees
will take up this matter at a hearing this spring,'' he added.
   Aspin said it may be more practical now than in the past to ship
U.S. beef and other products to Europe in light of a decline in the
value of the dollar.
   ``The committees will be examining the transportation system,
pricing and funding for shipment of these products,'' said de la
Garza.
   The European Community has been refusing to accept meat from
livestock treated with growth hormones, while U.S. officials say the
meat is not dangerous to humans.
   Last year, military commissaries sold 46 million pounds of
European beef for $55 million, said Aspin and de la Garza. Before
the European ban on hormone-treated beef, the United States was
selling about $100 million worth of beef in Europe.
</TEXT>
