<FIRST>u w AM-Hastings 1stLd-Writethru a0749 03-16 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs on Metzembaum vote after 5th graf pvs, Sen.
Howard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Won't Drop Impechment Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate refused Thursday to dismiss
impeachment charges that federal District Judge Alcee L. Hastings of
Miami conspired to get a $150,000 bribe and later lied about it at
his trial.
   The Senate voted 92-1 against dismissal of 15 of the 17 articles
of impeachment against the 52-year-old Miami judge. The lawmakers
then voted 93-0 against dismissal of another article.
   Hastings had not sought dismissal of still another charge, that
he disclosed information obtained from a federal wiretap and thus
torpedoed a federal investigation of Miami-area corruption.
   The Senate acted after 2{ hours of deliberation on the
52-year-old judge's move for dismissal of the charges on grounds
that he had been acquitted in a 1983 trial and could not get a fair
hearing in the Senate now in any case because too much time has
passed.
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, voted in favor of dismissal on
the first of Hastings' two motions, which would have dropped the
first 15 of the articles of impeachment.
   Metzenbaum was not reached immediately for comment, but press
secretary Nancy Coffey said the senator had constitutional qualms
about an impeachment trial on charges of which Hastings already had
been acquitted.
   ``Those were the counts on which he was acquitted and the senator
had constitutional concerns about double jeopardy,'' Coffey said.
   The Senate's decision sets the stage for an impeachment trial
expected to take as much as six weeks before a special Senate
committee.
   The panel's proceedings are to be videotaped for viewing by
senators who lack time to sit through the lengthy presentation of
evidence. The case then will come back to the Senate floor for a
vote on whether to remove Hastings from the bench and take away his
$89,500 annual salary.
   Hastings himself on Wednesday took the Senate floor to make a
personal appeal to the lawmakers to drop charges that he plotted to
obtain the payoff and then committed perjury to win his 1983
acquittal.
   ``I proclaimed my innocence then as I have from the outset and as
I do now,'' Hastings told the lawmakers.
   Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, one of a panel of House prosecutors,
told the Senate however that the judge's double-jeopardy defense did
not apply to impeachment trials and that Hastings should forfeit his
job because of ``his inexcusable breaches of the public trust.''
   In contrast, the senators deliberated behind closed doors on
Thursday and voted on Hastings' dismissal motion without any public
debate.
   Hastings stands accused of conspiring with Washington attorney
William Borders in 1981 to reduce from three-year prison sentences
to probation the punishment of two brothers, Frank and Tom Romano of
Miami. They were convicted in Hastings' court of skimming from a
Teamsters union pension fund loan.
   In return, Hastings and Borders were to receive $150,000.
   The Romano brothers, both of whom have since died, refused to pay
any bribe, but the FBI mounted a sting-type operation and arrested
Borders pulling out of a suburban Virginia motel with a garment bag
containing $125,000 handed to him by an undercover agent
masquerading as Frank Romano.
   Borders was convicted of conspiracy and went to prison.
   The House voted the articles of impeachment 413-3 on Aug. 3.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
