<DOCNO> AP890316-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1852EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     03-16 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0681</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palm Sunday Procession Is Canceled in Jerusalem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The traditional Palm Sunday procession in
Jerusalem was canceled on Thursday because of the Palestinian
uprising in the Israeli-occupied lands.
   On the political front, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's spokesman
said Thursday that Shamir has been holding secret meetings with
Palestinian leaders who do not belong to the PLO. Spokesman Avi
Pazner confirmed a report on Israel TV that such meetings were under
way.
   Israeli Arab leaders meanwhile called for a general strike by
Israel's 810,000 Arab residents on March 30 to support the
rebellion, which has killed at least 396 Palestinians and 17
Israelis since it began on Dec. 8, 1987.
   Violence continued Thursday, with 40 Palestinians reported
injured in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, most of them
beaten by Israeli soldiers. The territories have been under Israeli
control since the 1967 Middle East war.
   A spokesman for Father Michel Sabbah, the first Arab Catholic
patriarch of Jerusalem, said the Palm Sunday parade was called off
this year, as it was last year, ``because it is not possible to have
it with all the schools closed.''
   Schools in the West Bank and Gaza Strip have been closed since
last year by Israel, which considers them flashpoints for the
uprising.
   Schoolchildren traditionally march in the parade, which
commemorates Jesus' triumphal entrance into Jerusalem amid waving
palm fronds borne by his disciples.
   ``In the churches, everything will be held as usual,'' said the
spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers destroyed three Palestinian homes and
sealed two others to punish anti-Israeli activists.
   That touched off demonstrations in which Palestinian youths
burned tires, raised outlawed Palestinian flags and hurled rocks at
troops, Arab reports said.
   Soldiers opened fire at several protests, and one 16-year-old
Palestinian was reported wounded. Ahli Arab and Shifa hospitals in
Gaza City reported treating 35 Palestinians for beating injuries.
   The dynamited homes belonged to Palestinians arrested this month
for allegedly belonging to an assassination team linked to Palestine
Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat, the army said.
   Three West Bank Palestinians were shot and wounded in
stone-throwing clashes with soldiers, including two teen-agers shot
in the legs in Kabatiya, Arab reports said.
   A Palestinian shop in Nablus and one in Ramallah were set ablaze
by fellow Palestinians for selling Israeli-made goods, police said.
No injuries were reported.
   Leaders of the uprising have repeatedly called on store owners to
boycott Israeli goods.
   In Gaza Strip's Jabaliya refugee camp, troops late Wednesday
night bulldozed the home of Ibrahim Abu Mor, a Palestinian lawyer
wanted by Israeli authorities for allegedly heading Islamic Jihad, a
fundamentalist Moslem group, the army said.
   The United States objects to the destruction of homes as undue
punishment, especially when the activists have not been tried in
court.
   The strike call to Israeli Arabs was issued at a meeting in
Shaferam. Arab Israeli leaders said businesses will be closed and
rallies will be held on March 30 ``to protest against Israeli
government discrimination against Arab citizens and to show
solidarity with the people in the occupied territories.''
   The March 30 date commemorates a 1976 incident in which six Arabs
were killed in the Galilee in clashes over land expropriations by
Israel.
   Pazner meanwhile told The Associated Press Thursday that Shamir's
meetings with Palestinians started last December.
   ``Its purpose is to have a dialogue with non-PLO Palestinians. He
has been meeting with non-PLO Palestinians, and he will continue to
do so,'' Pazner said.
   He declined to identify the Palestinians, saying ``it could
endanger their lives.''
   His disclosure came a day after Shamir's foreign minister, Moshe
Arens, reacted strongly and negatively to suggestions by U.S.
Secretary of State James A. Baker III that Israel consider talks
directly with the PLO if other peace avenues fail.
   Arens is in the United States in advance of an expected April
trip by Shamir.
</TEXT>
