<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Party 1stLd-Writethru a0698 03-16 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Party, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Adopts Agricultural Reform, Elects Congress Members</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 14 grafs with more Ligachev quotes, other detail;
picks up 12th pvs `Soviet television...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party approved sweeping agricultural
reforms Thursday, giving farmers long leases on state land to
produce more of the meat, fruit and fresh vegetables for which
housewives now wait in line for hours.
   An average Soviet citizen now consumes about half as much meat
and fruit as an American, but up to double the sugar and potatoes.
   Yegor K. Ligachev, the ruling Politburo's man in charge of farm
policy, promised the people diets ``up to generally recognized
standards of nutrition'' by 1996.
   ``We are not promising something that we cannot achieve,'' he
told his first news conference with foreign reporters. ``We will be
able to change the food situation for the better.''
   The meeting of the 300-member Central Committee also elected the
party's 100 members to the Congress of People's Deputies, a new
2,550-seat legislative body that will meet for the first time in the
spring. President Mikhail S. Gorbachev was among them.
   Gorbachev had proposed that farmers be given long-term leases on
land so they would become more efficient. He also urged that they be
allowed to decide what to plant on the land rather than having the
bureaucracy decide.
   Western analysts have said the new system will do little good
unless lease-holders are allowed to choose which crops to plant, set
their own prices and make other decisions.
   Ligachev said leases could be signed for any period of more than
five years and be passed on succeeding generations of a family. He
said no one would be forced to lease land and that the giant state
and collective farms would remain the backbone of the Soviet
agricultural system.
   ``Radical changes in rural life and production relations should
be carried out on a purely voluntary basis ... without any kind of
force or repressive methods,'' said Ligachev, 68, who is widely
regarded as a conservative force in the Politburo.
   Setting targets for leasing would only encourage strong-arm
tactics to fulfill the plans, he said.
   In statements at the meeting, leasing was only one of many
methods for improving production. He said the new approach to
agriculture also would include self-financing, and greater democracy
in rural life.
   State and collective farms still will dominate agriculture, he
said. Some Soviet press reports have come close to advocating they
be scrapped, but Ligachev said none of the 12 Politburo members
favor it.
   ``Any proposal that leads to abolishing state and collective
farms has no foundation whatsoever,'' he declared.
   Even when land is leased to individuals and groups, he said,
state and collective farms will oversee production, ``proceeding
from the needs and possibilities of society.''
   Soviet television showed an hour-long report on the meeting,
including speeches by local and Moscow-based officials echoing
Gorbachev's calls for agriculture.
   The meeting abolished the giant superministry in charge of
agricultural policy, and Gorbachev interrupted its chief, Vsevolod
Murakovsky, who favored the traditional system in which all local
regions are required to send a percentage of their harvest to
central authorities.
   The television, breaking with its ususal practice, cut off its
report before Gorbachev gave his final statement to the plenum.
Ususally Gorbachev's statements in televised forums constitute the
main part of the TV report.
   In a nearly two-hour speech Wednesday, Gorbachev painted a
devastating picture of Soviet agriculture, with chemically spoiled
land, investments gone sour and destruction of systems prevalent in
the 1920s.
   He said food shortages were inadmissible. ``The shortage of food
creates social tension and generates not merely criticism but actual
discontent.''
   He said conditions in villages in some regions were so bad that
emigration to the cities had reached a ``critical level.''
   When Josef Stalin forced agricultural collectivization in the
1930s on a populace that was 80 percent agrarian, millions of
peasants were deported to Siberia and other remote regions or fled
to cities. Catastrophic famine ensued.
   Ever since, farmers working for state-owned farms have generally
delivered their yields to market at fixed prices to meet quotas set
by the state bureaucracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890316-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Quayle     03-16 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Says He's No Spiro Agnew</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle said Thursday that
despite his sometimes harsh rhetoric _ which has contrasted with
President Bush's _ he is not a lightning rod for Bush as Spiro Agnew
was for President Nixon.
   Playing on a memorable campaign exchange between himself and
Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen, Quayle said he
had asked Bush about the Agnew comparison, made by more than one
Quayle watcher.
   Bush paraphrased Bentsen's line during last fall's vice
presidential debate attacking Quayle for comparing himself to John
F. Kennedy, Quayle said in a quip that drew appreciative laughter
from his audience at the National Press Club.
   ``He put his hand on my shoulder. He said, `Dan, I knew Spiro
Agnew. Spiro Agnew was a friend of mine, and you're no Spiro
Agnew,''' Quayle said.
   But Quayle reiterated his attack on the Senate for its rejection
of Bush's defense secretary nominee, John Tower, saying that ``smear
information'' was used.
   Last week, Quayle went further, saying in an Indianapolis speech
that the Senate's rejection of Tower signaled a legislative attack
on the power of the presidency and a return to the tactics of the
McCarthy era.
   Bush's own rhetoric about his first major defeat in Congress
since becoming president was decidedly milder. Bush said the episode
was ``history'' and he wanted to move forward with good relations.
   Quayle said that when he made the accusation in Indianapolis, he
was not performing the Agnew tough-guy role to Bush's nice guy.
Agnew drew fire with his pungent speeches that often criticizing the
media and liberals in general.
   But Quayle said senators who knew Tower and had served with him
relied on other witnesses and unsubstantiated rumors instead of
their own knowledge of the man. And he offered another theory about
Tower's defeat.
   ``I do believe we're starting to set a new standard. What brought
down John Tower was probably more on the likeability issue, that he
simply was not well-liked. I don't believe that is a criteria to be
used for whether the president ought to have the right to have his
person as secretary of defense.''
   Quayle also defended the new administration's pace, which has
been criticized as too slow.
   ``We're succeeding an administration of our own party at a time
when the country is in good shape ... so we're certainly not going
to be stampeded into doing things for the sake of doing them soon,
or quickly, or to show `momentum' or some such thing.''
   ``Quick fixes are often bad fixes,'' Quayle added.
   Quayle also criticized politicians' ``frantic efforts to gain
press attention,'' but said he was not referring to the media-wise
campaign that elected him and Bush last fall.
   He said the political process is distorted when ``the need to
make the 7 o'clock news can lead politicians to announce initiatives
that really aren't well thought out _ initiatives that might well
make the headlines, but might not be very good for the health of the
country.''
   Asked about the Bush-Quayle campaign's acknowledged management of
the daily news, packaging events and keeping the candidates away
from reporters to keep from cluttering the canned message, Quayle
said he was not talking about campaigns but added: ``You've got a
certain message you want to get across.''
   In his speech, Quayle said he was criticizing ``the way frantic
efforts to gain press attention and produce sound bites can distort
our political process by elevating form over substance, and image
over reality.''
   As to the blistering press reports about his own background that
percolated throughout the campaign, the vice president said he
probably benefited from it in the long run. He said the intense
scrutiny was to be expected because he had been a little-known
senator outside his home state of Indiana when Bush picked him for a
running mate.
   ``You're an open target to criticism by your opposition. That is
the way we conduct our campaigns,'' he said. ``It's healthy to see
how one musters the scrutiny. I believe I have emerged a stronger
and better person because of it. It's an experience that had a
meaningful purpose for me as being the vice president of the United
States.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
