<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     03-16 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunners Blast Port, Set Ship, Warehouse Afire; U.S. Urges End To
Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem gunners blasted Beirut's port
Thursday, setting a cargo ship and a warehouse afire in fierce
battles with Christian forces around the capital. No casualties were
reported.
   Artillery duels in Beirut and in the mountains above the capital
coincided with a nationwide strike staged by Moslems to mourn
victims of the previous week of fighting, which police said left 49
people killed and 161 wounded.
   A Syrian official was quoted as saying an Arab League committee
has canceled a third meeting between rival Moslem and Christian
Cabinets to end the violence.
   A police spokesman said Moslem gunners blasted the Beirut port
with 25 rockets, setting fire to a cargo ship that tried to return
from open waters during a lull in the fighting.
   The spokesman identified the stricken vessel as ``The Angie
Wipp'' and said he could not give any details about its flag, owners
or what kind of cargo it carried.
   One of the port's warehouses also took a direct rocket hit during
the attacks, said the spokesman, who cannot be further identified
under standing regulations.
   Christian gunners fired a barrage of 155mm howitzer fire at the
Moslem residential districts of Sabra and Kasskass abutting Beirut's
dividing Green Line, said a police spokesman.
   Sniper fire and occasional grenade blasts crackled across the
ruins of the old commercial district.
   The police spokesman said the new hostilities in Souk el-Gharb,
15 miles southeast of Beirut, erupted shortly before sundown between
Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's forces, which hold the
town, and Druse fighters on nearby hills.
   The town commands a network of mountain roads leading from Druse
territory to the Christian heartland north and northeast of the
capital.
   Aoun's forces appeared to be following through with his stated
intention to drive Syria's 40,000 troops out of Lebanon. Militiamen
of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party are
backed by Syria.
   The Christian-run Ad-Diyar newspaper on Thursday quoted an
unidentifed Syrian official as saying that Damascus ``has not yet
taken a decision to retaliate against Gen. Aoun ... But if Aoun
should continue his provocations, retaliation will be decisive.''
   The official was quoted as saying Arab League peace talks will
not be held. The fighting was sparked by a March 6 air-and-sea
blockade Aoun clamped on illegal harbors run by Moslem militias
south of Beirut.
   The blockade angered Jumblatt, whose party runs two illegal port
facilities. Jumblatt vowed to bombard the Christian-run Beirut port
as long as the blockade of Druse harbors was maintained.
   Lebanon's commerical sea traffic was virtually halted and Beirut
International Airport, the nation's only air gateway, has been shut
since Saturday.
   Aoun, 53, heads the Christian cabinet that has been vying for
legitimacy with acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss' Moslem cabinet.
   The rival governments have been in place since Parliament failed
to elect a successor to President Amin Gemayel when his term ended
in September.
</TEXT>
