<FIRST>r a AM-SweatLodge     03-16 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweat Lodge,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Rules Utah Must Allow Sweat Lodges For Indian Inmates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-year legal battle over the state's
refusal to allow ceremonial sweat lodges for Indian inmates at Utah
State Prison ended Thursday when a federal judge ruled the ban is
unconstitutional.
   Applause broke out in the packed courtroom and American Indians
from several different tribes chanted and pounded drums outside
after U.S. District Judge J. Thomas Greene struck down the ban in a
bench ruling on motions for summary judgment.
   ``I'm grateful. The words are kind of hard to come by at this
time because the feeling is so good,'' said George A. Roybal, an
Assiniboine Sioux who, as a Utah prison inmate in March 1987,
initiated the lawsuit with five other inmates.
   ``What this thing is all about is us trying to help our people to
help themselves,'' he said.
   The Utah Department of Corrections had contended the sweat lodge,
which tribal officials contend is central to purification and
ceremonial rites dating back 40,000 years, threatened security
because the lodge must be dark and enclosed.
   But Greene cited two U.S. Supreme Court rulings and the success
of sweat lodges in 19 other state prison systems and two federal
penitentiaries in rejecting arguments that the small willow and
canvas structures posed a security risk.
   The judge said the prohibition was unreasonable and resulted in
``the Native American religion not being accommodated to the extent
other religions are.''
   ``The sweat lodge will simply be another chapel located within
the prison,'' Greene said.
   Michael O'Brien, an attorney representing the American Civil
Liberties Union, said guards could monitor ceremonies and prison
officials could impose limitations such as searches and requirements
that the lodge be dismantled after each service.
   ``The record is clear that 19 other states and the federal prison
system accommodate these sweat lodges without risk to security,''
O'Brien said.
   Telephone messages left at the office of Joseph Tesch, the
associate Utah attorney general who defended the case for the state,
were not immediately returned.
   The ACLU was one of several groups that provided legal or moral
support to the inmates' cause. The Native American Rights Fund and
the giant Navajo Nation also joined the plaintiffs in the lawsuit,
while the Central Salt Lake City Council of Churches, representing
pastors from six denominations, urged Gov. Norm Bangerter to
intervene on the inmates' behalf.
   Prison officials had earlier offered to allow a modified sweat
lodge equipped with a window and mechanical heating, instead of the
required heated rocks, but plaintiffs' attorney Danny Quintana
called the suggestion ``blasphemous.''
   Greene concurred, telling Associate Utah Attorney General Joseph
Tesch, at one point, ``It's like saying to a Christian you can have
a ceremony but don't mention Christ.''
   Attorneys for the Navajo Nation, which manages sweat lodge
programs for 500 inmates in federal and state systems, argued that
the ceremonies are vital to rehabilitation.
   The sweat lodge provides a link between the incarcerated Indian
inmate and his tribe, and the program administered by the Navajos
offers drug and alcohol counseling in addition to spiritual
guidance, said Navajo lawyer Lee Bergen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890316-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1951EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-16 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Breezy Day For Much of the Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gusty winds blew across much of the nation Thursday with dust and
sand swirling up to 60 mph in Nevada.
   Southwest winds over the Central Plains blew up to 43 mph at
Russell, Kan., Thursday morning with visibilities briefly as low as
4 miles in blowing dust.
   Northeast winds were behind a cold front over southern portions
of Nebraska and Iowa, and northwest winds of around 30 mph prevailed
over northern portions of Wisconsin and Michigan behind the same
cold front.
   Strong southwest winds caused widespread blowing dust and sand in
central and southern Nevada. At Lovelock winds hit 60 mph and
visibilities lowered to an eighth of a mile.
   Rain continued in the Pacific Northwest and into central
California.
   Snow fell in the mountains of the far West. Six inches was
reported in the higher elevations near Lake Tahoe Thursday morning
with blizzard conditions anticipated over some of the mountain
passes.
   Snow also fell in portions of the northern Rockies and northern
portions of Wisconsin and Michigan.
   Thunderstorms were reported over southeast Georgia, southern
Alabama and the Florida Panhandle. Hail accompanied a thunderstorm
near Mobile Ala., and thunderstorms brought heavy rain to the
Florida Keys.
   There was a sharp contrast in temperatures over the Great Plains
states. Early afternoon readings were in the single digits over
northern Minnesota and in the teens over much of the northern
Plains, but were in the 60s and 70s over the southern Plains.
   In southeast Nebraska at 2 p.m. EST it was 62 degrees in Falls
City while in Omaha, 90 miles to the north, it was 37 degrees.
   Skies were mostly sunny over the middle and northern Atlantic
Coast states. Temperatures ranged from the 30s and 40s over New
England to around 60 degrees in central Virginia.
   The low in the nation was 10 degrees below zero at Escanaba, Mich.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 5
degrees above zero at International Falls and Warroad, Minn., to 87
degrees at Jacksonville, Fla.
   The forecast for Friday called for scattered snow from the upper
Great Lakes across Minnesota and the Dakotas to the northern
Rockies. Rain was expected over the West Coast and northern and
central portions of the Plateau region. Scattered thunderstorms were
expected in southern Florida, western Texas and the middle
Mississippi and lower Tennessee valleys. Rainshowers were forecast
from Illinois to western New York state.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 20s and 30s from the
northern Rockies across the northern Plains and upper Mississippi
Valley to Michigan with teens near the Canadian border. Highs in the
30s were expected for northern New England. Highs in the 60s and 70s
were forecast from southern California across central Arizona, for
much of Colorado, New Mexico, the central Plains and the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys to the middle and south Atlantic Coast states.
Readings were expected to climb to the 80s from the desert Southwest
to much of western and southern Texas and from the central Gulf
Coast region to Florida. Highs elsewhere were expected in the 40s
and 50s.
</TEXT>
