<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin     03-16 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Forms Commission to Investigate Maverick's Views</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a second blow to maverick Boris N. Yeltsin in
the waning days of his parliamentary election campaign, the
Communist Party began an investigation Thursday of allegations that
he opposes some party positions.
   The decision on the final day of a meeting of the policy-making
Central Committee indicated more trouble ahead for Yeltsin. It came
two days after publication in a Central Committee journal of the
November 1987 speech that got him fired as Moscow party chief.
   Yeltsin, 58, is running for election March 26 to the new Congress
of People's Deputies and has said the campaign marks his political
rehabilitation.
   In the 1987 speech to the Central Committee, Yeltsin said faith
in Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms was waning and the leader was
becoming the subject of ``intolerable'' glorification.
   Vadim A. Medvedev, chief Kremlin ideologist, told a news
conference Thursday a panel was formed to investigate Yeltsin's
views after complaints were received from Central Committee members.
   He said Vladimir Tikhomirov, a Moscow worker and Central
Committee member, complained about Yeltsin's view of the role of the
party, about the bureaucracy Yeltsin heads in the State Construction
Committee and about discourtesy toward Tikhomirov.
   Other party officials said Yeltsin ``expressed some views that
stood at variance with the party line and those messages received by
the plenary meeting suggested the issue be formally discussed,''
Medvedev said.
   Yeltsin defended himself against charges that he advocates a
multiparty system, the ideologist said, but also told the Central
Committee he wants the issue discussed in the official press.
   Although he still is a Central Committee member and serves as
first deputy chairman of the State Construction Committee, Yeltsin
is campaigning as an outsider for a seat representing all Moscow.
His opponent is director of the giant ZIL auto company.
   He has demanded an end to special privileges for party and
government officials; extension of Gorbachev's policy of
``glasnost,'' or openness, and more economic reform. He remains
popular with many Muscovites, who wear buttons supporting him.
   In a debate televised Sunday night, Yelstin accused the Moscow
party organization he formerly led of conspiring against his
candidacy. In a speech a week ago, he accused the local party of
restricting voter access to his appearances.
   The weekly Moscow News said in its latest edition an anonymous
11-page criticism of Yeltsin was being distributed at some local
party heaquarters.
</TEXT>
