<FIRST>u a AM-Vincennes-Bomb     03-16 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vincennes-Bomb,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>School, Mrs. Rogers Decide She Will Not Return To Work There</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assoociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of the USS Vincennes skipper agreed
Thursday to quit teaching at a private school because her narrow
escape from a bomb attack prompted fears that students could be
exposed to terrorist acts.
   Parents worried that their children at the exclusive La Jolla
Country Day School might be endangered if Sharon Rogers returned to
teach her fourth-grade class, and they told their concerns known to
administrators.
   ``To ensure the safety of the children, the confidence of the
parents, and the integrity of the educational environment of La
Jolla Country Day School, Mrs. Rogers and the school have reached
the mutual decision that she will not be returning to the campus,''
headmaster Tim Burns said in a statement.
   The school was the target of a bomb scare on Tuesday. Police
searched the grounds and found nothing. Extra precautions have been
taken at the campus, including daily searches of classrooms by
school personnel before the children's arrival and the posting of
security guards at the entrance gate.
   School spokesman Jim Stewart declined to go beyond Burns'
statement except to say officials at the school were grateful Mrs.
Rogers was unhurt in the bombing. He would not say whether Mrs.
Rogers told her pupils about the decision during a conference call.
   Mrs. Rogers survived the bombing of the family van unhurt as she
drove to work alone last Friday.
   The FBI is investigating the bombing as a possible terrorist act
in retaliation for the mistaken downing last July of an Iranian
airliner by the Vincennes, which is commanded by her husband, Capt.
Will C. Rogers III.
   On Wednesday, a person purporting to be a member of Guardians of
the Islamic Revolution called a Los Angeles radio station and said
the group was responsible for the van bombing. The caller also
threatened more violence against Capt. Rogers and his family.
   Rogers and his wife remain under the protection of Navy security
agents at an undisclosed location, as they have since Friday's
bombing, said Dennis Usery, regional director of the Naval
Investigative Service.
   Usery declined to answer when asked how Mrs. Rogers was
responding to the decision against returning to the teaching job.
   Rogers continues as skipper of the Vincennes, which returned from
its Persian Gulf deployment last October.
   It was in the Gulf last July 3 during a battle with Iranian
gunboats that Rogers ordered the Vincennes' crew to fire missiles at
what was thought to be an attacking Iranian fighter jet. The plane
actually was a civilian airliner and all 290 people aboard were
killed in the missile strike.
</TEXT>
