<FIRST>u w AM-ArmsFraud 1stld-writethru a0791 03-16 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Fraud, 1st ld-writethru, a0791,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT that Reese pleaded guilty to conspiracy
and filing a false statement, not to conspiracy and bribery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Army colonel who supervised military
sales to El Salvador was indicted Thursday on charges he solicited
and took more than $70,000 in bribes from the president of an
Illinois gun maker.
   Col. Juan Lopez de la Cruz, a U.S. military advisor in San
Salvador between 1982 and 1984, was named in a seven-count
indictment that charged conspiracy, bribery and making false
statements, and aiding and abetting the filing of false claims.
   The indictment, returned by a federal grand jury in Alexandria,
Va., accused Lopez of conspiring with Dennis J. Reese, president of
Springfield Armory, Inc. to take bribes and to circumvent rules of
the foreign military sales program.
   The indictment charged that Lopez solicited and received $70,000
in bribes from Reese, who pleaded guilty last month to conspiracy
and to filing a false statement. Reese also purchased, at Lopez's
request, a $4,722 Rolex watch for the colonel.
   In return for the bribes, Lopez is accused of signing false
documents that enabled Springfield Armory to be reimbursed for sales
of weapons to the Salvadoran government, including $94,600 in phony
sales commissions.
   The indictment charged that Lopez and Reese arranged for false
commissions to be paid to two Salvadorans they designated as agents
to circumvent regulations governing the military sales.
   Lopez directed Reese to make out checks to the Salvadorans, who
cashed them and returned the money to Reese _ minus their fee, the
indictment said.
   Lopez, who was the advisor to the Salvadoran Military Group,
which advised the Salvadoran government on weapons sales, was
accused of signing false government documents stating that
commissions had been paid on the sale of $3.7 million worth of
firearms.
   He is also accused of aiding and abetting Reese's filing of false
claims for reimbursement of $94,600 from the Defense Department for
the false commissions.
   If found guilty of all seven counts, Lopez could be sentenced up
to 15 years for each of the two bribery charges and five years for
each of the five remaining counts.
   The bribery charges together would carry a fine of $210,000 while
the other charges carry fines of $250,000 apiece.
   Attempts to reach Lopez for comment were unsuccessful.
</TEXT>
