<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Eastern-Congress     03-16 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Congress,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republicans Block Senate Debate on Eastern Airlines Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican lawmakers blocked Democratic efforts
Thursday night to have the Senate consider legislation that would
require President Bush to intervene in the Eastern Airlines strike.
   The procedural standoff made it likely that the measure, passed
Wednesday by the House, could not come to a vote until after the
Senate's two-week Easter recess, which begins Saturday.
   The bill would force Bush to name an emergency board to recommend
a solution to the strike, and would impose a cooling-off period of
up to 26 days during which the airline's employees would receive
pre-strike wages. Bush opposes the bill, arguing the dispute between
Eastern and its unions should be settled directly between the two
sides, and administration officials have said the measure would be
vetoed.
   After hours of closed-door talks between legislators from the two
parties, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, tried to
commence debate on the measure, arguing that steps should be taken
to end the two-week old walkout.
   ``The federal government should not simply sit by waiting for
something to happen,'' Mitchell said.
   Republicans blocked that effort, using procedures under which an
individual lawmaker can prevent the consideration of a bill. They
argued the measure should be studied for at least a week by the
Senate Labor Committee, saying the situation was complicated by
potential efforts to buy the airline and by Eastern's filing for
protection from creditors under the bankruptcy code.
   ``There is a desire for us not to bottle this thing up forever,''
said Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., would not say that
Republicans would filibuster the measure, under which lengthy debate
is used in an effort to kill a bill. But he said, ``Debate would be
intense.''
   Mitchell said he would seek a vote after the Easter recess that
would prevent a filibuster. Such a vote would require 60 votes from
the 100-member Senate, in which Democrats have 55 members.
   The House passed the union-supported bill by a 252-167 vote, with
all but 20 votes coming from its majority Democrats.
</TEXT>
