<FIRST>u w AM-Hostages-Senate     03-16 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Senate,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Hostages</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Resolution Marks Fourth Anniversary of Anderson's Capture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate marked the fourth anniversary of the
kidnapping of Terry Anderson in Lebanon by passing a resolution on
Thursday calling for the release of all hostages.
   The Senate, on a voice vote, said it ``condemns all forms of
hostage taking for whatever purposes by individuals, groups or
governments.''
   It called on countries ``to condemn all forms of hostage taking
and to work for the release of all hostages.''
   Anderson, The Associated Press' Middle East bureau chief, was
kidnapped in Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   Eight other Americans are missing in Lebanon and believed held
hostage by groups operating there: Thomas Sutherland, Frank Reed,
Joseph James Cicippio, Edward Austin Tracy, Jesse Turner, Robert
Polhill, Alann Steen, and William Higgins.
   The measure was introduced by Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</TEXT>
