<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 2217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Flight103 3rdLd-Writethru a0800 03-16 1174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0800,1201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warnings Issued Before Bombing; Coverup Charged; Suspect Reportedly
Known</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Times of London saying police
know who bomber is. Pickup 10th graf `A photostat...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transport Department says it issued two
warnings of a bomb plot in the month before Pan Am Flight 103 blew
up over Scotland, but the airline said Thursday it never received
the first warning and the second arrived weeks late, by mail.
   The Times of London reported Thursday night that police know the
bomber's identity and will disclose details next week. But
authorities denied reports in a British tabloid that a suspect was
arrested.
   Transport Secretary Paul Channon said the second warning, two
days before the Dec. 21 crash, was ``of no importance whatsoever,''
because the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration already issued its
own warning to U.S. carriers about the threat.
   Members of the opposition Labor Party accused the government of a
cover-up and demanded an investigation. The Transport Department
issued its statement Wednesday night after a newspaper report of the
warnings.
   The warnings issued by the British government Nov. 22 and Dec.
19, just two days before the disaster that killed 270 people, spoke
of a bomb hidden in a radio-cassette player, the Transport
Department said.
   Police say they established that the explosives were in a
radio-cassette player planted in a suitcase stowed in the jumbo
jet's hold.
   Pan Am said the Transport Department's Dec. 19 memo did not reach
it until Jan. 17 and that it never received the Nov. 22 warning. In
New York, company spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon acknowledged Pan Am did
receive the FAA warning Nov. 18 and as a result ``put into place
some heightened security procedures,'' but she declined to elaborate.
   Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt, changing to a Boeing 747 in
London. It blew up over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing all 259 people
aboard and 11 on the ground.
   The Times reported in its Friday issue, early copies of which
were available Thursday night: ``Police and security service
investigators now know precisely who made and placed the bomb and
the whereabouts of the bomber.
   ``The results of what Whitehall (British government) sources term
`one of the most remarkable feats of criminal detection ever known'
are expected to be disclosed next week.
   ``It is understood that Mr. Channon has already discussed the
findings in outline with Dr. Jurgen Warnke, his West German
counterpart,'' the Times said without giving any further details.
   Authorities denied a report Friday by the London tabloid Today
that said the terrorist who planted the bomb was under arrest
``somewhere in Europe.''
   A police spokesman in Frankfurt, West Germany, quoted by the
British domestic news agency Press Association said he knew nothing
about any terrorists being held in connection with the bombing. A
spokesman at the Scottish Office, the British government department
responsible for Scotland, described the report as ``pure
speculation.''
   A photostat of the Dec. 19 warning published by the Daily Mirror
showed it addressed to ``All U.K. airlines (and El Al, Air India,
U.S. airlines, South African Airways).''
   The Mirror said the notice advised security authorities to look
for telltale signs: that the instrument wouldn't play, its insides
would rattle, the X-ray would show more wiring than usual and the
antenna socket would be taped shut.
   Suspicions of a bomb plot arose in October when West German
police caught a Palestinian terrorist group with a radio-cassette
player containing explosives and a barometric device that would
detonate a bomb at high altitude, according to British and West
German officials.
   ``We sent advice to the relevant security authorities,'' the
Transport Department said in its statement. ``They were told what to
look for. The American authorities would have done the same for
American airlines.''
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the
arrests in West Germany also prompted the FAA issued a warning Nov.
18 that told of the terrorist group, ``the existence of this bomb,
its characteristics, and to advise that increased security measures
should be introduced to counter this threat.''
   ``This bulletin remains in effect today,'' he added.
   On Dec. 5, the U.S. Embassy in Helsinki was warned in a telephone
call of a plot to bomb a Pan Am airliner on a Frankfurt-U.S. flight
during a two-week period in December. The FAA issued an
``intelligence alert'' that there might be a bomb attempt against a
Pan Am flight from Frankfurt.
   Speaking on BBC-TV, Channon said the Nov. 22 warning was sent to
British airlines and airports, ``and of course the Federal Aviation
Administration sent out their own warning to the American airlines.''
   Asked about Pan Am's statement that it didn't get the second
warning until Jan. 17, Channon said: ``There is no importance to it
whatsoever. All it contained, virtually, was a color photograph of a
cassette player and a few more unimportant pieces of information
about how a bomb in Frankfurt had been constructed.''
   He said the evidence that the bomb was placed aboard the plane at
London's Heathrow Airport ``is very slender _ indeed all the
evidence seems to point the other way.''
   Asked if this meant he was blaming U.S. and West German
authorities for failing to prevent the bombing, he said: ``I don't
make any comment about that. That's for the investigators to decide
and for the police.'' West German authorities say there is no firm
evidence that the bomb was smuggled aboard in Frankfurt.
   In Frankfurt, Manfred Langendorf, chief of the Hesse state
interior ministry's office for airport security, said Thursday all
airlines operating in West Germany _ including Pan Am _ were told in
early November about the radio-cassette player containing explosives.
   David Wilshire of Britain's governing Conservative Party, who
follows air transport affairs, denied suggestions authorities simply
dropped a highly sensitive warning into the Christmas mail deluge.
   He said the Dec. 19 warning was sent by telex and the mailed
versions were courtesy copies. He said that Pan Am, in any case, had
received one of the November warnings.
   Wilshire said security officials at London's Heathrow Airport
built a mock bomb after the Nov. 22 warning to run through X-ray
machines, but added that the machines scan only carry-on bags and
airlines are responsible for checked luggage.
   Labor Party transport spokesman John Prescott said the
government's responses were ``just not good enough. The government
are covering up. ... Let's have a public inquiry.''
   Elizabeth Delude-Dix, an American whose Irish husband was killed
on Flight 103, said: ``I'm bewildered and also very angry.
   ``Now we know that the government had information which told them
the carrier that would be affected _ Pan American; the origin of the
flight _ Frankfurt; that the threatened period was during the month
of December, and now we've learned that they also had information
about the exact kind of bomb that was used.''
   If security authorities had ``only looked at all the information
at their disposal they could perhaps have prevented this,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
