<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Military     03-16 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Military,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Sanctions 13 Officers Connected to Uprising last December</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army commander Francisco Gassino
punished 13 officers Thursday for either joining a rebellion in
December or not preventing their men from doing so. Most were forced
to retire.
   Gen. Gassino's office said Col. Edgardo Parellada, director of
the Infantry School, and seven other officers were retired and Col.
Hugo Tabbia, head of the mountain warfare school in Bariloche, and
two other officers were relieved of duty, which eventually will
force them into retirement.
   Two captains were barred from continuing their studies at the
National War College.
   Parellada remained loyal to President Raul Alfonsin, as did the
chiefs of an infantry regiment at Mercedes, west of the capital, and
a communications post to the south, but all three were ousted by
subordinates who followed Col. Mohamed Ali Seineldin, the rebel
leader.
   Seineldin led an uprising at the Campo de Mayo army base and
Villa Martelli arsenal on the outskirts of the capital Dec. 2 and
surrendered two days later.
   He and several other officers were arrested. All are in military
prisons, along with officers involved in similar uprisings in April
1987 and January 1988.
</TEXT>
