<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines-Congressman 1stLd-Writethru   03-16 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Congressman, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0810,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippines Congressman Slain at Airport</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with lone gunman killing congressman,
details, background. Pickup 8th graf `In an...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lone gunman killed Congressman
Moises Espinosa on the island province of Masbate on Friday shortly
after he arrived by plane from Manila, congressional and military
sources said.
   Espinosa was the first member of Congress to be slain since
President Corazon Aquino took office in February 1986.
   Rep. Antonio Cuenco, deputy speaker of the House of
Representatives, told reporters Espinosa was killed moments after
arriving in Masbate at 7:30 a.m. (6:30 p.m. EST Thursday). No
arrests were reported.
   Espinosa ran as an independent but later joined the Struggle of
the Democratic Filipino, which favors President Corazon Aquino.
   Rep. Milagros Trinidad quoted Espinosa's family as saying a
single gunman shot the congressman with a semi-automatic rifle as he
stepped onto the airport pavement.
   Earlier reports said up to five assailants attacked him. The
Associated Press reached the governor's office in Masbate by
telephone, but the woman who answered said she had no details and
the rest of the staff had rushed to the airport.
   Quoting relatives, Mrs. Trinidad said Espinosa was accompanied by
bodyguards but they were unable to fire because they had surrendered
their weapons to the plane's crew before departing Manila.
   Cuenco said five House members would fly to Masbate later to
investigate the killing. Military officials confirmed the death but
said a full report would probably not be available until Saturday
because of poor communications to Masbate, about 235 miles south of
Manila.
   Espinosa, 55, was elected to the House from Masbate in May 1987.
His brother, Emilio, is governor of the province and another
brother, Tito, is also a member of the House of Representatives.
   He was survived by his wife, Ludivina, three sons and three
daughters.
   In an earlier incident, police in Manila police reported Thursday
that a soldier who was part of the contingent assigned to protect
Mrs. Aquino went on a shooting spree and wounded two people before
neighbors stabbed and beat him to death.
   A police report said Patrolman Ramil Villafranca went on a
shooting rampage late Wednesday in his neighborhood in the
working-class district of Tondo and shot and wounded two people.
   Residents then pulled out knives and clubs, chased Villafranca,
then beat and stabbed the soldier, the report said. Villafranca's
attackers fled before police arrived, it said.
   The report did not say what triggered Villafranca's rage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
