<DOCNO> AP890316-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     03-16 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ten Dead In Rebel Clashes, Aquino Approves IMF Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels killed a police
intelligence agent Wednesday in a Manila suburb, and the military
said nine other people were slain in clashes between insurgents and
government forces.
   Police said Patrolman Leandro Serrano was in his jeep preparing
to leave for work in suburban Navotas when five gunmen opened fire,
killing him instantly.
   The assailants, who escaped, left a note signed by the Alex
Boncayao Brigade saying Serrano was slain because he was assigned to
a police counterintelligence unit.
   The Alex Boncayao Brigade is the Manila wing of the New People's
Army, which has been waging a 20-year insurgency to establish a
Communist state.
   On Mindanao island, 500 miles southeast of Manila, the military
said three rebels and three soldiers were killed Monday in Lanao del
Norte province.
   Three more soldiers died in rebel ambushes the same day in the
Mindanao provinces of Agusan del Norte and Surigao del Norte,
military reports said.
   In another development, the military said nine soldiers and four
Defense Department civilians were fired for financial irregularities
as part of a crackdown on corruption.
   Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa said the 13 dismissed
employees had finance jobs at the Armed Forces General Staff, the
central Philippine Visayas Command and at the military hospital in
Quezon City.
   He said all were undergoing investigation to determine if they
would be court-martialed for embezzlement or misappropriation of
funds.
   The military command has come under increasing pressure from
Congress, the public and the news media to eliminate corruption,
which flourished in the 160,000-member army during the 20-year
administration of President Ferdinand Marcos. Marcos was ousted in
1986.
   Also Wednesday, President Corazon Aquino told reporters she had
approved in principle a package of reforms and other measures her
government will undertake as a condition for $1.3 billion in IMF
loans.
   She said a ``letter of intent'' accepting the IMF terms will be
forwarded to Fund headquarters in Washington after a review by the
Philippine Senate.
   Formal approval also will pave the way for $1.6 billion more in
new loans from commercial banks and for talks with foreign creditors
to reschedule up to $2 billion of the country's $28 billion foreign
debt.
   In its letter of intent, the government pledges to reduce the
budget deficit by improved tax collection, to liberalize imports
regulations and to disband or sell off most of its state-owned
businesses.
   It also agrees to continue a floating exchange rate which has
seen the peso lose about three percent of its value against the U.S.
dollar in the past year.
   Critics contend the government cannot meet the terms of the
package without raising prices for electric power, transport and
food.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
