<FIRST>r a AM-HearinKidnapping     03-16 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hearin Kidnapping,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney To Appear For Detention, Removal Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents who searched a St.
Petersburg lawyer's office found further evidence linking him to the
disappearance of a Mississippi millionaire's wife, a prosecutor told
a federal magistrate Wednesday.
   U.S. Magistrate Harvey Schlesinger ordered the lawyer, Newton
Alfred Winn, held without bond and returned to Mississippi to stand
trial on federal charges of extortion and perjury in the kidnapping
of 73-year-old Annie Laurie Hearin.
   Mrs. Hearin, wife of Jackson, Miss., businessman Robert Hearin,
disappeared on July 26, 1988, and has not been found although her
husband complied with a ransom note.
   While Winn is not charged with the woman's kidnapping, he is
charged with extortion for hiring a woman to mail a note from Mrs.
Hearin to her husband urging him to comply with a ransom demand.
   He also faces charges of lying to a federal grand jury on Aug. 3,
when he denied any knowledge of the disappearance, FBI officials
said.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Stephen Kunz said agents searched Winn's
combination home and law office and found a map of Jackson, Miss.,
with the location of the Hearins' home circled. Also marked were the
locations of businesses and a little-known farm owed by the Hearins'.
   The agents seized six aerial maps of Jackson, an old Royal
typewriter, a 9mm semi-automatic gun and a .38-caliber revolver.
   The FBI has concluded that a Royal typewriter manufactured
between 1912 and 1926 was used to type the ransom note for Mrs.
Hearin. Investigators are conducting tests on the typewriter found
at Winn's home to see if it was used to type the ransom note, Kunz
said.
   Kunz also said a neighbor of the Hearins identified Winn from a
photo lineup as a man she had seen in a white van in the
neighborhood a few days before the kidnapping.
   FBI agent Thomas Montgomery testified that Winn paid a woman
friend $500 to fly to Atlanta and mail a letter written by the
kidnap victim a couple weeks after the kidnapping. The letter urged
Hearin to meet the ransom demand.
   The day after receiving the note, Hearin paid out almost $1
million to the 12 men listed in the ransom note, including Winn, who
returned the money.
   Winn, 64, who served as his own attorney for the hearing, stood
up near the end of the hearing and said, ``Much of this surprises
me.''
   Winn and the 11 others listed in the ransom note to Hearin were
current or former franchise holders of School Pictures Inc., in
which Hearin owned controlling interest. The corporation had sued
all 12, claiming they owed the company money, and won a judgment
against Winn of about $150,000.
   Hearin's worth reportedly exceeds $100 million. He is co-owner of
Mississippi Valley Gas Co. and co-owner of Yazoo Manufacturing Co.,
a gardening equipment manufacturing company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
