<FIRST>r a AM-KittyDukakis     03-16 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kitty Dukakis,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kitty Dukakis Resumes Speaking Tour After Alchoholism Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILLANOVA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight days after completing an alchoholism
rehabilitation program, Kitty Dukakis was back on the lecture
circuit Wednesday, addressing college students on the lack of women
in politics.
   The wife of the Massachussets governor and failed Democratic
Presidential candidate, Michael Dukakis, arrived at Villanova
University wearing a soft cast on her left ankle to protect
ligaments torn in a fall earlier this week.
   She discussed her alchoholism with reporters before her speech.
   ``There's a word with my disease and that's called recovering,''
she said. ``I'll always be recovering and I hope I'll be able to
follow the steps of the program. That will be a part of my life.''
   Mrs. Dukakis said she feels encouraged about her future and
frequently described her outlook as ``positive.''
   Mrs. Dukakis was hospitalized in February for alchoholism
rehabilitation at Edgehill Newport in Newport, R.I., for 31 days.
   She has said her drinking began shortly after the November
election, but as she did at a news conference shortly after her
release last Tuesday, she refused Wednesday to blame the campaign
for her drinking.
   In her speech, Mrs. Dukakis said alcoholism or drug abuse knows
no barriers of class, race or sex.
   ``Contemporary society still reserves a special stigma, a modern
letter of scarlet, for women who become dependent on drugs, whether
liquid or solid,'' she said.
   Women are accustomed to struggles, she said, as is seen in
women's efforts to get ahead in politics.
   ``No area of political involvement is more important for women
today than that of fund raising. Here, through networks of friends,
associates and neighbors, we have a golden opportunity to make a
significant impact all across the country,'' she said.
   Mrs. Dukakis said she hasn't had a chance to form an opinion of
the Bush administration because she was not allowed to watch
television news or read newspapers during her treatment.
   In 1982 she overcame a 26-year addiction to diet pills.
   She said she is working on a book about the presidential campaign
and will continue speaking around the country.
   Before being hospitalized for alchohol addiction, she had
delivered three speeches on various topics in Los Angeles and
Florida.
</TEXT>
