<FIRST>r a AM-MansonTransferred     03-16 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manson Transferred,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charles Manson Transferred to New State Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORCORAN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted mass-murder Charles Manson has
been transferred from San Quentin State Prison to a new maximum
security unit in the San Joaquin Valley, a prison official said
Wednesday.
   Lt. Evelyn Mazon said Manson, one of the most notorious of
California's 78,000 convicts, was sent to Corcoran State Prison this
week to be housed in the state's toughest new maximum security unit.
   ``San Quentin is undergoing a major change in mission, from a
maximum-security prison to a medium-security prison,'' said Mike Van
Winkle, a Corrections Department spokesman.
   Manson is among 957 high-risk inmates who have been transferred
to the $253 million Corcoran prison since it opened 13 months ago.
The prison's population on Wednesday was 3,576 inmates.
   Officials did not name any other well-known inmates now housed in
the facility, roughly midway between Los Angeles and San Francisco
and about 200 miles southeast of San Quentin.
   Manson, 52, has spent nearly all of his adult life in federal and
state prisons.
   He had been on parole less than two years from the federal prison
at Terminal Island near Los Angeles when his ``Manson Family'' cult
followers murdered actress Sharon Tate, coffee heiress Abigail
Folger, Polish filmmaker Voityk Frykowski and six others in a
month-long murder spree in 1969.
   Manson was convicted of masterminding and ordering the Tate and
other murders in an effort to trigger a race war that he believed
was foretold in the Beatles' song ``Helter Skelter.''
   Manson is serving a life sentence for the Tate murders, but is
technically eligible for consideration for parole, if the state
Board of Prison Terms considered him suitable for release.
   At his latest hearing 13 months ago, the board again turned down
parole for three years _ the longest period allowed without
additional review. Board member Albert Leddy at that time said it
was ``highly unlikely'' that Manson, who has been turned down seven
times for parole, ever would be released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
