<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:WilliamDouglas Adv20   03-16 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: William Douglas, Adv 20,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday PMs, March 20, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Justice William O. Douglas Still Creates News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note anniversary of nomination is March 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty years after his appointment to the
Supreme Court and nine years after his death, William O. Douglas
remains a source of strong emotions in the state that shaped his
life and his opinions.
   A critical documentary is scheduled to air next month, a major
symposium on Douglas' career is planned in Seattle, newly released
government files reveal an FBI scheme to discredit him, and the
state Legislature is considering the $100,000 purchase of his
Cascade Mountain hideaway for a public memorial.
   ``He is a compelling figure,'' said Walt Lowe, whose documentary
is to air on public television stations. ``The strength of his
personality, the magnitude of his work. He was a person who saw a
chance to do good and he did it.''
   Douglas was raised in poverty in Yakima, graduated from Whitman
College in Walla Walla, then taught high school here for two years
before deciding in 1922 to become a lawyer. After serving as a law
professor, lawyer, and chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, he was nominated to the Supreme Court on March 20, 1939,
by President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
   During 36 years on the high court, Douglas wrote a record 1,200
decision.
   He was a consistent supporter of abortion rights, First Amendment
press protections, the environment, and the rights of criminal
suspects, including the controversial Miranda decision. He used his
position to oppose racism in schools and U.S. Army surveillance of
Vietnam War protesters.
   The Supreme Court recently overturned some affirmative action
programs and will hear arguments on a case that could affect its
landmark ruling legalizing abortion, so Douglas' views remain
important, said H.G. Locke, organizer of the three-day Seattle
symposium scheduled to begin April 15. It will look at him as
environmentalist, internationalist, civil libertarian and as a man.
   Lowe's documentary, funded by the Pacific Mountain Network of the
Public Broadcasting System and produced by KYVE of Yakima, is
scheduled to air in the West on April 17, the anniversary of
Douglas' elevation to the court.
   It paints an unflattering portrait of Douglas' domineering mother
and includes a scathing attack by his daughter, a discussion of his
four marriages and his extramarital affairs, and interviews with
former clerks who remember a driving perfectionist with little
regard for their personal lives.
   What emerges is a picture of an egotistical, often unpleasant
man, deeply scarred by early poverty, who rose primarily through his
brilliance.
   Douglas' daughter, Mildred Read, remembers a distant father with
little time or use for his children. ``He didn't want to be talked
to at breakfast because he was reading the paper. He didn't know
what to do with us.''
   His first clerk, David Ginsberg, now a Washington, D.C., lawyer,
recalled a stern boss: ``There was never a thought that I was
overburdened.''
   Ms. Read said her father had many affairs, moving on as he grew
tired of each woman. Mercedes Eichholz, Douglas' second wife, whose
lengthy affair with the justice broke up his first marriage after 29
years, said, ``His pursuit was so hot and heavy he wore me down.''
   The Portland Oregonian reported in January that secret FBI files
showed a pattern of misdeeds against Douglas covering two decades
and including former President Nixon's attempt to impeach him in
1970. The FBI first began keeping tabs on him in the early 1950s,
when former Gov. Arthur Langlie wrote to U.S. Attorney General
Herbert Brownell that communists were regular guests at Douglas'
summer home in La Push.
   More than three decades later, state officials are once again
concerned with one of Douglas' summer homes _ but this time they
wish to honor the native son. A bill has been introduced in the
House that seeks to purchase the alpine cabin that Douglas built in
1965 near Goose Prairie, about 25 miles east of Mount Rainier in the
Cascade Mountains.
   A U.S. Forest Service report issued last Tuesday noted that
turning the cabin site into a wilderness studies institute would be
appropriate. ``Using the property would encourage an understanding
of wilderness principles,'' said Don Rotell of the forest service.
   Cathy Douglas Stone, the jurist's fourth wife, put the home up
for sale last year. If it becomes a public memorial, she has agreed
to return many of the furnishings and memorabilia to the
chalet-style dwelling.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs March 20</NOTE>
