<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0819EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:OscarTelecast Adv20   03-16 0938</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Oscar Telecast, Adv 20,0956</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, March 20 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reviving Oscar Magic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics say the Academy Awards
telecast is showing its age. Producer Allan Carr says that's the way
it should be.
   In an attempt to keep the program's ratings from slipping, Carr
will celebrate Oscar by reveling in its yesteryears.
   ``I'm restoring it, hopefully, to what it was in its glorious
day,'' Carr said of the March 29 broadcast of the 61st Annual
Academy Awards from the Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles. The
program will be shown at 9 p.m. EST by ABC-TV.
   Carr and scenic designer Ray Clausen will recreate a likeness of
the Cocoanut Grove, the tropical nightclub where the Oscar dinner
banquet was held in 1940. Famous movie couples will be seated at
tables between the palm trees, and a bandstand will be on the stage.
   ``This is the ultimate variety show,'' Carr said. ``It's also the
ultimate awards show that all the other awards show copy. So I have
to make this a return to Oscar _ the way it was in the old days _
because now you have the Tonys, the Grammys, the American Music
Awards, the People's Choice Awards. ... There's an awards show on
every other week.
   ``The Oscars are supposed to be really glamorous and fun. It's
the highest awards we give our royalty in this country. I'm going to
shock people with glamour and humor.''
   Carr comes from a career filled with flamboyant spectacles. As
the producer of the stage hit ``La Cage aux folles'' and the movies
``Grease,'' ``Can't Stop the Music'' and ``Where the Boys Are '84,''
his projects have rarely strayed from playfulness and overblown
kitsch. He even held a black-tie dinner party in 1976 at the Lincoln
Heights jail in a rundown section of East Los Angeles, to celebrate
the opening of ``Murder by Death,'' which starred the late author
Truman Capote.
   ``Whether people like me or don't like me, or they like what I do
or don't like what I do, they know that I love Hollywood and I'm a
big enthusiast for Hollywood,'' Carr said.
   ``For the last four years, the orchestra has not been in the
auditorium; they were at an ABC studio five miles away and the music
was piped in. But this is going to be a Broadway show. I insisted
that the orchestra comes back, Marvin Hamlisch will be in the pit
conducting, and ramps have been put over the orchestra pit so the
people can run up the aisles.
   ``I am producing, really, two things: A live show for the people
who are there _ like a Broadway opening night _ and a television
show which has a feeling of a Broadway opening night for the people
at home.''
   There will be no single program host this year. Don Johnson and
Melanie Griffith will present the first statuette, Cher and Michael
Douglas will present the last, and dozens of other stars will manage
everything in between.
   Off-screen couples will be paired on-screen: Farrah Fawcett will
appear with Ryan O'Neal; Goldie Hawn will be with Kurt Russell; and
Demi Moore will be escorted by her husband, Bruce Willis.
   ``It's like `Chariots of Fire.' It's like a relay race,'' Carr
said. ``The presenters pass the torch to the next person.''
   The telecast will honor awards presenters as well as winners.
When Stewart and Kim Novak appear to hand out a trophy, the audience
will be shown a clip from their work together in 1958's ``Vertigo.''
   The awards show will be held on Wednesday this year, unlike the
traditional Monday. The move is a result of both the preceding
Easter holiday and a possible television technicians strike the
following week. The show, Carr said, will be seen in 164 countries,
including the Soviet Union for the first time.
   ``When it was announced that I was going to produce the show,
people said, `You've got to have more of the entrances and the
arrivals. That's what people love to see.'... The Oscars are about
entrances. And so you will see great stars, through five generations
of different age groups, making the entrances down these incredible
staircases.''
   One production number will focus on up-and-coming stars, and
there will be a retrospective of film musicals.
   ``I wanted to bring my love of the musical movie to the Oscars,''
Carr said. ``Through lots of research, I realized that more movie
stars made musicals in the '50s than any other decade. So I have put
together this homage to the stars of the '50s musical, and you will
see people like Betty Grable, Gene Kelly, Donald O'Connor ... but
also Mario Lanza, Elvis Presley, Ava Gardner, Rita Hayworth and Lana
Turner.''
   Carr said complaints about past Oscar shows running past their
allotted three hours miss the real point.
   ``You only realize how long it is if you're bored,'' he said.
``My answer is: You didn't ask how long `Ben Hur' was. Now that
`Lawrence of Arabia' is out again _ it's almost four hours long _ no
one complains. If you're entertained, you don't watch the clock.''
   To keep the pace brisk, Oscar winners with multiple trophy
recipients _ as is common in technical awards _ will have one
designated speaker. After 30 seconds of thank yous, the microphone
will go dead and the camera will go to the next podium. Said Carr:
``They can talk as long as they want, but no one's going to hear
it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
