<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReviews Adv00 1stLd-Writethru 03-16 1259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Reviews, Adv 00, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0874,1294</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf to correct spelling of Francis; 12th graf, ``Arquette
gives the,'' to fix typo in adenoidal; 13th graf, ``What a joy,'' to correct
spelling of palette; and 27th graf to correct spelling of Bunyan. ^AP WEEKEND
ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``New York Stories,'' ``The Adventures of Baron Munchausen''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Both movies were released March 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``New York Stories''
   
   It began as an excellent idea: Take three top American
filmmakers, set them out on the streets of New York and loop their
efforts into one full-length feature to celebrate those collective
talents and the city they supposedly enshrined.
   Unfortunately, the idea doesn't quite gel with ``New York
Stories.''
   The Touchstone Pictures release consists of three vignettes by
Martin Scorsese, Francis Coppola and Woody Allen. But only
Scorsese's ``Life Lessons'' is worth the cost of today's pricey
movie tickets. It's also the first story in the production so one
can easily slip out at its conclusion and skip the next two.
   ``Life Lessons'' also is the only vignette that truly mirrors the
spirit and attitude of New York _ in this case, the downtown art
world. It has a feel, texture and mood, thanks in part to the gritty
and witty original screenplay by Bronx-born writer Richard Price,
and the sensitive and probing lens of the celebrated cinematographer
Nestor Almendros. It is a tight short story, a film exposition that
develops as brilliantly and explosively as the giant canvases
Almendros so wonderfully captures with his camera.
   Coppola's ``Life Without Zoe,'' by contrast, is a shallow effort
centered around the Sherry Netherland Hotel, the privileged few and
the superficialities of Eurotrash. It has nothing really to do with
New York and in fact concludes in Greece.
   Allen's ``Oedipus Wrecks'' justifies itself as a New York story
with a cameo by Mayor Edward I. Koch and a throwaway line about how
New Yorkers take certain bizarre happenings in their stride.
   Nick Nolte gives a memorable performance in ``Life Lessons'' as
Lionel ``The Lion'' Dolby, a brash, uncompromising, paternalistic
artist whose brutal, expansive paintings match his passion and
daring. He plays father to young women, taking them in as his art
assistants and repaying them with ``life lessons.'' Ahem.
   His latest, Paulette (Rosanna Arquette), fancies herself an
artist but has become smothered by Lionel. She's decided to leave
him, but he lures her back with no strings attached. They resolve
their relationship in a predictable way, but it's fun to watch.
   Arquette gives the same pouty, whiney, adenoidal performance
she's given in such movies as ``The Big Blue.'' She's difficult to
listen to, let alone watch. And she's dwarfed by Nolte's Lionel.
   What a joy he is, from the opening shots of a paint-splattered
cognac bottle, palette, cassette player and the artist himself
staring at a blank canvas while Procul Harum's ``A Whiter Shade of
Pale'' blasts through the studio, to his actual execution of the
canvas. One feels his brush strokes, which surely no one lower than
God is directing.
   ``Life Without Zoe'' offers little inspiration. Which is
regrettable given the vision and talent Coppola has displayed in
other works: ``Apocalpyse Now,'' ``The Godfather,'' ``Tucker.''
   The story concerns 12-year-old Zoe (Heather McComb) who lives
alone at the Sherry cared for by the hotel's male staff. She is
spoiled, precocious and chatty. Her father (Giancarlo Giannini) is a
world famous flute player and stays on the road. Her mother (Talia
Shire) is an emotionally frayed photographer with an adolescent
sensibility. She, too, would rather be on the road than home. These
people don't seem to like each other or their daughter very much.
   But it's difficult to like any of them. Coppola's characters are
not real. One does not care about the distraught mother or the
abandoned child, and the father comes across as a smarmy gigolo.
   There is a happy ending with a united family, but life would
indeed be better without Zoe.
   The best thing about Allen's ``Oedipus Wrecks'' is the title.
After that, it's all down hill. The movie is only for those diehard
Woody Allen fans who get their jollies with endless jokes about the
much-maligned Jewish mother, and who think that sitting with an
analyst is a hip thing to do.
   Allen plays a 50-year-old nebish who wants to marry the
unobtainable WASP (Mia Farrow). But mom's not too keen on this
arrangement. Borrowing from his ``Purple Rose of Cairo,'' Allen
employs an outlandish and bizarre trick that virtually leaves Mom in
the sky.
   Mae Questal is wonderful as the mother, and Julie Kavner _ the
Brenda Morgenstern of TV's ``Rhoda'' _ is more Jewish than Jewish as
the nice Jewish girl who gets the nice Jewish boy with a little help
from Tarot, witch doctors, voodoo and tea leaves.
   The Jack Rollins and Charles H. Joffe production was produced by
Robert Greenhut and is rated PG.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Adventures of Baron Munchausen''
   
   Baron Karl Friedrich Hieronymus von Munchausen was a German
soldier and adventurer who lived in the 18th century. He also was a
master prevaricator whose tales would shrivel Paul Bunyan's to
munchkin size.
   Terry Gilliam, a founding member of the irreverent Monty Python
troupe, has taken this legendary liar and made ``The Adventures of
Baron Munchausen'' the third in his fantasy triology that includes
``Time Bandits'' and ``Brazil.''
   Where ``Time Bandits'' primarily had a comedic appeal to
youngsters and ``Brazil'' tapped more philosophical and political
chords, ``Baron Munchausen'' is a priceless romp with more visual
effects and excursions into pure fantasy than any movie in memory.
There's even an unbilled cameo by Robin Williams as the King of the
Moon.
   The story opens in ``late 18th century, the Age of Reason,
Wednesday,'' with an attack on an ancient city by the ferocious
forces of the Ottoman Empire. A play about Baron Munchausen is
underway at a local theater, but the real baron is in the audience
and takes issue with the mockery on stage.
   The movie soon becomes the baron's story. And the spectacle is
nonstop: a hot-air trip in a balloon made of ladies' knickers that
takes the baron (John Neville) and Sally Salt (Sarah Polley), a
little girl who believes in imagination, to the moon and heaven;
heads that separate from bodies; a Venus rising from a half-shell,
complete with little angels with little wings; sea monsters; strange
trees, creatures, seas.
   But there's so much more in Gilliam's odyssey. The film is a
wondrous and brilliant work whose underpinnings tap the very essence
of imagination and conformity. The rigid bureaucrat Horatio Jackson
(Jonathan Pryce) questions the place of fancy, imagination and
dreamers in the age of reason. There isn't one, he says.
   Fairy tales, however, never die.
   Charles McKeown, who also has the dual role of Rupert and
Adolphus, wrote the masterful screenplay with Gilliam. Eric Idle
appears as Desmond and Berthold, and Oliver Reed is Vulcan.
   The Columbia Pictures release is produced by Thomas Schuhly and
is rated PG.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
