<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     03-16 0876</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0916</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strike-hobbled Eastern Airlines won an emergency order from a
federal bankruptcy judge aimed at forcing rivals to maintain
business agreements with the carrier, such as agreements providing
for the transfer of passengers and baggage among airlines.
   Meanwhile Wednesday in Washington, the House approved legislation
that would require a recalcitrant President Bush to name an
emergency panel to try to end the devastating Machinists union
strike against Eastern.
   In another development, union officials at Eastern said they were
encouraged by reports that Eastern boss Frank Lorenzo was exploring
the possible sale of the carrier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit narrowed
sharply in January to $9.49 billion, the lowest imbalance in three
months, as a big decline in consumer imports offset a higher oil
bill, the government reported.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that the imbalance between
imports and exports fell by 13.7 percent from a revised December
deficit of $10.99 billion as the United States posted a rare trade
surplus with Europe and the deficit with Japan fell to its lowest
point in 2{ years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy grew at a moderately strong pace
early this year, with widespread evidence of upward pressure on
production costs and prices, the Federal Reserve Board reported.
   The study released Wednesday found that with labor markets tight
and factories continuing to operate at high levels even as they
expand and modernize, ``materials and product prices are edging up,
albeit sporadically and at an uneven pace.''
   In a separate report that showed continued strength in the aging
economic expansion, the government said business inventories
continued their steady rise in January, accompanied by healthy
growth in sales.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two newspaper-based conglomerates controlled by
Canada's Thomson family announced they plan to merge operations into
a giant media company worth about $7.2 billion.
   The merger announced Wednesday is subject to approval by minority
shareholders in the two companies, Thomson Newspapers Ltd. and
International Thomson Organisation Ltd.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures industry leaders gathered for
their annual four-day meeting amid speculation that federal
authorities in Chicago were preparing to charge six people in
connection with an investigation of trading fraud in the commodities
pits.
   Anton Valukas, the U.S. attorney in Chicago, would not comment
Wednesday on the rumors, which have been spreading among defense
attorneys.
   Meanwhile, some members of Congress who usually attend the
Futures Industry Association's annual meeting at the industry's
expense reportedly have made other plans this year, apparently
wanting to avoid appearing to be too close to the industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Buy! Buy! Don't believe the gringos'
lies!'' chanted a street vendor of grapes, summing up the anger
Chileans felt over a U.S. scare concerning fruit from the South
American nation.
   Even though the action was taken after cyanide was found in two
grapes Chile exported to the United States, the president of the
State Bank on Wednesday called the U.S. action ``an aggression,
almost an act of war.''
   In the United States, meanwhile, millions of pounds of Chilean
fruit was being held for tests at dockside at ports in Philadelphia,
Los Angeles and Miami.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Washington Apple Commission voted
unanimously to spend $1.7 million for advertising to reassure
consumers that apples are safe, despite nationwide concerns over use
of the chemical Alar, which causes apples to remain on the tree
longer.
   The commission, which represents growers of the nation's largest
apple crop, voted Wednesday to take $1 million in emergency funds
and borrow $669,000 from banks to buy advertising in major markets
around the country.
   The Natural Resources Defense Council, whose recent report
touched off the furor, warned the apple commission to be careful
about the content of its advertising.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Living on welfare while dying of AIDS, Ron found grim
satisfaction that his death would enrich the beneficiary of his
$35,000 life insurance policy.
   Now, under an experiment by the Canadian subsidiary of Prudential
Insurance Co., the 44-year-old Ontario man has received $25,000 of
his own death benefits to make his last days more livable.
   He is one of only five people to receive ``living benefits''
under a program that has paid out less than $100,000 thus far.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Copyright Office urged Congress to consider
protecting future films from colorization, but said it would
probably be unconstitutional to extend such protection to existing
movies.
   The office said Wednesday it would prefer legislation that would
also protect visual artists, such as sculptors and painters, by
giving them ``moral rights'' to bar unauthorized alteration of their
works.
   But it said it could support legislation applying to film makers
alone.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The government's report of a slightly smaller-than-expected U.S.
trade deficit for January provided the impetus for a moderate
advance in the stock market Wednesday. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials gained 14.29 points to 2,320.54.
   The dollar rose sharply against major foreign currencies,
bolstered by the trade report. Gold prices declined.
   Bond prices finished virtually unchanged.
   Energy futures prices rolled up impressive gains for a third
straight session; precious metals plummeted; livestock futures were
higher and pork futures mostly higher.
</TEXT>
