<FIRST>r f BC-MorrellRuling     03-16 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Morrell Ruling,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Throws Out Arbitrator's Ruling in Morrell-Union Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arbitrator's ruling that union workers
who staged sympathy strikes should get their jobs back from John
Morrell &amp; Co. was thrown out by a federal judge.
   Company officials called the judge's ruling Wednesday a major
victory and said it frees Morrell from any back pay obligation.
   The union promised to appeal. At the time the arbitrator made his
ruling, a union leader said the back pay to the 2,400 workers who
went on strike could amount to $40 million.
   In a 14-page decision, U.S. District Judge Richard Battey ruled
that arbitrator William Rentfro, a University of Colorado law
professor, overstepped his authority when he decided in November
that a six-month sympathy strike at Morrell's flagship plant in
Sioux Falls in 1987 was legal.
   Battey ruled that Morrell does not have to follow Rentfro's
decision and rehire workers who were replaced during the sympathy
strike.
   ``We will immediately move to the 8th (U.S.) Circuit Court of
Appeals and hopefully get the proper decision,'' said Jim Lyons,
president of United Food and Commercial Workers Local 304A in Sioux
Falls.
   A year ago, a jury in Battey's federal courtroom in Rapid City
decided the 1987 sympathy strike and two one-day walkouts in 1986
were illegal. On Nov. 10, 1988, another jury awarded the company
$24.6 million in damages.
   Battey said the issue of whether the jury decisions in both the
liability and damage phases of the case are sound is a matter for
the appeals court.
   In order to let the arbitrator's award stand, Battey said he
would have to find that the company agreed to let Rentfro rule on
the legality of the sympathy strike on the contract language alone.
   ``The suggestion that Morrell agreed to submit the legality of
the sympathy strike to arbitration after having secured a successful
jury verdict flies in the face of common sense,'' the judge said.
   Last month Morrell imposed a new contract on workers at the Sioux
Falls plant, cutting the wages of 2,000 employees by up to 18
percent. More than half the workers at the plant are replacements
hired during the 1987 sympathy strike.
</TEXT>
