<FIRST>r f PM-HotelBattle     03-16 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hotel Battle,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Developer, Metropolitan Life Settle $7 Billion Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hotel developer Patrick Kennedy and
Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. have settled a $7 billion fraud
conspiracy lawsuit less than two months before their case was to go
to court, officials said.
   Kennedy, owner of La Mansion Hotels in San Antonio and Austin,
charged in a January 1988 lawsuit the insurance company, which
financed construction of one of Kennedy's three hotels, conspired to
acquire the hotels and replace the management with that of its own
subsidiary, Doubletree Hotels.
   As part of the agreement announced Wednesday, the 295-room La
Mansion del Norte in San Antonio, which had been at the crux of the
lawsuit, will be passed over to Metropolitan after an uncontested
foreclosure scheduled for April 4.
   In return, Kennedy will receive financing from Metropolitan so he
can repurchase La Mansion del Rio, a 340-room hotel on the River
Walk that opened in 1968, but which Kennedy had to sell in 1986
because of financing problems.
   No financial terms of the deal were announced.
   The parties were scheduled to go to state district court on May 1.
   ``I am just absolutely, unequivocally overjoyed to be back in
absolute ownership of La Mansion del Rio. It's meant a great deal to
me since I built it in 1968 and it's meant a lot to San Antonio in
the city's growth in the past 20 years,'' Kennedy said.
   He said because of an agreement signed with Metropolitan
officials late Tuesday, he was unable to deviate much from a
prepared joint statement.
   Metropolitan spokeswoman Dorothy Kelly also said she could not
elaborate beyond the statement.
   La Mansion del Norte Hotel had been the subject of the battle
between Kennedy and Metropolitan, which had financed about $11
million for construction on the hotel.
   Kennedy claimed in the lawsuit that between 1981 and 1984,
Metropolitan began thinking of taking over La Mansion del Norte
after the insurance giant acquired 20 percent of Doubletree Hotels.
   Metropolitan planned to foreclose on the hotel after Kennedy said
he couldn't make payments on it, but a restraining order pending the
outcome of the lawsuit prohibited Metropolitan from pursuing the
foreclosure.
   La Mansion Hotel in Austin, a 350-room hotel which opened in
1984, was foreclosed on in 1987 by American General Insurance Co., a
servicing agent of Metropolitan. Kennedy was the hotel manager and
he was replaced by Doubletree.
   Kennedy said last year that because of the slump in the Texas
economy, he had approached Metropolitan about refinancing his loan
for La Mansion del Norte, but Metropolitan officials declined and
sought foreclosure.
   Kennedy declined to elaborate on his financing structure for his
planned expansion, which would include managing the hotels
initially, before deciding on ownership or construction of new
structures.
</TEXT>
