<FIRST>r f PM-OilReport     03-16 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Report,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Oil Production Continues Decline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaska oil production fell for the third straight
month in February and overall U.S. crude production continued to
decline sharply, an industry trade group said.
   Imports also rose last month compared with the same time last
year but consumption remained flat, the American Petroleum Institute
said in its monthly report Wednesday.
   Alaska production, which had offset declines in other parts of
the United States in recent years, fell by 100,000 barrels a day in
February, while other U.S. production dropped by 300,000 barrels a
day, a total decline of about 5 percent, API said.
   ``The year-to-year declines in production indicate a continuation
of decreases in lower 48 production as well as a flattening, if not
a reversal, of an upward trend in Alaskan production seen during the
last several years,'' the trade group said.
   Imports in February totaled 7.9 million barrels, compared with
6.9 million barrels at the same time last year, but receded from
January's high of 8.2 million, the group reported.
   API, which represents major oil producers and refiners, said the
January import surge reflected an effort by U.S. oil companies to
take advantage of cheap and plentiful world oil before OPEC began
cutting back its output early this year.
   Imports now constitute over 40 percent of the oil consumed by
Americans, a level that has raised concern about national security
as the United States becomes more dependent on foreigners for
petroleum needs.
   ``The continued decline in domestic production and rise in
consumption together imply underlying growth in imports of more than
10 percent per year,'' the trade group said.
   Contributing to the rise in overall imports last month was a
strong increase in oil products such as heating oil and gasoline.
For the first two months of 1989, product imports were up 20 percent
over the same time last year. Also, U.S. refinery capacity has
shrunk in recent years and refineries are currently operating at
more than 80 percent capacity.
   Gasoline deliveries, meanwhile, fell 1.5 percent from last
February, due partly to a normal seasonal slowdown, the institute
report said.
   Heating oil deliveries growth also dropped to 3.2 percent despite
colder-than-normal February weather, API said.
   Despite the growing imports and slowdown in gasoline demand,
total inventories fell by 8 million barrels in February, down
slightly from January and from the same time last year, the report
said.
</TEXT>
