<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Buyers Bjt   03-16 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Buyers, Bjt,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icahn Still Leading Potential Buyer Of Eastern, Sources Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wily financier Carl Icahn, the majority owner and
chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., remains the leading potential
buyer of strike-torn Eastern Airlines, according to labor and
financial sources close to the situation.
   Icahn expressed interest in buying Eastern last October, and the
Eastern Machinists, who struck the airline March 4, indicated last
week they want him to explore a possible buyout. By acquiring
Miami-based Eastern, Icahn could use the airline's north-south
routes as possible feeders into TWA's trans-Atlantic network.
   The sale of Eastern is gathering momentum as an option for parent
Texas Air Corp. as the crippling strike against the carrier
continues with no sign of resolution, said the sources, who asked
not to be identified.
   Lorenzo has asked his investment bankers at Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. to gauge potential interest in buying Eastern among
investors and other airlines, the sources said.
   Drexel declined to confirm that it had been approached by Lorenzo
or make any comment on the issue, said Steve Anreder, a spokesman
for the Wall Street firm.
   On Wednesday, the 12th day of the strike, Eastern still was
operating only a fraction of its normal flights. Furthermore, most
of Eastern's pilots have continued honoring the strike despite
appeals and warnings from management, making it virtually impossible
for the airline to expand service.
   Eastern sought federal bankruptcy court protection from creditors
last Thursday. But analysts and other observers suggested that Texas
Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo would have difficulty rebuilding Eastern
through Chapter 11 and may be reaching a point where he is obliged
to sell the ailing carrier to stem his losses.
   Icahn continues to lead the list of potential buyers, followed by
Grandview, a group of investors and former corporate executives, the
sources said. The Grandview group's strongest suit is said to be
management expertise, giving it the belief that it could negotiate
contracts with Eastern's unions that Lorenzo was unable to get.
   Icahn and representatives of Grandview did not return phone calls
Wednesday seeking comment.
   Last October, Icahn talked with Lorenzo about acquiring Eastern.
The move came shortly after real estate developer Donald Trump
confirmed he was negotiating with Texas Air about a possible
purchase of Eastern's air shuttle operation.
   The planned shuttle sale, valued at $365 million, is awaiting the
approval of the bankruptcy judge.
   Icahn and Lorenzo dueled over control of TWA over three years
ago. A lot has changed since then, for both the men and the
deregulated airline business. Lorenzo, whose Texas Air empire went
on to acquire Eastern for $676 million after his TWA bid failed, may
have decided that running a debt-burdened and fractious airline is
too much trouble.
   Eastern has been fraught with labor agitation and staggering
financial losses before and since Lorenzo took over.
   For Icahn, who has chased giant companies ranging from USX Corp.
to Texaco Inc. in recent years, the acquisition of Eastern would
make TWA the largest U.S. airline in terms of revenue passenger
miles, an industry measurement of capacity.
   Some major airlines also have been rumored to be looking at
Eastern, but the reports have been denied by spokesmen for the
carriers.
   The value of Eastern to potential buyers are its assets _ planes,
airport gates, lucrative New York-Florida routes _ which they
believe they could deploy more effectively than Lorenzo has, and
thus turn the airline around.
</TEXT>
