<DOCNO> AP890316-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0104EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Coca-Cola-Buffett     03-16 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coca-Cola-Buffett,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway Owns $1.15 Billion of Coca-Cola Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Berkshire Hathaway Inc., which is headed by
investor Warren Buffett, has accumulated since last summer a 6.3
percent stake in Coca-Cola Co. that is now valued at about $1.15
billion, Coke has disclosed.
   Coca-Cola officials said they viewed the purchases as a ``strong
vote of confidence'' from the widely-respected investor, who with
his wife controls 45 percent of the Omaha, Neb.-based Berkshire
Hathaway's stock.
   In a telephone interview Wednesday, Buffett described the stock
purchase as ``simply a passive investment'' and said he is happy
with the way the company is being managed. Berkshire Hathaway is a
diversified holding company.
   Buffett has a reputation for taking sizeable stakes in a limited
number of companies and hold them for a long time.
   The disclosure sent Coca-Cola stock up $1.25 a share to $51.50 in
active trading of about 1.1 million shares on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   Coca-Cola Chairman Roberto C. Goizueta disclosed the Berkshire
holding in a memo to the soft drink maker's employees late Tuesday.
   He said Berkshire had accumulated 6.3 percent of Coca-Cola's
common stock over the ``last several months.''
   Atlanta-based Coca-Cola has about 364 million shares outstanding.
   Buffett said the stake amounted to about 22 million shares,
accumulated by various insurance subsidiaries of Berkshire Hathaway
over the past eight or nine months.
   In his memo to the employees, Goizueta said the investment ``is
in keeping with Berkshire Hathaway's track record of making
long-term investments in companies with a strong consumer franchise
and a focused business.''
   He called it ``a strong vote of confidence and a welcomed
endorsement of our past success and future potential.''
   He also noted that Buffett was ``one of the biggest fans of
Cherry Coke'' and declared it the official soft drink of Berkshire
Hathaway at that company's 1986 annual meeting.
   Buffett acknowledged that he favors the drink, and said he has
been ``very impressed by the international strength of the Coca-Cola
brand and the job that management has done.''
   He said his company had not previously disclosed the stake
because insurance companies are not required to do so until their
holding reaches 10 percent or stands at 5 percent at the end of a
year. Federal rules require other shareholders to disclose a holding
in a company when it reaches 5 percent.
   Coca-Cola is the world's largest soft drink maker. It earned
$1.04 billion, or $2.85 a share, on revenue of $8.34 billion in 1988.
   Berkshire Hathaway Inc., which has about 1.14 million common
shares outstanding, has a stock value of about $5.47 billion based
on its closing price of $4,800 a share Wednesday on the NYSE.
   Buffett, known as much for his folksy wisdom and unpretentious
lifestyle as his financial acumen, has combined a patient,
value-oriented stock strategy with a knack for finding investment
diamonds in the rough.
   Forbes magazine estimates his personal wealth at about $1.4
billion.
   Buffett acquired Berkshire Hathaway, a Massachusetts
cloth-milling concern with $10 million in assets, in the mid-1960s.
Since then he has turned it into a diversified holding company with
about $2 billion in assets.
   Most of Berkshire's operating revenue comes from insurance
operations. The company also has interests in the publisher Buffalo
News Inc., in Washington Post Co. and in Capital Cities-ABC Inc.
</TEXT>
