<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-16 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Climbs Against Yen; Nikkei Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices erased earlier gains and lost ground on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 130.73 yen, up 0.85 yen from Wednesday's
129.88-yen finish. The currency, which opened at 130.68 yen,
fluctuated in a range of 130.60 yen and 130.95 yen.
   Dealers said the currency's strength in Tokyo followed its gain
in New York overnight, inspired by a U.S. Commerce Department report
Wednesday that the nation's trade deficit fell to $9.49 billion in
January from a revised December shortfall of $10.99 billion.
   A Mitsubishi Bank dealer said ``there was no reason to sell the
dollar'' considering the trade figures. Dollar-buying interest
remained strong throughout the day, the dealer said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``Market players' dollar-buying interest will remain strong for a
while,'' the dealer added.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a
376.13-point winner the previous day, erased its gains in the early
session and lost 2.24 points, or 0.007 percent, to finish at
32,098.24.
   After moderate gains in the morning session, trading in the
afternoon became directionless and fell, said a trader with a major
securities firm in Tokyo, also speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Although trading was active, profit-taking by speculative
investors in the afternoon session resulted in the Nikkei's loss, he
added. Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.3 billion
shares.
   ``But demand-supply balance in Tokyo stock market has been
getting better,'' the trader added.
</TEXT>
