<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-16 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Up, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar edged higher in light European
trading early today despite what dealers said was a concerted bout
of dollar-selling by European central banks.
   Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said several central banks, including West Germany's
Bundesbank, intervened together on the open market in efforts to
curb the dollar's recent rise.
   They said the size of the intervention was not immediately clear,
but was large enough to temporarily interrupt the dollar's upward
trend.
   A trader in Rome predicted the central banks would be unable to
dampen bullish interest in the dollar. ``They intervened to put the
brakes on the dollar and to show the market that they are present,''
he said.
   The dollar headed sharply higher Wednesday after the U.S.
government reported that the nation's trade deficit shrank to its
lowest level in three months, from a revised December shortfall of
$10.99 billion to $9.49 billion in January.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.85 Japanese yen to a closing 130.73 yen. Later, in
London, it fell back to 130.27 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates included: 1.8684 West German marks, up from 1.8670; 1.6060
Swiss francs, up from 1.6038; 6.3225 French francs, up from 6.3200;
2.1129 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1065; 1,370.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,369.37; 1.1967 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1935.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7225 from $1.7235 late
Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $390.40 a troy ounce,
down from $392.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $391.
   In Zurich, the noon bid price was $390.70, down from $393.25 bid
late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $5.65 to close at a bid $396.89.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $6.07 a troy
ounce from $6.12 bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
