<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0753EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Budget     03-16 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tax-Committee Members Join Budget Meetings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations over the fiscal 1990 budget are
getting down to the touchy topics of tax increases and entitlement
cuts, but bargainers say decisions are still off on the horizon.
   ``Well, we're going to talk revenues and see where the
conversation takes us,'' House Budget Committee Chairman Leon
Panetta, D-Calif., said Wednesday.
   Although President Bush has promised no new taxes, his $1.16
trillion budget includes $14.2 billion in new revenues that need to
be discussed, Panetta said. That figure includes new ``fees'' for
government services and changes in the tax law that the White House
argues are not tax increases.
   The heads of the House and Senate tax-writing committees were
joining the budget talks for today's meetings. The conversation was
also to touch on entitlement programs under those committees'
jurisdiction.
   Both Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, and Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., have said their panels
would not approve the $5 billion in Medicare cuts requested by Bush.
   Rostenkowski has also nixed Bush's plan to cut the tax rate on
capital gains.
   Bentsen on Wednesday said $7.5 billion of the Bush tax package
was based on items Congress previously rejected or was unlikely to
approve _ the capital gains tax, expanding the Medicare tax, and
repealing a scheduled cut in the airport excise tax.
   ``I find it troubling that the administration, instead of showing
leaderhip on this issue, is effectively leaving it up to Congress to
fill the gap,'' he said.
   ``I know very well the political constraints that the president
is operating under, given the `read my lips _ no new taxes' pledge
he made during the campaign last year,'' Bentsen said. ``But I must
say in all candor ... I'm going to do my best to help him but it's
hard to see how the numbers are going to add up.''
   Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, said the appearance of the tax-writing committees in the
budget talks did not mean that the panel was leaning toward a tax
boost.
   The negotiators wanted to ``ascertain from them what's realistic
by way of spending restraints or what might be realistic by way of
revenue enhancements,'' he said.
   Richard Darman, the director of the Office of Management and
Budget, described the meetings as laying out the options rather than
hard bargaining.
   ``We still haven't really begun what I would call serious
negotiating,'' he said.
   Asked when the hard part would begin, he said, ``I thought it was
going to start a long time ago, and so far it's still going pretty
well,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
