<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Congress     03-16 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Congress,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Sends Bill To End Eastern Walkout To Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation that would force President Bush to
intervene in the Eastern Airlines strike faces stronger opposition
in the Senate, but House passage has already given organized labor a
morale boost.
   The House passed the union-sought measure 252-167 on Wednesday,
largely with the support of the chamber's majority Democrats. Only
20 Republicans supported the legislation, and just 15 Democrats
voted against it.
   President Bush opposes the bill, and Republicans in the Senate
are expected to maneuver to try to block it. That chamber's tricky
procedures often allow a minority of legislators to wreak havoc on
legislation they oppose, and the bill is given only a long-shot
chance at ever becoming law.
   Nonetheless, lobbyists for organized labor, who have rallied
around Eastern's striking unions, say they will push hard for Senate
passage.
   ``We trust they'll take it up,'' Robert M. McGlotten, director of
legislation for the AFL-CIO, said after the House vote.
   The Senate begins a two-week recess after Friday's session, and
supporters of the measure say they would like to see an effort to
take up the bill before the break. Time is a factor in the dispute,
with striking workers needing money to pay their bills and Eastern
already having obtained protection from creditors under the
bankruptcy code's Chapter 11.
   Eastern is demanding $125 million in wage and benefit concessions
from members of its machinists union, which wants $50 million in
improvements. The walkout has forced Eastern to fly only about 100
flights daily, compared to 1,040 before the strike.
   The measure would require a cooling-off period of up to 26 days
and force Bush to appoint an emergency board, which would study the
dispute and recommend a solution. Neither Eastern nor the
8,500-member International Association of Machinists, which began
its walkout March 4, would be required to accept the proposed
formula.
   But even if the measure goes no further than the House, it has
already has cheered labor and its Democratic allies.
   House passage is a morale-booster to the striking machinists and
to Eastern's pilots and flight attendants, who have also walked off
their jobs. It's an indication to the labor movement that after
eight years of rough times under the Reagan administration, it is
still capable of mustering support in Congress.
   And it has forced Bush and Republican lawmakers to appear to be
defending Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent company, Texas
Air Corp. Lorenzo has been accused by workers of trying to break
Eastern's unions and dismantle the company, and his business
practices are often criticized by Democrats and Republicans alike on
Capitol Hill, including Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner.
   Rep. Douglas Bosco, D-Calif., called Lorenzo ``the neutron bomb
of the airline industry, saving assets as booty and taking the
people and letting them go.''
   But Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., told a reporter, ``I haven't
heard any Republican stand up and defend Frank Lorenzo.''
   The bill's opponents say the Eastern walkout has caused
inconvenience but not a transportation emergency that requires
government intervention. They also note that Eastern and the
machinists began bargaining for a new contract in October 1987, and
say there is no reason to believe an emergency board would be
successful.
   Supporters argued that the emergency board would provide cover
for the two sides to be able to accept a solution to their bitter
dispute without appearing to have given in.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
