<FIRST>r f PM-FDA-Generic     03-16 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FDA-Generic,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel to Question Officials in Generic Drug Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional subcommittee wants to question
more than 60 government officials and employees in its investigation
into alleged improprieties in the Food and Drug Administration's
processing of generic drug applications.
   A federal grand jury in Baltimore reportedly is conducting a
criminal investigation into the matter, based on information the
House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on oversight and
investigations uncovered last summer.
   The subcommittee's investigation is proceeding independently of
the criminal investigation, said Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.,
subcommittee chairman, and Rep. Thomas Bliley of Virginia, the
ranking Republican on the panel.
   Dingell said Wednesday that the investigation centers on ``the
question of whether FDA processed generic drug applications fairly
and in accordance with the law.''
   Bliley said the panel's focus ``is on the approval process and
whether or not it has been conducted in a fair and impartial
manner.''
   A report in the Baltimore Sun earlier this week quoted sources as
saying the grand jury was investigating allegations that FDA
employees took bribes and accepted favors to approve companies'
applications to market generic drugs.'' The newspaper quoted one
source familiar with the investigation as saying indictments could
be returned by the end of the month.
   Generic drugs are low-cost versions of brand-name drugs. Once the
patent for a brand-name drug expires, companies can copy the
compound and apply to the FDA for approval of a new generic drug.
   Dingell and Bliley sent a letter to Health and Human Services
Secretary Louis Sullivan, whose department includes FDA, telling him
subcommittee investigators want to question employees at FDA and in
the HHS general counsel's office.
   The lawmakers provided Sullivan with a list of 64 employees the
investigators wanted to interview, but the subcommittee did not
identify them. A subcommittee source said all but four of those on
the list work at FDA and they reach as high in the agency as
Commissioner Frank Young.
   Dingell noted in the press release that ``just because a
government employee is questioned in an investigation of this
magnitude does not imply any wrongdoing on their part.''
   Dingell and Bliley told Sullivan that investigators wanted to
complete the interviews by the end of the month. They also submitted
a list of documents for the department to produce by March 24 and
noted that most items on the list ``have been the subject of
outstanding requests since last summer.''
   FDA spokesman Mike Shaffer said the agency had no comment, but he
said, ``We of course will cooperate with the investigation. The
agency is anxious to have everything resolved.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
