<FIRST>r f PM-Chile-Fruit     03-16 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile-Fruit,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chileans Angered Over Tainted Fruit Incident In U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With millions of pounds of Chilean fruit
being held for testing in U.S. ports because of a cyanide scare,
producers and workers whose livelihoods depend on fruit exports
seethed with anger.
   ``Buy! Buy! Don't believe the gringos' lies!'' a Santiago street
vendor of grapes chanted Wednesday. Some passersby laughed and many
made purchases.
   Producers and union officials say thousands of industry workers
have been laid off as a result of the scare.
   On Monday, the United States urged consumers not to eat Chilean
fruit after two grapes imported from Chile were found to be tainted
with cyanide.
   Most Chilean fruit was pulled from U.S. markets' shelves.
   Similar decisions were taken by Japan and Canada and several
western European countries said they were tightening controls on
Chilean fruit.
   Chilean exporters, growers and packers voluntarily suspended all
operations Tuesday for 72 hours to allow thousands of crates of
stored fruit to be checked.
   The National Exporters Association said Wednesday that ``not a
trace'' of any alien substance had been found in the crates of fruit
ready for export that had so far been checked.
   Officials of Chile's military government say preliminary
estimates indicate the crisis could cost Chile at least $800
million. Nearly 65 percent of Chile's fruit exports _ grapes,
melons, apples and peaches _ go to the United States and the country
is at the peak of its fruit harvesting season.
   The U.S. and Japanese embassies in Santiago received anonymous
telephone calls earlier this month saying fruit exports would be
poisoned. An investigation turned up nothing, authorities said.
   The Chilean agriculture minister, Jaime de la Sotta, says the
cyanide found in the two grapes in Philadelphia on March 2 amounted
to 0.52 parts per million. U.S. officials said a child would have to
eat 2,000 grapes to ingest a fatal dose.
   Wednesday afternoon, several of the nation's leading fruit
exporters toured the capital's center street with pick-up trucks
loaded with fruit, and gave away grapes and apples to the public.
Hundreds of people enthusiastically ate them. Organizers said the
idea was to show the world Chilean fruit is safe.
   Most Chilean fruit enters the United States through the port of
Philadelphia, others through Miami, Los Angeles and Tampa, Fla.
   Boats containing hundreds of thousands of crates of Chilean fruit
awaited off Tampa as fruit inspections continued.
   In Philadelphia, Food and Drug Administration officials completed
sampling Wednesday of the 362,000 crates of grapes and other fruit
from Chile. No further contamination was found.
   In Chile, the president of the Central Bank, Enrique Seguel,
called the decision to remove the fruit from U.S. stores ``totally
out of proportion.''
   Domingo Duran, president of the National Farm Producers
Association, said nearly 40,000 workers had been laid off by
Wednesday, but union leaders put the figure at 17,000 workers.
   ``The consequences of the thoughtless U.S. decision are worse
than those of several earthquakes,'' Duran told a Wednesday news
conference. ``It is totally irresponsible to react like that because
of two tainted grapes, just two grapes, not two clusters.''
   ``I directly accuse the United States of paving the way to
terrorism against the international food trade in the future,''
Duran said.
   He said the U.S. decision will encourage terrorists in the
future. The Chilean govenment officialy blamed the tainting of the
grapes to ``terrorism backed by the Communist Party.'' The
communists denied the charge.
   Angry reactions came from other quarters, too.
   Alvaro Bardon, president of the state-owned State Bank, called
the U.S. decision ``an agression, almost an act of war.''
   He blamed ``certain sectors of the State Department,'' which he
said were influenced by Chilean opposition politicians.
   Scores of citizens interviewed by radio and TV stations also
strongly criticized the U.S. decision, calling it exaggerated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
