<FIRST>r f PM-CasinoGambling     03-16 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Casino Gambling,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ohio House OKs Casino Gambling Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT E. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State representatives have approved a bill
that could make Ohio the third state to legalize casino gambling.
   The proposal approved by the House 57-42 Wednesday would limit
the operation to a five-year pilot project in the northeastern Ohio
city of Lorain.
   The bill was sent to the Senate, where a Democratic leader
predicted passage, but Democratic Gov. Richard Celeste refused to
say whether he would approve the proposal.
   Senate Minority Leader Harry Meshel, a Democrat, said he thinks
the bill could provide a badly needed economic boost for northeast
Ohio, ``and I haven't heard a lot of opposition to it. I think it's
going to pass.''
   New Jersey and Nevada are the only states that have legalized
casino gambling.
   Debate in the House involved claims that the bill would damage
the state's image and hurt its economy.
   Republican Rep. James Petro argued that industries considering
locating in Ohio might look elsewhere out of family and community
considerations. Gambling does not provide ``real jobs or real
growth,'' he contended.
   Backers of the legislation said that an envisioned $300 million
casino will have a major impact on the state's economy _ not only in
Lorain but all across northern Ohio, including Cleveland, 40 miles
to the east.
   The bill provides that if voters in Lorain approve of the
venture, the casino would be overseen by a state commission of five
members to be named by the governor.
</TEXT>
