<FIRST>r f PM-Shuttle-Newspaper     03-16 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Newspaper,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discovery Astronauts Get the Morning Paper</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovery's astronauts today enjoyed
the first home delivery in space of an American newspaper.
   A facsimile machine flying in orbit for the first time was used
to send Discovery a copy of the front page of The Roundup, an
employee weekly at the Johnson Space Center. And it was delivered in
space before it was delivered on the ground.
   The issue had been rushed into print by editor Kelly Humphries so
that it could be sent to the space shuttle today. The paper will not
be distributed on Earth until Friday.
   Discovery astronaut Dr. James M. Bagian stopped his work in space
long enough to read the newspaper and comment to Mission Control.
   ``Thanks for the home paper here, the Roundup,'' he said.
   ``We wanted to tell you that's the first newspaper that's been
sent to an American spacecraft,'' replied Pierre Thuot, capsule
communicator at Mission Control.
   ``It's a good thing that it's you who is there because if it was
Dave (Low) I would expect that he would have sent me up the Wall
Street Journal,'' joked Bagian. Low, who is known to take an
interest in finance, is capsule communicator on an earlier shift.
   The first newspaper in space carried a lead story about the
Discovery launch on Monday and a story at the bottom of the page
about a welcome home ceremony at Johnson for the five-man crew,
which returns on Saturday.
   There also was a story about American-Soviet cooperation in the
exploration of space and a feature about the value of Earth photos
taken by shuttle astronauts.
   The facsimile machine aboard the shuttle is used to send
instructions and daily schedules to the astronauts.
</TEXT>
