<FIRST>s f BC-ContraBoom Adv19   03-16 0970</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Contra Boom, Adv 19,0998</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>REPEAT FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, March 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Locals Profit From Contra Presence, Hope Fighting Is Over</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TEG1 of Feb. 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS TROJES, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contra army stranded near here
may be a headache for diplomats and a political problem in the
United States, but it has also brought a minor economic boom to the
isolated valleys of eastern Honduras.
   ``I'm doing very well. Nowadays all is calm,'' said Eulogio
Chavez Montoya, owner of the Vendita Miraflores store, pointing to
racks of cowboy boots at 80 lempiras each _ about $27 at the black
market rate.
   Buildings throughout town are freshly painted and small stores
are packed with everything from soccer balls to corn flakes.
Families that never had electricity own generators, drink
refrigerated Cokes and watch ``Cagney and Lacey'' via satellite
dishes.
   The boom began a little more than a year ago, when the U.S.
Congress cut military aid to the Nicaraguan rebels trying to topple
the leftist Sandinista government led by President Daniel Ortega.
   The Contras filtered out of Nicaragua as they exhausted supplies;
about 11,000 fighters and thousands of family members now are living
in camps a few miles from the border, supported by U.S. aid.
   Many local Hondurans, who in thploded, killing one of her nieces and
wounding four other children.
   Farther from the camps, the most common complaint about the
Contra presence was drunken driving. ``I guess since they can't
fight they have to entertain themselves,'' said Cesar Rodas, 21, of
Danli.
   Valentin Valladardes, who started a tire repair business in Danli
with a rented air compressor, said he was trying to ride out an
industry shakeout _ too many people competing for truck drivers'
business.
   His wife said Honduran criminals escape justice by joining the
rebels; a Contra mechanic heatedly replied that the Contras are
being blamed for anything that goes wrong within 50 miles.
   The 100 families of Capiri turned into refugees themselves in
1985, when there was frequent fighting in the border region.
   ``We had to get out of here,'' said Jose Medina, a 63-year-old
storeowner. ``Now, there's more confidence in being able to work.''
   ``It's all up to President Bush,'' Medina added. ``Tell him not
to turn up the flame.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, March 19</NOTE>
