<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-Hayman Adv19   03-16 0926</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Hayman, Adv 19,0961</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>REPEAT FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, March 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Perfume Czar Hopes To Build House Of Fragrances Starting With 273
Address</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY301 of March 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred Hayman's blueprint for building the first
American ``house of fragrances'' specifies a pyramid-shaped
cornerstone.
   Hayman, the man behind one of the perfume industry's most
successful scents, is introducing a new concoction that he thinks
may create an even bigger splash than Giorgio Beverly Hills.
   His new fragrance is called ``273'' for the address on Rodeo
Drive of the sumptuous Beverly Hills boutique that was the
birthplace of the Giorgio perfume. It comes in a crystal flacon
designed by Hayman in a pyramid shape.
   If his dreams of 273's popularity come true, Hayman says he
intends to expand his fragrance collection under the provisional
banner Clientele Privee, his interpretation of a Parisian perfumery.
   But Hayman doesn't want an exact repeat of the Giorgio success
story.
   That fragrance family, which he sold to cosmetics and toiletries
company Avon for $165 million in 1987, became phenomenally popular
after its debut in 1981. Despite Hayman's emphasis on exclusivity,
Giorgio eventually became widely available in department stores and
elsewhere, losing some allure in the process.
   Hayman says it was difficult to resist demands from retail
outlets clamoring to stock Giorgio.``But I will this time because
I'm convinced small is beautiful,'' says the man who pioneered the
use of ``scent strips'' in magazines, as a come-on for Giorgio.
   At first, 273 will be sold solely through the boutique that has
been rechristened ``Fred Hayman Beverly Hills.''
   It's pricey, having an elevated ``prestige'' status among its
perfume peers. One ounce of the perfume costs $185 and 2.5 ounces of
the cologne goes for $45.
   If demand for 273 takes off, Hayman will face some ticklish
marketing.
   Prestige products pose sales-pitch paradoxes. People who fancy
such goods _ from perfumes to watches to the latest exotic dog breed
_ typically don't want things just anybody can buy.
   So, from a merchandizing standpoint, the problem becomes one of
satisfying demand enough to stimulate interest but not so much that
the product loses the special cachet that scarcity supplies.
   Moreover, the availability of prestige perfumes is overflowing.
Movie stars, from Elizabeth Taylor to Cher, clothing designers and
entertainers have added their own contributions to the gushing
stream of new products.
   A footnote to the recent history of numerous perfume
introductions is the U.S. debut in March of fragrances by Bic Corp.,
of throwaway razor, ballpoint pen and cigarette lighter fame.
   Andrew Shore, who follows the scent business for Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., says the lifespan of perfumes is frequently as short as
12 to 24 months. If a fragrance lingers for four years or so, it is
considered a franchise from which successful spinoff products can be
derived.
   ``Incredibly saturated'' is how Shore describes the market,
adding that it is polarized with ultra high-priced items at one
extreme and mass market stuff at the other.
   Unit sales have fallen for the past five years, he says. Modest
growth in sales' value occurred because new fragrances fetch
increasingly higher prices. He estimates retail sales rose to $3.25
billion in 1988, up from $3.15 billion a year earlier.
   Hayman has a simple answer to whether 273 will rise to the top.
   ``There's always a market for the best,'' he said during an
interview while on one of his frequent trips to New York.
   273 is described as a flowery, fruity, spicy blend of more than
250 ingredients, with the key ones being gardenia, tuberose and
jasmine. Its components are expensive and so is its packaging.
   The crystal, pyramid-shaped bottle is embossed with a 24 karat
gold line surrounding the stopper. Bright yellow, reminiscent of the
Giorgio hue and Hayman's favorite color, and fire-engine red are
used for 273, as well as for the Beverly Hills store.
   During a conversation, Hayman, who left his native Switzerland
for the United States in 1941 and speaks Swiss, French and English,
gives the impression he would rather not know the word ``discount''
in any language.
   His boutique, which claims to have the highest sales per square
foot of any store in the country, never marks down prices on
merchandise. For more than 20 years of running the store, Hayman has
had the good fortune to discover little-known designers who
cultivated big followings, such as Halston.
   The boutique was originally called Giorgio by George Grant who
decided to Italianize his name because Italian imports accounted for
much of the clothing carried in the shop. Hayman bought out Grant
and another partner in the mid-1960s.
   Hayman seems to embody Beverly Hills. He owns a vintage Rolls
Royce and is definitely a have, not a have-not.
   Recently, he appeared fit and pleasantly tanned, clad in a
expensively styled suit. Recovering from back surgery required after
years of jogging, he was more comfortable standing through an
hour-long interview in his suite at a chic hotel on the east side of
Manhattan's Central Park.
   When his former wife, Gale, came up with the idea that blossomed
into Giorgio perfume, Hayman was disinterested. ``At first, I
thought it was not a good idea.'' He says he doesn't normally wear
fragrances himself but now the business is in his blood.
   At 63, Hayman says he has no intention of retiring anytime soon
and hopes to establish his Clientele Privee _ French for private
client _ as a perfume powerhouse.
   End adv for Sunday, March 19.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
