<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     03-16 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0368</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices climbed today, propelled by new
evidence of a slackening in economic growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.21 to 2,322.75 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 438 up, 260 down and
495 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 27.87 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Federal Reserve reported this morning that industrial
production was unchanged in February from the month before.
   A separate government report showed a decline of 0.2 percentage
points, to 84.3 percent, in capacity utilization of the nation's
production facilities.
   Analysts said those figures were read by traders as evidence of
an easing in the strains the economy has been exerting on inflation
and interest rates.
   However, brokers also noted persistent uneasiness about Friday's
impending report on the producer price index for February. A 1
percent increase in the index during January unsettled both the
stock and bond markets.
   A further complication for the immediate market outlook was the
``triple witching hour'' taking place on Friday, when the last
trading occurs in a series of stock-index options and futures.
   There was talk on the Street that this quarterly phenomenon could
produce more volatility than recent similar occasions, since the
pace of computer program trading by professionals using these
contracts appears to have revived lately.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up \ at
46[; Exxon, up [ at 45|; USX, up \ at 32], and International
Business Machines, up ] at 117].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.33 to 167.00. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .19 at 331.98.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average gained 14.29 to
2,320.54.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 787 up, 596 down and 541 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 167.07 million shares, against 139.97
million in the previous session.
