<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ThirdWorldDebt 1stLd-Writethru   03-16 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Third World Debt, 1st Ld-Writethru,0801</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with testimony; picks up 4th graf pvs, Brady
unveiled.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, which is asking banks
to forgive voluntarily part of the $410 billion debt owed by Third
World countries, opposes establishing an international agency that
could require writing off some of the loans, Congress was told today.
   Assistant Treasury Secretary David Mulford, the principal
architect of the voluntary debt-forgiveness plan, said such an
agency would cause more interruptions in the repayment of loans and
interest and further reduce the value of the loans in secondary
markets.
   Congress last year directed President Reagan to explore setting
up an International Debt Management Authority that could require
renegotiation of the loans on more favorable terms to developing
countries. Many lenders have been able to get only 40 percent of the
loans' face value in selling them to other lenders.
   ``We have concluded after months of study that debt reduction and
debt service reduction can be successfully accomplished in the
marketplace,'' Mulford told the Senate Banking Committee's
subcommittee on international finance and monetary policy.
   ``We believe that (a) market-oriented approach...addresses
congressional concerns with less risk to tax-payers'' than a new
international agency would, he said.
   The panel's chairman, Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., praised the
administration for recognizing the necessity of forgiving some of
the debt.
   ``To paraphrase Winston Churchill, this is not so much the
beginning of the end, or even the end of the beginning, but it is
perhaps the beginning of the beginning,'' Sarbanes said.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady told the House Ways and Means
Committee on Wednesday that many of the details are likely to be
worked out only after individual negotiations begin with some of the
major Third World debtors, major U.S. economic allies, banks and
international institutions.
   Brady unveiled the plan in a speech last Friday in which he
conceded that the so-called 1985 Baker Plan, named for his
predecessor at Treasury and now Secretary of State James A Baker
III, had largely failed in solving the Third World debt crisis.
   Instead of asking banks to forgive a portion of their loans to
impoverished, debt-saddled nations in Latin America, the Baker plan
called on them to write new loans for countries willing to make
government enterprises private and institute austerity programs.
   Many countries did, but few new loans were written by private
banks. And much of the new money that did come forth from
international lending institutions such as the World Bank was used
by many debtor nations to pay the interest on their loans to private
banks.
   Brady suggested U.S. banks could be encouraged to forgive a
portion of their loans with guarantees that the World Bank or the
International Monetary Fund would provide, if necessary, money to
the debtor countries to make interest payments on their remaining
balances.
   ``At least you're moving in the right direction _ decreasing
their debt instead of increasing it,'' Rep. Thomas Downey, D-N.Y., a
member of the Ways and Means Committee, told Brady.
   In outlining the new plan, Brady said only through voluntary debt
and debt-service reduction can some developing countries ever hope
to restore their credit worthiness.
   Bush did not publicly endorse the new plan until Tuesday, raising
questions about whether the initiative was Brady's alone or had the
backing of the full administration.
   Brady acknowledged Wednesday there was some ``confusion'' in the
administration, but said his speech outlining the new strategy had
been approved in advance by the president.
   Major U.S. lender banks have vigorously resisted efforts by some
lawmakers, among them Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., to force them to
write off a portion of their Third World debts.
   ``Across-the-board mandatory solutions are simply not the
answer,'' William Rhodes, head of debt restructuring at Citicorp
told the House Banking Committee earlier this year.
   He said imposed debt forgiveness ``would seriously retard'' the
ability of Third World debtors to return for new loans.
   But with riots two weeks ago in Venezuela over austerity programs
and radical political movements on both the left and right
threatening many fragile Latin democracies, the Bush administration
is now looking at Third World debt as a national security issue as
well as an economic one.
   U.S. banks now hold $97.7 billion of Third World debt, compared
with nearly $140 billion six and one-half years ago when the crisis
was precipitated by Mexico stopping interest payments on its debt
because of plummeting oil prices.
   The six largest borrowers _ Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Mexico,
Venezuela and the Philippines _ now owe those nine banks some $47
billion, less than the $65 billion of their combined capital bases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890316-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f AM-AdBreakup Adv19 1stLd-Writethru 03-16 1167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ad Breakup, Adv 19, 1st Ld-Writethru,1206</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, March 19</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Year-Old Bustup of Lord Geller Ad House Leaves Bitter Taste</BYLINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to make it walked sted stalked.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been a year since rebellious executives
walked out of advertising agency Lord Geller Federico Einstein Inc.
to start their own, a split that has left two emotionally scarred
rivals and courtroom accusations of business sabotage.
   Lord Geller's biggest client, International Business Machines
Corp., took its business elsewhere. A legal dispute on the breakup
remains unresolved. Two agencies now use the Lord name in their
logos.
   Moreover, Lord Geller and the new agency, Lord Einstein O'Neill &amp;
Partners, combined handle only about 60 percent of the business and
employ only about two-thirds as many people as Lord Geller did
before the breakup.
   The saga has drawn attention outside the advertising world
because it has raised questions about the impact of executive
defections in other service industries such as law and accounting.
   Some ad agency folks took delight in the courage the breakaway
executives showed in leaving, citing a desire for autonomy. But at
the same time, they sympathized with those left behind.
   A marketing consultant who advises advertisers about selecting an
ad agency said the lingering legal controversy about the breakup may
be frightening some potential clients from considering either agency.
   ``In making a search for a new agency, a company is looking for a
long term, stable relationship, and I think both agencies at the
moment are viewed as kind of unstable agencies,'' said Stanley
Canter of Canter Achenbaum Associates.
   Lord Geller, however, insists it has stabilized with billings of
$50 million and a payroll of 100 people, down from $212 million in
billings and 320 employees before the breakup.
   Billings reflect the amount of money advertisers pay for
broadcast and published ads. Agencies often get a percentage of
billings for their work.
   Lord Einstein said its growth from zero to $75 million in
billings and 82 employees in its first year makes it one of the
fastest growing startups.
   Of those employed at Lord Geller before the breakup, between 65
and 70 still work there while about 40 are working for Lord
Einstein. About 210 have gone elsewhere, either because they were
laid off or quit.
   Ad industry analysts say the deep pockets of Lord Geller's
parent, the Britain-based WPP Group, may guarantee its survival.
WPP's chief executive Martin Sorrell is believed to be committed to
maintaining Lord Geller as a second ad network separate from WPP's
other agency, J. Walter Thompson Co.
   Lord Einstein also has a powerful partner, the ad agency Young &amp;
Rubicam, which holds a 49 percent stake in the new agency.
   Richard J. Lord helped found Lord Geller Federico Einstein Inc.
in 1967. Five years later, Lord and his partners sold the agency to
J. Walter Thompson.
   The agency probably is best-known for its IBM work, especially
the campaign that used the Charlie Chaplin ``Little Tramp''
character to show how IBM's personal computers can bring order to
the most chaotic businesses.
   Along with Thompson, Lord Geller was purchased as part of WPP
Group's unsolicited $566 million acquisition of JWT Group Inc. in
July 1987.
   Lord and other top executives of Lord Geller chafed under
Sorrell's rule, and after Sorrell rejected a buyout proposal, they
decided to leave.
   On March 18, 1988, Lord and another Lord Geller founder, Arthur
W. Einstein Jr., joined four other Lord Geller executives in the
walkout, leaving only a memo to announce their resignations to the
people they left behind.
   The 63-year-old Lord, whose plans to retire at age 64 were put on
hold indefinitely with the new agency startup, concedes it was ``a
terrible way to do it'' but said his lawyers advised against telling
the staff in person.
   J. William Wardell, the only member of the seven-person
management committee at Lord Geller who did not defect, recalls
hearing a roar build outside his office as copies of the memo were
dropped outside each door.
   He promptly assembled a group to keep the agency running and
contacted clients about what had occurred.
   Within three weeks, Lord Einstein hired about 40 people, most of
them Lord Geller colleagues who wanted to join their old bosses, and
signed ex-Lord Geller clients WNBC-TV and The New Yorker magazine.
   Sorrell sued the defecting managers, accusing them of a
conspiracy to sabotage their old agency. The executives denied it. A
New York state court judge barred Lord Einstein from signing Lord
Geller clients.
   But as of this past week the judge had not entered a final ruling
and had not dealt with the phase of the case in which damages, if
any, will be determined.
   Within a month of the breakaway, Sorrell appointed Wardell as
president of Lord Geller and hired two outsiders to help him run the
agency, Agi Clark of N.W. Ayer and Tim Elliott of Ogilvy &amp; Mather.
   Ms. Clark said she was enticed by the challenge of proving wrong
``everybody who thought it was going to fall apart.''
   In the next few months, Anne Klein II fashions, The Wall Street
Journal and a division of Fuji Photo Film Co. left Lord Geller. But
Schieffelin &amp; Somerset Co. kept its Hennessey cognac there, as did
the Contel Corp. corporate account.
   Lord Einstein, meanwhile, got special projects from IBM with the
court's consent and added a $30 million account from Saab Scania of
North America.
   Both agencies were shut out, however, when IBM took its $100
million account to two other agencies in September. IBM accounted
for about half of Lord Geller's billings.
   Eight days after that decision, Lord Geller laid off 90 people,
trying to cushion the blow by giving fired employees three months
severance pay. Another layoff in December and attrition reduced the
work force further.
   Lord Geller shifted sights to new business. It landed a Lederle
Laboratories drug account, Sheridan home furnishing and Contel
telephone operations. Travel, publishing, computers, fashion and
financial services are areas Lord Geller is pursuing.
   Lord Einstein reached the breakeven point in January, Lord said,
and is on the hunt for clients in food, travel, fashion and high
technology.
   Lord said his group had no way of knowing when they left that his
old agency would lose clients and have to trim the payroll so much.
   ``What we left there was a healthy agency,'' Lord said. He blames
the post-breakup problems on Sorrell.
   But even at that, Lord said he tries to keep tabs on what has
happened to his former employees and said nearly all have found
other ad jobs.
   So how does he feel about having his name on two agency doors?
``I don't feel any better about it than Martin does,'' Lord said.
   Lord Geller considered changing its name but decided against it.
``Our victory will be all the sweeter with the same name,'' said Ms.
Clark.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 19</NOTE>
