<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Jaguar     03-16 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Jaguar,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automaker Posts Large Profit Drop, Worker Approve Package</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaguar PLC, the British luxury car maker, said
Thursday its 1988 earnings fell 54 percent because North American
results were hurt by the weak dollar.
   Meanwhile, Jaguar car workers voted to accept the company's
latest pay offer, ending a strike threat at the Coventry plant, the
company said.
   Jaguar said 4,497 workers approved the two-year pay package, and
3,527 rejected it. The company offered rises of about 4.7 percent in
the first year and 4.4 percent in the second, plus bonuses.
   The workers had threatened weekly one-day strikes and refusal to
work overtime.
   In its earnings report, Jaguar said earnings for the year totaled
28.4 million pounds or $48.8 million, equivalent to 27 cents a
share, vs. 61.3 million pounds or $105 million, equivalent to 58
cents a share, in 1987.
   Sales rose 7.3 percent to 1.075 billion pounds or $1.85 billion,
compared with 1.002 billion pounds or $1.72 billion a year earlier,
bolstered by strong sales in Europe and Asia, it said.
   Jaguar said the weak dollar reduced last year's earnings after
taxes by about $77 million.
   Plans to offset the impact of a weak dollar in 1988 ``were only
partially successful,'' the company said. These plans included
increased output and sales, competitive pricing, and higher
productivity.
   Last year, while overall sales rose 8 percent to 51,939 units,
U.S. sales slipped 9 percent to 20,727 units, and Canadian car sales
fell 19 percent to 2,154 units, the company said.
   The company has reduced its dependence on the U.S. market. Last
year, about 45 percent of sales came from the United States,
compared with 65 percent in 1986.
   In Britain, sales rose a strong 31 percent, and sales on the
European continent advanced about 20 percent.
   ``There will be more satisfactory profits in the near future and
we'll be able to tackle challenging exchange rates,'' Chairman John
Egan said.
   ``Faced with the difficult hurdle of exchange rates we are doing
a competent job,'' Egan said. ``But we need to become more efficient
and make sure we become as cost-effective as out key competitors.''
   Jaguar did not provide quarterly or half-year results and is not
required to under British law.
</TEXT>
