<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices gained ground today, propelled by
new evidence of a slackening in economic growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.85 to 2,328.39 by
11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 657 up, 480 down and
584 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 59.54 million shares at
midmorning.
   The Federal Reserve reported that industrial production was
unchanged in February from the month before.
   A separate government report showed a decline of 0.2 percentage
points, to 84.3 percent, in capacity utilization of the nation's
production facilities.
   Analysts said those figures were read by some traders as evidence
of an easing in the strains the economy has been exerting on
inflation and interest rates.
   However, brokers also noted a persistent mood of caution about
Friday's impending report on the producer price index for February.
A 1 percent increase in the index during January unsettled both the
stock and bond markets.
   A further complication for the immediate market outlook was the
``triple witching hour'' due on Friday, when the last trading occurs
in a series of stock-index options and futures.
   There was talk on the Street that this quarterly phenomenon could
produce more volatility than recent similar occasions, since the
pace of computer program trading by professionals using these
contracts appears to have revived lately.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up [ at
46; USX, up \ at 32], and International Business Machines, up 1[ at
118[.
   Pacificorp led the active list, up | at 34|. The stock was added
to Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock composite index, prompting buying by
funds set up to parallel the performance of the index.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.55 to 167.22. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .06 at 331.85.
</TEXT>
