<FIRST>r f BC-Iran-Oil     03-16 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Iran-Oil,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Iranian Seismic Tests Reveal Large Offshore Reserves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian said Thursday that new oil
reserves found in the Persian Gulf will help boost Iranian off-shore
oil production to 700,000 barrels a day within four years, state-run
Tehran radio reported.
   A broadcast by state-run Tehran radio, monitored in Nicosia,
quoted Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh as telling a news conference
that seismic testing in Iranian waters off the coasts of Qatar, Ras
Al Khaimah, Sharjah, Dubai and Saudi Arabia had located huge
reserves of oil and natural gas.
   At their peak in the 1970s, Iran's offshore fields had a total
capacity of more than 700,000 barrels of oil per day. But many
facilities were wrecked during the 8-year Iran-Iraq war with
offshore production falling to its current level of 230,000 barrels
of oil per day.
   Iran has been attempting to rebuild its oil industry since a
United Nations-mediated cease-fire Aug. 20.
</TEXT>
