<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-SpottedOwl 2ndLd-Writethru   03-16 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spotted Owl, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lujan Calls For Changing Endangered Species Law to Consider Economics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead. SUBS grafs 9-10, `Reaction among ...' with two
grafs to CLARIFY that Adams comments were made in response to a query two
days before Lujan's remarks.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DERMOT COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan says federal law
should allow economic considerations to be taken into account in
deciding whether to protect species like the northern spotted owl.
   ``I'm told, on the one hand, that I want to protect an endangered
species,'' he told the Seattle Post-Intelligencer on Wednesday. ``On
the other hand, I hear that's going to devastate the entire
Northwest lumber industry.
   ``How do we solve that problem? I believe we should be able to
take economic considerations into account.''
   Lujan's comments, made in Washington, D.C., came the same day a
federal judge refused to delay the sale of timber on as much as
50,000 acres of U.S. Forest Service land in Washington state and
Oregon that is home to the spotted owl.
   U.S. District Judge William Dwyer's ruling left forest service
plans for protecting the owl in effect pending trial on an effort by
environmentalists to preserve even more habitat. Timber companies
say the current set-asides are excessive.
   The forest service is in the Agriculture Department, outside
Lujan's control. But Lujan said he expects to receive
recommendations May 1 from the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service on
whether to list the owl as endangered.
   Such a designation, sought by environmentalists to protect
forests in the Pacific Northwest from logging, could mean the loss
of thousand of jobs in the region, timber industry officials have
said.
   ``Maybe we should change the law'' to consider such economic
factors, Lujan said. He added that ``the spotted owl business is
probably the prime example.''
   Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., responding to a query on Monday, said
a legislative proposal along the lines Lujan suggested on Wednesday
``would create a national furor'' and ``turn the rest of the country
against you.''
   ``I don't think such an effort (to change the Endangered Species
Act) would get anywhere in Congress,'' he said.
   Similar views were expressed by Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., whose
district leads the nation in the harvest of national forest timber.
He said log exports rather than environmental laws have caused
domestic timber shortages.
   ``I think there will be a natural, emotional reaction to demand
that the spotted owl be exempt from the Endangered Species Act,''
said DeFazio. ``It's a simple solution _ blame the owl _ but some
people are bashing the environment as a smoke screen.''
   Dwyer also rejected a request by the Washington Contract Loggers
Association to stop the forest service from reducing the allowable
timber cut. That issue, too, should be resolved at trial or in
negotiations, he said.
   The judge asked all parties to state by March 29 what should be
done to resolve the issue. The suit, filed Feb. 8, claimed the
agency's owl management plan failed to set aside enough land to
protect the bird.
   ``I'm really delighted with the decision because it buys us time,
which I feel is what we need,'' said Rep. Jolene Unsoeld.
   Unsoeld said in a telephone interview from Washington, D.C., that
small mill owners, labor and environmentalists have indicated a
willingness to discuss how to maintain a ``sustainable timber
industry, as well as achieve some of the environmental objectives.''
   Todd True, an attorney for the Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund,
said environmentalists were reviewing their options.
   ``The biological evidence is that the owl is at the threshold of
extinction and that it can not afford to lose additional habitat,''
he said.
   The forest service plan, approved in December, called for
designation of 374,000 acres of mature and old-growth timber in 13
national forests as habitat for what the agency estimates are 2,000
breeding pairs of spotted owls in Washington and Oregon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
