<DOCNO> AP890316-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AT&amp;T-RateCaps 1stLd-Writethru   03-16 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AT&amp;T-Rate Caps, 1st Ld-Writethru,0880</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Abolishes AT&amp;T Long-Distance Rate Regulations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with action; picks up 4th graf pvs, Congressional
concern.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission today
abolished regulations by which American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.
has set long-distance rates for more than two decades.
   The unanimous commission vote, which came after two years of
hearings and filings from consumer groups, Congress and the
telephone industry, would replace AT&amp;T's so-called rate-of-return
regulations on July 1 with a formula designed to drive rates down
and save consumers an estimated $900 million over four years.
   FCC Chairman Dennis Patrick described the commission action as
``a major milestone...in our approach to, our understanding of the
regulatory process.''
   He said it was time to move on from the rate-of-return process
established for the old Bell System in the 1960s.
   ``We simply can no longer have a regulatory approach that was
crafted in the 1960s, to use that system in the 1990s and beyond. It
is simply outdated,'' he said.
   Commissioner Patricia Diaz Dennis said she favored the plan but
with some concern, particularly over a provision that would limit
how far AT&amp;T could lower its long-distance rates. But she said, ``I
do support this grand experiment.''
   Commissioner James Quello also said he had concerns about the
floors on AT&amp;T rates, and said he hoped they could be lifted quickly
in future FCC rulings. But he described rate caps as ``a
precedent-setting issue that is really going to benefit the
public.'' He said the rate cap plan was ``long overdue.''
   Patrick said local telephone companies will not come under the
rate cap plan at this point, but that they would be included by July
1, 1990. He said the commission was going to accept further public
comment on that issue and asked the local companies to submit plans
to use rate caps by May 17.
   Patrick said he thought he had calmed the waters in Congress over
rate caps, where there has been great concern that residential
consumers would not be well-protected, particularly rural telephone
users.
   Patrick maintains the plan would save consumers $900 million by
letting AT&amp;T establish its interstate prices under a prescribed
formula.
   But the so-called price caps proposal may be derailed in
Congress, where opposition ranges from outright hostility to the
view that the plan could be salvaged if it included better
safeguards for consumers _ particularly rural telephone users.
   Congressional concern over rate caps, which Patrick first
proposed in a speech more than two years ago, caused him to postpone
a vote on the plan in January.
   He tried to assuage congressional concerns about consumers this
week in a lengthy response to a set of questions from Sen. Daniel K.
Inouye, D-Hawaii, who chairs the communications subcommittee of the
Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
   On the House side, Energy and Commerce Chairman John Dingell,
D-Mich., and Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., who chairs the
telecommunications and finance subcommittee, have been openly
critical of Patrick's proposal.
   A House subcommittee member, Rep. Jim Cooper, D-Tenn., introduced
legislation earlier this month that would prevent implementation of
price caps until Congress can study the proposal more thoroughly.
   Cooper said he wanted explicit assurances in the plan that
universal telephone service and subsidies for high-cost telephone
service in remote areas would be maintained and that long-distance
rates would not rise disproportionately in those remote areas.
   Since the 1960s, AT&amp;T has been subject to so-called
rate-of-return regulation that allows it a certain profit beyond
costs. Currently, AT&amp;T can earn about 12 percent above its expenses.
   Patrick's plan would allow AT&amp;T to raise its rates 3 percent less
than the rate of inflation _ in effect a 3 percent cut _ with an
additional 2 percent reduction for residential and small business
users.
   But if AT&amp;T could lower its expenses under such a system, its
profits would increase.
   Rates would be set on three categories, or ``baskets'' of AT&amp;T
service: residential and small business; 800 services; and all other
business services. Within the residential-small business basket,
prices in the individual categories could not increase by more then
5 percent plus the change in inflation rate.
   Rep. Rick Boucher, D-Va., said at a hearing last month on the
plan that the FCC should require AT&amp;T to share with customers half
of any windfall profits arising from the plan.
   Another subcommittee member, Rep. Tom Tauke, R-Iowa, said the
revised plan had removed ``floors'' on prices in each of the
categories. The plan, as outlined by Patrick, only would maintain
ceilings on how high such prices could go.
   Tauke said that without floors AT&amp;T possibly could lower prices
far enough to drive out competition, but Patrick said floors could
discourage AT&amp;T from increasing efficiency to lower prices.
   Patrick's plan would cover all dominant interstate carriers. For
AT&amp;T specificially, it would cap prices for a period of four years.
   The 3 percent reduction would be imposed after adjustments for
cost changes outside of AT&amp;T's control, such as the charges that
local phone companies require AT&amp;T to pay to connnect with the local
phone networks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
