<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   03-16 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0259</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed to
slightly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The possibility of broken contracts were blamed for the early
downside pressure on both commodities. A report in the bean pits was
that Pakistan would not follow through on a 99,000-ton purchase of
soy oil, and that gloom spread across the bean market.
   Traders said wheat should have received some support after a
one-day tour of the Kansas fields showed the winter wheat crop in
poor shape. But dampening any upside move was a rumor that China
will cancel a 270,000-ton buy of new-crop wheat.
   On the open, wheat was unchanged to 1\ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery at $4.38{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents lower to
{ cent higher, with March at $2.78\ a bushel; oats were 1\ cents
lower to unchanged, with March aqt $2.07 a bushel; and soybeans were
unchanged to 1{ cents higher, with March at $7.68 a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were mostly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .77 cent lower, with April at 77.20
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent to .60 cent lower, with
March at 80.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .65 cent lower to .15
higher, with April at 43.17 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies
were .27 cent to .75 cents lower; with March at 37.40 cents a pound.
