<FIRST>u f BC-Tyson-Holly     03-16 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tyson-Holly,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson Increases Offer for Holly Farms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc., the largest poultry
producer in the country, on Thursday sweetened its offer for Holly
Farms by more than $60 million to total $1.11 billion cash.
   The raised offer, from $60 a share to $63.50, came a few weeks
before Holly Farms shareholders were scheduled to meet to consider a
rival deal with ConAgra Inc., to acquire Holly Farms in a stock swap
valued at $1 billion.
   Holly Farms, based in Memphis, Tenn., has been fighting Tyson's
attempted takeover since last fall. The company's board said it
would consider Tyson's latest offer ``in due course,'' but asked
shareholders not to tender their shares to Tyson until the board
made a final recommendation.
   Tyson had earlier told Holly's board that Tyson was willing to
pay $63.50 a share for Holly stock. The latest offer, Tyson said,
was contingent on termination of the Holly-ConAgra deal.
   The Springdale-based poultry giant already has asked a state
court in Delaware _ where Holly Farms is incorporated _ to nullify
the ConAgra-Holly Farms deal or to hold a hearing on the
appropriateness of the proposal.
   Under the proposal, ConAgra would be able to buy certain Holly
Farms assets even if the merger failed.
   Don Tyson, chairman and chief executive officer, also released a
letter he sent to the Holly Farms board concerning the $63.50 offer
to Holly Farms shareholders.
   ``Obviously this increase should eliminate your continued and
erroneous assertions that Tyson was not, and is not committed to
acquiring all outstanding Holly common shares at $63.50 per share,''
Tyson said. ``Moreover, this represents deliverable real value to
your stockholders if _ instead of thwarting a decision on the
lock-ups by the Delaware Chancery Court by favoring a ConAgra
transaction _ you would join with us in expeditiously seeking the
court's determination.''
   Tyson said its tender offer for Holly common shares has been
extended until March 31. The release said that, as of the close of
business Wednesday, Tyson had received tenders of approximately 1.3
million common shares of Holly Farms.
   The target company has about 17.44 million shares outstanding,
making the total value of Tyson's latest offer worth $1.11 billion.
</TEXT>
