<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Fruit-Cyanide 2ndLd-Writethru   03-16 0951</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fruit-Cyanide, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0980</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chilean Official Confident Solution Coming on Problems of Fruit Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 2, We are, to CORRECT minister's name to include surname.
Inserts grafs 6-8, A joint statement, with statement. Cuts last 5 grafs
pvs to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chilean foreign minister said today after
meeting with Secretary of State James A. Baker III that he is
confident a solution can be found to the problems arising after a
U.S. government warning that citizens should not eat Chilean fruit.
   ``We are confident that with a joint effort we can have a
solution,'' the foreign minister, Hernan Felipe Errazuriz told
reporters. He described his meeting with Baker as ``very
constructive'' and said, ``We need an urgent solution today.''
   Baker, responding to Chilean anger over the U.S. government
warning, said the action was not taken on political grounds.
   ``It has been taken strictly as a health and safety measure and
we think the foreign minister understands that,'' Baker said.
   He added that Chilean officials and those from the Food and Drug
Administration were discussing possible solutions, but did not
describe what options were under consideration.
   A joint statement issued after the State Department meeting said
the two sides agreed to work together on an urgent basis to resolve
the problem.
   The Chilean side expressed deep concern over the country's heavy
financial losses, noting that 200,000 workers and their families
``face unemployment and even destitution,'' the statement said.
   Baker responded that U.S. industry and consumers were being
harmed as a consequence of ``the despicable act'' of those
responsible for poisoning the fruit.
   An FDA spokesman said the agency weighed economic as well as
health concerns when it decided to warn the public about the
possible poisoning of Chilean fruit, an agency spokesman said.
   Such a decision ``has great economic potential'' to harm the
South American country that exported $581 million in fruit worldwide
last year and hopes to export $850 million worth next year, said
spokesman Don McLearn.
   On the other hand, ``you had a probable confirmation'' that
cyanide found in two red seedless grapes from Chile ``was a
tampering, not a hoax.''
   ``Then, how far do you go with a decision based on that evidence?
That's very tough,'' he said.
   FDA Commissioner Frank Young's decision was to warn consumers not
to eat any Chilean fruit _ which includes virtually all fresh grapes
sold in U.S. markets at this time of year _ and to urge stores to
remove all Chilean fruit from their shelves.
   Supermarkets reacted quickly, and today produce shelves remain
empty of Chilean fruit. Many stores have posted signs assuring
customers that the fruit on display didn't come from Chile.
   At ports in Philadelphia, Los Angeles and Miami, tons of Chilean
grapes, pears, raspberries, watermelons and other non-citrus fruit
were being held under refrigeration while tests on the produce
continued.
   No further contamination has been found, the FDA said.
   Meanwhile, U.S. officials have been meeting through the week with
representatives of the Chilean government and U.S. fruit importers
to develop a plan that would ``do the least economic damage (to
Chile) and assure the safety of the fruit supply,'' McLearn said.
   The FDA's warning to consumers appeared to come some 24 hours
after FDA inspectors discovered two suspicious-looking red grapes
that tests later confirmed to contain traces of cyanide, according
to a chronology outlined by McLearn.
   The chain of events began March 2 when the U.S. embassy in
Santiago received a call from a Spanish-speaking male who threatened
to inject cyanide into Chile's export fruit.
   A government source, speaking on the condition of anonymity, has
said the caller indicated in his threat that his motive was ``to
focus attention on the lower classes of Chile.''
   The message was passed to the U.S. Customs Service, which began
detaining ships with Chilean fruit at U.S. ports.
   The FDA learned of the threat late in the afternoon on Friday,
March 3, McLearn said. The following day, Young called in a group of
FDA officials to talk about the situation, said McLearn, who
attended the meeting that lasted into the evening.
   Young decided the detention by the Customs Service should
continue through the weekend, while he talked to officials at the
State Department and Customs, the Chilean ambassador and fruit
importers ``to try to figure out the magnitude of this and grapple
with the decision of what to do,'' McLearn said.
   But by the end of the weekend, the State Department had concluded
the threat was a hoax, he said.
   ``We felt at that point there was no reason for a full detention
but that we would do surveillance,'' McLearn said. ``At that point
we were prepared to let the fruit through,'' and issued a release
about the hoax.
   A story about the determination that the call had been a hoax
appeared in a Santiago newspaper, and on March 8, the caller _ ``we
assume it was the same guy,'' the FDA spokesman said _ phoned the
embassy again and said the threat was not a hoax.
   The FDA heightened its inspections at the U.S. ports, the
spokesman said.
   Most of the fruit enters through the port at Philadelphia, and
there the Almeria Star had just arrived with the next major import
from Chile, he said. It was on that ship that inspectors, making a
visual inspection last Sunday, found two discolored grapes that had
crystalline rings around puncture marks.
   The grapes were sent to an FDA laboratory in Philadelphia, which
made an initial finding that the grapes contained cyanide. They then
were sent to another FDA lab in Cincinnati, which confirmed traces
of the poison in the grapes, McLearn said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
