<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-NewspaperAds     03-16 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Newspaper Ads,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ad Spending in Newspapers Rose 6.1 Percent in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spending for newspaper advertising rose 6.1
percent to an estimated $31.2 billion in 1988, the smallest
percentage gain in 13 years, an industry-backed research
organization said Thursday.
   The increase was down from a 9.0 percent rise in 1987 and was the
smallest advance since a 5.0 percent rise in the recession year of
1975.
   The Newspaper Advertising Bureau Inc. said preliminary estimates
indicate spending for retail advertising, the largest category for
newspapers, rose 4.0 percent to $15.84 billion last year.
   Classified ad spending rose 10.1 percent to $11.77 billion and
national ad spending was up 2.6 percent to $3.59 billion.
   Media analysts have blamed the sluggish growth in retail ad
spending partly on recent consolidation in the retailing business.
   They said retailers also were reluctant to boost ad spending in
the wake of the October 1987 stock market crash because of
uncertainty earlier in the year about how the crash would affect
consumer spending patterns.
   Retail ad spending grew only 1.7 percent in the second quarter of
1988, for instance, but picked up in the last half of the year,
rising 4.4 percent in the third quarter and 5.2 percent for the
fourth quarter.
   Overall ad spending in newspapers was up 6.6 percent in the
fourth quarter.
</TEXT>
