<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed in
light, quiet trading Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders said tenders that may have gone unbought were responsible
for early downside moves by both the grains and beans, and may have
set the tone in the absence of any fresh news the rest of the day.
   Pakistan apparently canceled overnight on a 99,000-ton purchase
of soy oil, and that spread pressure across the bean market. But
expectations the Pakistanis might return to the market and light
cash sales of beans around the country provide some underpinning
through the rest of the day.
   Traders expected wheat to move upward after a one-day tour of the
Kansas fields concluded recent dry weather had harmed the winter
wheat crop. But dampening any upside move was a rumor that China
will cancel a 270,000-ton buy of new-crop wheat.
   On the close, wheat was \ cent lower to 1{ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.37 a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to } cents higher, with March at $2.78 a bushel; oats were \
to 1} cents higher, with March at $2.08{ a bushel; and soybeans were
1 cent lower to 1{ cents higher, with March at $7.67{ a bushel.
