<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     03-16 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $1.26 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 460 money market mutual
funds rose $1.26 billion in the latest week to a new all-time high
of $296.55 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise n the seven-day period ended Wednesday, followed a $1.25
billion increase in the funds' assets the previous week, according
to the Washington-based mutual fund trade group.
   It was the tenth straight weekly all-time high for money market
mutual fund assets reported by the trade group.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 228 general purpose funds rose $913 million to $96.11
billion, assets of 94 broker-dealer funds increased $565 million to
$127.96 billion, and assets of 138 institutional funds decreased
$213.6 million to $72.47 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.85 percent from 8.75 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 8.68 percent from 8.58 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 32
days, up from 31 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts rose to 6.50 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.48 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, rose to 5.15 percent from 5.14 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.96
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.86 the
previous week. Yields were 9.13 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 9.03
percent; 9.10 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 9.04 percent; and 9.09
percent on 5-year CDs, up from 9.04 percent.
</TEXT>
