<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 2146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-NationalSemiconductor     03-16 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-National Semiconductor,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Semiconductor Loses $81 Million In Third Quarter From Cont.
Ops.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Semiconductor Corp., which
has shed one division, agreed to sell another and laid off 2,000
workers to stem losses, announced Thursday it lost $81 million from
continuing operations in its most recent quarter.
   Charles E. Sporck, president and chief executive officer, said
the company's chip business was hurt by a decline in bookings in
late 1988 caused by a buildup of customers' inventory, a slowdown in
computer sales and seasonal factors.
   He said he expects improvement in the current quarter following a
restructuring of the chip division, cutbacks in the worldwide
workforce and reduced spending.
   The chipmaker's losses for the first nine months of its fiscal
year through February 26 reached $116.8 million from continuing
operations, compared with a $34.6 million gain during the same
period a year earlier. In the third quarter last year, the company
had a gain of $13.4 million from continuing operations.
   Net losses of $44.6 million in the quarter and $100.3 million in
the nine-month period were cushioned by a $45.1 million gain from
the sale of National's Datachecker Systems Inc. That division,
though, lost $8.8 million in the quarter and $28.6 million in the
first three quarters.
   Net sales were $589 million for the quarter, up from $572 million
a year earlier. For the first nine months this year, sales were $1.8
billion, up from $1.6 billion a year earlier.
   ``The size of the loss doesn't shock me, but it was larger than I
anticipated,'' said Jim Hammons, a computer industry analyst with
the Sierra Group in Tempe, Ariz. ``I don't know that it's going to
hurt them any more on Wall Street. Nobody expected them to do very
well this quarter.''
   National Semiconductor's chances of recovering much in the fourth
quarter are slim, Hammons said, and would depend on how well they
market products and use the cash from their recent sales of
divisions.
   ``They have some new products coming out that could help them,
but I don't think they'll be ready to help in this quarter,'' he
said.
   On Feb. 27, National Semiconductor announced it had agreed to
sell its National Advanced Systems for $398 million to Hitachi Ltd.
of Japan and Electronic Data Systems, a unit of General Motors Corp.
National Semiconductor expects to close the sale during the current
quarter.
   National Advanced Systems is Hitachi's largest distributor of
mainframe computers that run the same programs as International
Business Machines Corp.'s big mainframes. It has 2,200 employees
worldwide, including 1,200 in the United States.
   After that sale, National Semiconductor would be pared down to
about 35,000 worldwide. The company announced 2,000 layoffs earlier
this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
