<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-16 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed in domestic dealings
Thursday after rising in Europe despite central bank intervention.
   Gold prices declined. Republic National Bank of New York said
gold was bid at $388.75 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from
Wednesday's late bid of $391.10.
   Traders agreed much of the activity centered around the Japanese
yen. Before easing, the dollar had reached a high in U.S. trading of
about 131.30 yen, a level not seen since last October. But traders
said the move reflected more weakness in the yen than strength in
the dollar.
   ``It was sort of a new level, but what happened was that there
was selling of the yen, more so than a buying of dollars,'' said
Frank Watson, a vice president at the New York branch of Swiss Bank
Corp.
   The dollar put in a more positive performance earlier in Europe,
where the currency closed higher across the boards despite
intervention to temper its rise.
   Dealers said the European central banks stepped in and had some
success in forcing the dollar lower for awhile, but without added
intervention by the Federal Reserve, the currency gained on the day.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to close at 130.73 Japanese yen, from
129.88 yen. Later in London, the dollar traded higher at 130.85. In
New York, the dollar rose to 130.86 yen, from 130.60 yen on
Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7210 late Thursday, cheaper
for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.7235. In New York, one pound
cost $1.7189, cheaper than $1.7200 late Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8689 West German marks, down from
1.8723; 1.6083 Swiss francs, up from 1.6080; 6.3275 French francs,
down from 6.3355; 1,371.75 Italian lire, down from 1,373.50, and
1.1953 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1964.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday's late
rates, included: 1.8710 West German marks, up from 1.8670; 1.6075
Swiss francs, up from 1.6038; 6.3235 French francs, up from 6.3200;
2.1085 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1065; 1,371.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,369.37, and 1.1965 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1935.
   Gold prices fell. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery closed at $389.80 a troy ounce, down
from $392.10 on Wednesday.
   The decline overseas was more pronounced. In London, gold traded
at a late bid of $388.25 a troy ounce, down from $392.25. The late
bid price in Zurich was $388.60 an ounce, down from $393.25. Earlier
in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $391.70, down from $395.37.
   Silver prices also weakened. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $6.059 a troy ounce, down from
$6.091 Wednesday. In London, the metal traded at a late bid of $6.04
a troy ounce, down from $6.12.
