<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 1722EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Fares Bjt   03-16 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Fares, Bjt,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern's Rivals Raising Fares on Competitive Routes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some rivals of strike-torn Eastern Airlines have
raised fares on competitive routes since the 13-day-old walkout
began, moves they say stem from higher demand but that one consumer
group complains is price gouging.
   Some competitors said Thursday that their recent fare hikes were
unrelated to the Eastern strike, which has grounded most of the
airline's flights.
   The walkout by Machinists has been supported by most of the
pilots and flight attendants at Eastern, which sought bankruptcy
protection from its creditors about a week ago.
   All the airlines are heading into the peak spring travel period
combining Spring Break and the Easter and Passover holidays.
   Eastern archrival Delta Air Lines says it hasn't raised fares but
has tightened fare restrictions as a result of the Eastern debacle.
   On flights from cities in the Northeast to Florida, where it
competes with Eastern, Delta has boosted its cancellation penalty on
discount fares to 100 percent from 25 percent. Delta took the action
because the Eastern strike had led many passengers to book on
multiple carriers including Delta _ creating ``no shows'' for those
airlines, said Delta spokeswoman Jackie Pate.
   In addition, she said, Delta has reduced the number of cut-rate
fares available on certain flights ``to protect business
travelers.'' The spillover from the Eastern walkout meant that
discount-fare passengers were displacing full-fare business fliers
on Delta flights, Ms. Pate said.
   Other Eastern competitors _ notably Trans World Airlines Inc. and
USAir Group Inc. _ confirmed they recently raised fares on some
routes they share with Eastern.
   Those moves were called ``opportunistic'' and ``gouging'' by Dan
Smith, consumer affairs director of the International Airline
Passengers Association in Dallas.
   Smith said he was skeptical about the insistence by TWA and USAir
that their fare boosts were unrelated to the strike and were not an
attempt to capitalize on Eastern's woes.
   ``You would hope they would be more sensitive during these
unusual circumstances,'' Smith said.
   The possible disappearance of Eastern from the skies likely would
reduce the number of discounted fares available to passengers, he
said.
   Spokesmen for United Airlines, American Airlines and Pan Am
Corp., which also compete with Eastern on some routes, said those
carriers had not raised fares since the Eastern walkout started
March 4.
   TWA plans to increase its discount fares between New York and San
Juan, Puerto Rico, starting March 23 in order to bring them closer
to TWA's Florida fares, which are sharply higher, said TWA spokesman
Bob Blattner in St. Louis, Mo.
   He called the timing of the move a ``coincidence.''
   The round-trip discount fares between New York and San Juan will
be raised from $239-$259 to $259-$289. TWA's discount New York-Miami
fares, which haven't been increased, range from $258 to $298.
   USAir spokesman David Shipley said that carrier ``has not raised
any fares as a result of the Eastern strike.''
   Rather, he said, USAir's recent increases were an extension of a
move begun last November. The latest hikes include a rise in the
regular one-way fare between Boston and Tampa, Fla., to $329 from
$319, also effective March 23.
   The Boston-Tampa route competes directly with Eastern. Shipley
declined to give examples of other new fare increases applied to
non-competing routes.
   ``These people are businessmen and they've seen an opportunity to
raise fares,'' said Andrew Geller, an airline analyst at Provident
National Bank in Philadelphia.
   Some members of Congress and others have argued that a demise of
Eastern could seriously reduce competition in the nation's airline
industry, whose ranks have been thinned by deregulation. They have
warned the reduced competition could lead to higher fares, defeating
the intended main purpose of deregulation _ to make it affordable
for more Americans to fly.
</TEXT>
