<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Futures Rise Slightly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil-Trend Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures rose slightly in active trading
Thursday after rallying sharply a day earlier.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the April contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 7 cents
to close at $19.84 a barrel.
   On Wednesday the contract soared to the highest level in nearly
17 months, closing at $19.77. The last time the near-month contract
was higher was on Oct. 30, 1987, when the near-term contract settled
at $19.96 a barrel.
   Among refined oil products traded on the exchange, the April
contract for unleaded gasoline edged up 0.03 cent to finish at 55.83
cents a gallon. The heating oil contract for delivery in April
declined 0.36 cent to 53.83 cents.
   Analysts said the market was in a retrenchment phase after
Wednesday's gains.
   ``The market was stuck today. It consolidated after yesterday's
sharp gains,'' said Andrew Lebow, an analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man
International Futures Inc.
   Peter Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc., said trading volume was ``good.''
