<FIRST>r f AM-Fruit-Importers     03-16 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fruit-Importers,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fruit Fallout: Poisoning Menaces $900 Million Import Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile-Fruit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The poisoning of grapes from Chile poses a
high-profile threat to a business that has grown to $900 million a
year by using Southern Hemisphere farmers to put fruit on American
tables all winter.
   American importers and Chilean farmers worry that if the cyanide
sabotage case isn't solved soon, they could lose the market for the
25 percent of their crop still on trees or aboard U.S.-bound ships.
   The tampering, which prompted the Food and Drug Administration to
recommend pulling grapes, nectarines, pears and other Chilean winter
fruit from market shelves, also might give the business a permanent
public relations black eye, one big importer said.
   ``I think it's a major, major, overreaction...an entire industry
is being destroyed,'' Los Angeles importer Rick Eastes said Tuesday.
   Eastes, manager for the David Oppenheimer-California import firm
munched a couple of red flame seedless grapes from Chile for
reporters Tuesday to underscore his anger over the FDA's no-sell
recommendation.
   The FDA advised grocers to pull Chilean fruit from the shelves
Tuesday after tests in Philadelphia found cyanide _ at far below
harmful levels _ had apparently been put in two clusters of grapes.
   Virtually all the so-called summer fruit on American grocery
shelves this time of year is from Chile, whose farmers have learned
to exploit the Southern Hemisphere growing season that is a mirror
image of that in the north.
   From a trickle of grape imports in the 1950's, the business has
grown to projected shipments this year with a retail value of $900
million, said Caryl Saunders, a San Francisco spokeswoman for the
industry.
   In 1979, when imports were starting to gain momentum, the retail
value of Chilean grapes and stone fruit was $72 million, said Ms.
Saunders. By 1988, that had climbed to $600 million.
   More than 100 ships full of Chilean fruit are expected to land
this year, to be distributed nationwide from the ports of
Philadelphia; Long Beach, Calif., and Tampa and Cape Canaveral in
Florida.
   The business is organized by the growers, under the banner of the
Chilean Winter Fruit Association, and the importers, called the
American Produce Association.
   That loose alliance carefully orchestrates the traffic to avoid
ruffling the feathers of American farmers.:
   Grapes, which make up three-quarters of the shipments, are
carefully withheld until the last California emperor grapes clear
the supermarkets, usually sometime in December. Grape shipments are
cut off _ earlier than would be decreed by nature _ in late April
when the first California grapes make their way to market.
   There is little overlap in growing season for nectarines and
other fruit, so there is less potential for conflict with American
growers, Ms. Saunders said.
   Importers and growers are anxious for the FDA to declare the
fruit safe, because products already on U.S. shores is will
deteriorate beyond salvation in a week or two, Ms. Saunders said.
Additionally, an estimated 25 percent of the crop remains on the
trees and vines of Chile's farms, or on ships headed north.
   Importer Eastes called the FDA's advice to quit selling Chilean
fruit unnecessary and maintained that testing here and new security
measures imposed at packing houses in Chile adequately protect
American consumers. He suggested the agency was trying to burnish an
image tarnished in the public mind by the current furor over Alar, a
possibly carcinogenic chemical sprayed on a fraction of the U.S.
apple crop.
   Fruits imported from Chile include grapes, nectarines, peaches,
plums, apricots, pears, Granny Smith apples, cherries, raspberries,
blueberries, cantaloupe and honeydew melons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890316-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-89 0018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;Ls-Hawaii     03-16 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Hawaii,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Trade Association's Convention in Hawaii is Canceled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A savings and loan trade association on
Wednesday canceled its annual convention in Hawaii this year, thus
avoiding television images of S&amp;L executives lolling on palm-fringed
beaches at a time when the industry is asking for the biggest
taxpayer bailout in U.S. history.
   ``It would not be appropriate for us to hold a convention in
Hawaii at a time when Congress and the administration are working to
find a solution to this terrible crisis facing taxpayers,'' Bud
Koch, chairman of the National Council of Savings Institutions, said
in a statement.
   The council, the smaller of two main trade groups representing
S&amp;Ls, is taking a lesson from its larger rival, the U.S. League of
Savings Institutions.
   The league held its convention in November at a luxury hotel on
Waikiki Beach in Honolulu. It said it went ahead with the meeting
because it had been planned years in advance and would have been
costly to cancel at the last minute. Nevertheless, the group endured
criticism after television news reports showed executives on the
beach and attending a lavish luau.
   The council said would it would suffer ``substantial financial
costs'' by canceling its meeting, which had been scheduled for May
on the island of Kauai, but Koch said, ``Thrifts who are members of
the national council ... have concluded that it would be wrong to
conduct business as usual.''
   President Bush's plan for bailing out the savings and loan
deposit insurance fund would spend about $150 billion over the next
10 years. Most analysts say at least half of that would come from
taxpayers. That exceeds the combined costs of the Marshall Plan aid
to Europe after World War II and the bailouts of the Chrysler Corp.,
New York City and Lockheed Corp.
   Koch said the council may schedule a special meeting in
Washington in May to elect officers and take care of other business
normally conducted at the annual convention.
   In another development, one of three members of the Federal Home
Loan Bank Board, the agency regulating S&amp;Ls, announced his
resignation effective Aug. 18. Lawrence White, appointed to the
board on Nov. 12, 1986, is returning to teach at New York
University's school of business.
   Under the president's proposed S&amp;L plan, the bank board would be
reduced to a single chairman, who would report to the treasury
secretary.
</TEXT>
