<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-16 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar Futures Soar on Chinese Buy-Swap Rumor, Technical Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar futures prices surged to their highest levels in nine
months Thursday amid rumors that China had come into possession of
as much as 500,000 tons of sugar.
   ``What you saw was a market catching fire,'' said Arthur
Stevenson, analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., New York.
``And the real excitement is the possible growing participation in
the markets of China _ the world's most populous nation.''
   On other markets, energy futures were mixed to marginally higher
after three straight sessions of strong rallies; gold and silver
futures dipped, but platinum rose; and livestock and pork futures
edged lower.
   Sugar settled 10 cents to 51 cents higher on the New York Coffee,
Sugar and Cocoa Exchange, with the contract for delivery in May at
12.59 cents a pound.
   Buying began with a rumor that the Chinese had bought between
150,000 and 500,000 tons of raw sugar from Thailand, though many
traders cast doubts that the shipment exceeded 350,000 tons.
   Many others traders said they believed the Chinese actually
bought the sugar last fall from Cuba and, learning the Soviets had
made a similar-sized purchase from Thailand, simply swapped
shipments to take advantage of economies in delivery of the sugar.
   Also fueling the market was talk the Brazilians had sold 100,000
tons and that Argentina was in the market for a large shipment.
   The climbing prices triggered a string of technical buy-stops _
decisions made by price-chart considerations _ and the market broke
a ``quadruple top'' at 12.38 cents and continued rising.
   Energy futures, which hit a 16-month high Monday and soared again
in successive sessions, were mixed. Crude oil highlighted the
complex, losing 5 cents at the opening on profit-taking, and
recovering gradually in light trading.
   Crude oil settled 2 cents lower to 9 cents higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, with April at $19.84 a barrel; heating oil was
.02 cent to .36 cent lower, with April at 53.83 cents a gallon; and
unleaded gasoline was .50 cent lower to .12 cent higher, with April
at 55.83 cents a gallon.
   Reports of cuts by OPEC and non-OPEC producers, as well as
problems with production facilities in Norway and Qatar had fueled
previous rallies.
   Gold and silver continued sliding in the face of a firm dollar
and uncertainty about whether higher inflation is in the offing.
   Platinum got a boost from apparent trade-house buying prompted
either by ideas the market was oversold or by recent sales by the
Japanese.
   Gold settled $2.30 to $2.90 lower at the New York Commodity
Exchange, with March at $389.80 a troy ounce; silver slipped 3.2
cents to 4.7 cents, with March at $6.059 a troy ounce. Platinum was
$7.20 to $7.70 higher, with April at $545.50 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and pork futures mostly were lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange. Volume was light as traders, many expecting a
bearish tone, remained on the sideline in advance of the USDA's
cattle-on-feedlot report issued after the close.
   Live cattle were .37 cent lower to .02 cent higher, with April at
77.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent to .35 cent higher,
with March at 80.60 cents a pound; live hogs were .50 cent lower to
.10 cent higher, with April at 43.17 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .05 cent to 1 cent lower; with March at 37.15 cents a
pound.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed in light, quiet
trading Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat settled \ cent lower to 1{ cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in March at $4.37 a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to }
cents higher, with March at $2.78 a bushel; oats were \ to 1} cents
higher, with March at $2.08{ a bushel; and soybeans were 1 cent
lower to 1{ cents higher, with March at $7.67{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
