<FIRST>u f AM-Fruit-Cyanide 1stLd-Writethru f0274 03-16 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fruit-Cyanide, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0274,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chilean Officials Call for Swift End To Fruit Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new 2nd graf with meetings today; INSERTS 5 grafs after
6th pvs, `The FDA' to add detail on talks with industry on level of inspections
being proposed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-level Chilean delegation called Thursday
for ``swift action'' to avoid further economic and social turmoil in
Chile resulting from the suspension on U.S. sales of Chilean fruit
over an apparent cyanide poisoning attempt.
   Meanwhile, U.S. officials were meeting with representatives of
the Chilean government and its fruit growers, trying to find a way
to release for sale the tons of Chilean fruit detained at American
docks without compromising public safety.
   The Chilean call was disclosed in a joint communique issued after
Secretary of State James A. Baker III met with the Chilean foreign
affairs and agriculture ministers.
   As Chilean fruit continued to pile up at airports and docks and
the livelihoods of hundreds of thousands of Chileans were
threatened, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration said a small team
of FDA inspectors will be sent to Chile on Saturday to check
security on Chilean fruit.
   The State Department meeting came four days after the FDA warned
Americans to avoid Chilean fruit because traces of cynadide were
found in Chilean fruit shipped to Philadelphia.
   There was no sign of an imminent end to the crisis despite the
high-level attention it was receiving.
   The FDA said technical meetings were continuing to determine what
levels of inspections might be feasible for fruit at American docks.
   A government source who spoke on the condition of anonymity said
there had been discussion of inspections of 8 percent to 10 percent
of the fruit on the docks now and in the future, and release the
produce if no contamination is found. However, ``it doesn't appear
to be feasible to do that high a level now.''
   For the future, Chilean officials are proposing to inspect
visually about 4 percent to 5 percent of their fruit before it is
shipped for export, the source said.
   ``We're getting reasonably close on that (Chile's) end of things
on something that might be acceptable, but the problem of what to do
with what's on the ships and in warehouses is still up in the air,''
the source said.
   The fruit that's been removed from store shelves ``is such a
different problem they may just end up with no solution to that
except to dump it,'' the source said.
   The Washington Post reported that the Chilean Exporters
Association estimates about $20 million worth of fruit is detained,
under refrigeration, at docks and airports in the United States,
about $4 million worth is to arrive in the next few days by ship,
and $15 million worth is ready to be shipped from Chile.
   Inspectors at ports in Philadelphia, Los Angeles and Miami have
examined 6,859 cases of grapes and nearly nearly 4,000 cases of
other fruits: honeydew melons, nectarines, apples, raspberries,
pears, cantalopes, plums, peaches, seedless watermelon, Juan Canary
Melons and blackberries.
   The joint communique issued at the State Department stressed the
determination of both sides to reach a solution.
   Chilean Foreign Minister Hernan Felipe Errazuriz told reporters
after the meeting that he is confident a solution will be found and
described the encounter as ``very constructive.''
   Baker, responding to Chilean anger over a U.S. government warning
that citizens not eat Chilean fruit, said the action was taken
strictly as a health and safety measure.
   ``We think the foreign minister understands that,'' he said.
   In Miami, Robert Aders, the president of the Food Marketing
Institute, said the entire food industry will be hurt by the
discovery of cyanide in Chilean produce and cancer-causing chemicals
in apples.
   ``The loss will probably be felt throughout the system,'' he said.
   Chilean produce continues to arrive in the United States, and
Aders noted one shipment reached Miami Wednesday night.
   ``The indication is they're not going to let it be sold,'' he
said.
   Aders predicted surveillance of imported fruit will increase,
saying, ``I expect that there'll be a lot more activity at the dock,
including vigilance at the point of shipment.''
   But security will continue to be a problem. ``The whole food
system is based on the integrity of the people in it,'' he said.
``Suddenly it's an attractive place for criminals to go to express a
grievance.''
</TEXT>
