<FIRST>u f AM-SundstrandIndictments 1stLd-Writethru f0317 03-16 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sundstrand Indictments, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0317,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Ex-Employees Indicted in Fraud Scheme</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT spelling of ``waver.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former Sundstrand Corp. executives were
charged Thursday with conspiring to defraud the federal government,
five months after the defense contractor agreed to plead guilty to
fraud and pay a $115 million fine.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas said the indictments ``demonstrate
that the federal government will not waver from employing the
resources necessary to protect the integrity of the defense
procurement process.''
   The indictments are part of an ongoing three-year investigation
of the Rockford-based defense contractor.
   Sundstrand pleaded guilty in October to fraud charges in a
four-count criminal information. The $115 million fine was the
largest fraud settlement in Defense Department history.
   The aerospace manufacturer allegedly overbilled the government
for aircraft parts; underbid actual costs on other contracts and
attempted to recover through overhead accounts set up for other
purposes; and submitted claims for such things as babysitting
expenses and country club memberships.
   Sundstrand spokesman Claude Vernam said the company was not
involved in Thursday's indictments. He declined further comment.
   The three men were identified as Joseph McCarthy, 53, of
Rockford, a former division controller; Ray John Chapel Jr., 46, of
Reston, Va., a former division pricing manager; and Ralph Hamann,
63, of Rockford, a former pricing group supervisor.
   They were charged with one count each of conspiring to defraud
and scheming to conceal. McCarthy was charged with two counts of
making false statements, and Chapel and Hamann with four counts of
the same offense.
   McCarthy faces a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and $1
million in fines; Chapel and Hamann face 30-year terms and $1.5
million in fines if convicted.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney William Clabault did not say what role
the three allegedly played in the fraud scheme involving Sundstrand.
He declined to say whether the men acted on company orders or have
agreed to cooperate.
   After the settlement was approved last fall, Sundstrand was
suspended from bidding on or receiving government contracts until a
grand jury concluded its probe.
   On Jan. 26, Sundstrand agreed to repay an additional $62.3
million to the Pentagon and make cost-saving concessions on future
contracts one defense official estimated could be worth another $34
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
